<HEADLINE>
MILLER'S ACT ANNOYING TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Until now, the Los Angeles Lakers have left most
of the grousing about officiating and star treatment to their
opponents. But in the wake of a 33-point loss to Indiana on Friday,
the Lakers aimed their ire at the Pacers' Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   He flops. He entangles. He draws fouls on the Lakers. And it
bugs the bejesus out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets away with so much of the flopping and so much of
launching himself, propelling himself into defenders that are just
standing around guarding other people,'' said Rick Fox. ``I don't
know if it's something he's done for so long that it's just
accepted now, and it's just part of his game, you just blow the
whistle whenever you see him flopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got a guy on our team that gets some good calls for
flopping, and he takes charges,'' Fox said, referring to teammate
Derek Fisher. ``With your home floor, they call it the way they do.
He likes that contact, Reggie likes to create the contact because
then it keeps the defender off-balance, it keeps the defender
hunting him out as the prey, and he's allowed to create contact and
flop like a 90-pound bass.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is notorious for extending his limbs as he shoots, trying
to catch a stray arm or leg of the defender. In the fourth quarter
of Friday's Pacers victory, Miller snared Fisher and flopped while
shooting a 3-pointer. The whistle blew, Fisher blew his lid and got
called for a technical foul, and Miller shot (and made) four free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller obviously kicked Fisher on that shot,'' Lakers coach
Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thug treatment: One foul Fox did not dispute was his collaring
of Austin Croshere late in the third quarter, which drew a flagrant
foul call. It turned into a 4-point play that increased Indiana's
lead from 15 points to 19.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson questioned the wisdom of the play, but Fox had no
regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they've had their way all night scoring. At what point
do you give up another layup?'' Fox said. ``Then they go up 17, or
do you try to put a stop to that? At that point, we'd been down 15,
17, 20 points the whole game, and that flagrant foul was not going
to change the course of the game. If anything, it would maybe
change it to another direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive: The Lakers surrendered a postseason-high 120 points
and 57.4 percent shooting to the Pacers, but the NBA's best
defensive team in the regular season still believes in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not worried about that at all,'' Ron Harper said. ``The
only thing we gotta do is come out and have energy and we're all
right. And I guarantee you, that it ain't the same thing out there
(in Game 6) I bet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall return,'' Harper vowed. ``We shall return.''
</P>
<P>
   Home again: Only Portland has beaten the Lakers at Staples
Center in the playoffs. And the Lakers are 3-0 at home against
Indiana this season. But no one is assuming trends will
automatically hold as the series shifts back to L.A. for Game 6
and, if necessary, Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't guarantee them an automatic win,'' Fox noted. ``We
came (to Conseco Fieldhouse) and got one ourselves. We've had
success at home all year, but nothing's guaranteed right now, not
when you give a team a little life support system in Game 5.''
</P>
</TEXT>
