<SLUG> BC-BOX-UNDERCARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER KO VICTORY, MORALES EYES TITLE TRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just before ``Destiny'' - the main event's billing
- hit Staples Center in the form of the Oscar De La Hoya-Shane
Mosley welterweight championship bout, Erik Morales was designing
his own fate during Saturday's undercard.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, of Tijuana, knocked out Mike Juarez, of Omaha, at 1:12
of the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Despite it being the first time Morales (37-0, 29 KOs) moved up
to the featherweight division, it was the third time he introduced
Juarez (22-9-1) to the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference for me was my stamina,'' Morales said.
``This weight is good for me. At 122 pounds I wasn't able to move
and do the things that I wanted to do because I was too weak. I did
feel stronger with my punches and just plain stronger at this
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory will likely set up a title fight between Morales
(37-0, 29 KOs) and WBC featherweight champion Guty Espadas on Sept.
2. It would take place either in San Diego or Morales' native
Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle of bulk vs. height, bulk won.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's Eric ``Butterbean'' Esch, who has turned himself into
a curious national phenomenon, knocked out Kansas City's Kerry
Biles (6-foot-6, 266 pounds) at 2:52 of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Esch (6-0, 333) did not attract his following from slick boxing
skills or good looks.
</P>
<P>
   After dominating Biles (2-2) in the first round, Esch left his
guard down briefly and took a stiff jab from Biles.
</P>
<P>
   Esch left his hands down and invited Biles to deliver a
combination which landed square in Esch's face. All Esch did was
smile and giggle a bit before knocking Biles out with a right
cross.
</P>
<P>
   After a disastrous bout in his first big fight - a loss to Floyd
Mayweather on May 22 - Uganda's Justin Juuko gave Diego Corrales
more of a fight than anticipated. Corrales, of Sacramento, finally
knocked out Juuko at 2:35 of the 10th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a million punches,'' Corrales said. ``It took
everything I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia St. John of Calabasas won a unanimous decision over Linda
Robinson (3-1) of Texas in a women's featherweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   St. John lifted her record to to 18-0 after controlling the
majority of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Shannon Taylor (27-0-1) won a unanimous decision over
Charles Whitaker (17-9) of the Cayman Islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
