<SLUG> BC-BBN--ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Wagner finds sixth inning just as vexing
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ So much for Billy Wagner sitting on the dock of the
bay and clearing his head, free of the pressures of pitching when
the game is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   When Astros manager Larry Dierker had to make a decision
regarding how to get his team through what turned out to be the
most crucial situation of Saturday's game, he gave the ball to the
man to whom he had turned on so many occasions.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the ninth inning, but it was pressure nonetheless, and
the result was about as melodic as a broken record. The Astros blew
a two-run lead after 5{ innings and lost 6-4 to the San Francisco
Giants at Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who one day earlier had been stripped of his closer's
role, entered the game with a 4-3 lead, two out and two runners on
in the sixth inning. He walked each of the four batters he faced
and threw a wild pitch in what became a four-run, game-winning
rally for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time in 252 career appearances Wagner
failed to record an out, and it marked the first time he had walked
more than three batters in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just couldn't find the strike zone,'' Dierker said of
Wagner, who walked only three batters in the entire month of April.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's outing was a snapshot of what a struggling pitcher
goes through. Although Wagner walked a career-high four batters,
wild would not be the best word to describe his outing.
</P>
<P>
   Almost inexplicably, the Giants laid off some hittable pitches
that might have been called strikes under better circumstances for
the struggling lefthander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I made some good pitches,'' Wagner said.
``There are a lot of things going on this year that I've never
experienced. I know I'd love to be a hitter; just don't swing the
bat. The strike zone is as tight as ever. I've heard 50,000
theories on what's wrong with Billy Wagner. Ask the guys in the
other clubhouse; I'm no different than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics don't tell the entire story, but they suggest
something is different from a year ago when Wagner walked only 23
batters in 74 innings. He has walked 18 batters in 47 fewer innings
this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, if Wagner got himself into trouble with walks, he
usually could get out of it with strikeouts. But his strikeouts
have been on the decline even though his velocity and movement are
well above average. Nevertheless, Wagner is on pace to finish with
his lowest strikeout total (69) since 1996, when he had 67
strikeouts in 37 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there's just no explanation,'' Giants manager Dusty
Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as perplexing was why Dierker used Wagner in such a
situation one day after the club decided he needed a break from the
so-called pressure cooker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was pressure,'' Dierker said. ``But it was the middle of
the game, and if he had problems we still had time to come back. We
had time, but we didn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to find an easier situation, but this was a day we
were going to get him in a game. We're going to try to get him in a
game every other day, and we're not always going to be able to
manufacture opportunities where we have a three- or four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not unaccustomed to pressure. He's come through very well
in pressure situations up until this year. You can't protect
players at this level. We're not into development. That's for the
minor leagues, and he's not going to the minor leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants took a 2-0 lead against Astros starter Jose Lima
(1-10) in the first inning on an RBI single by Jeff Kent and a
sacrifice fly by J.T. Snow. But the Astros scored a run in the
second and three in a third-inning rally highlighted by Moises
Alou's two-run double off Giants starter Livan Hernandez (5-6).
Unfortunately for the Astros, they managed only five hits the rest
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances, we just didn't get the big hits,'' Astros
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants reclaimed the lead with four runs in the sixth, and
despite Wagner's struggles, he could have gotten out of the fix
with the one-run lead intact if not for a defensive lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Converted first baseman Daryle Ward, making just his second
start in right field this season, misplayed Bill Mueller's pop foul
that should have been the third out of the inning. Instead, Mueller
got new life and drew a walk to load the bases. Barry Bonds'
bases-loaded walk forced home the tying run, and the Giants scored
the go-ahead run on a wild pitch. A bases-loaded walk plated the
final run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind played a part and I was also looking out for the
(bullpen) mound,'' Ward said. ``When I looked back up, the ball was
behind me. I was trying to protect myself; I didn't want to fall on
that mound. This was my first game playing the outfield in San
Francisco. I'll know what to expect next time.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
