u s BC-BBC-LSU-Stanford-HNS &LR;      06-18 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-LSU-Stanford-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cresse comes through as LSU wins fifth title
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
OMAHA, Neb. _ Maybe they should change the name here to Eaux-maha,
since LSU appears to have taken up residence.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers got a single to left field by catcher Brian Cresse to
score Ryan Theriot from second base in the bottom of the ninth
inning, and LSU slipped past Stanford 6-5 in an exhilarating finish
to win the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The hit turned the infield at Rosenblatt Stadium into an
impromptu Louisiana-flavored party, missing only boudin and gumbo.
Players piled on top of Cresse around the shortstop position.
Weeping relatives wearing Mardi Gras beads surrounded the players.
Fans scooped up dirt to put in bottles to take home.
</P>
<P>
   Cresse's single enabled LSU to win its fifth national
championship before 24,282 on Saturday, with the four previous
titles coming in the 1990s. LSU tied Arizona State for the
second-most national championships behind Southern California's 12.
</P>
<P>
   Cresse said he had always dreamed of a game-winning hit in a
championship contest. In fact, he had a similar dream Friday night
before the title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is going to sound corny,'' he said. ``But before I
went to sleep last night, I dreamed I would hit a home run to win
the game. I'll take a single.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Trey Hodges of Klein Oak, not Cresse, was named the
tournament's Most Valuable Player. He pitched in three games,
winning two, and had an ERA of 1.69 in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges matched Stanford pitcher Justin Wayne _ the fifth overall
pick in the pro draft earlier this month by Montreal _ pitch for
pitch and kept the Tigers in the game. He allowed two hits and no
runs in four innings of relief, earning the win to up his record to
5-2. He had surgery last year and began throwing well toward the
end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm was kind of sore today,'' said Hodges, who was drafted
in the 17th round by the Atlanta Braves. ``But after Jeremy's home
run, all the soreness left me. I really thought we were going to
win the game eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Witten hit a two-run homer that tied the score at 5 in
the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   LSU coach Skip Bertman called it his most satisfying national
championship because the team overcame multiple injuries to go 13-0
in the postseason. He also put to rest rumors that he might retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been going one year at a time since 1997,'' Bertman said.
``I'm going to be back. I promised the recruits I'll be here. But I
only do it for one year at a time. It would have been tempting to
do a Dick Vermeil.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama started in the eighth inning when Blair Barbier hit a
solo homer to draw LSU to within 5-3. Three batters later, Witten's
blast tied it.
</P>
<P>
   The big blow for Stanford had been a fourth-inning grand slam by
Craig Thompson off of LSU starter Brian Tallet to give the Cardinal
a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Hodges put Stanford down in order in the top of the ninth,
Theriot singled to start the winning rally. Mike Fontenot followed
with a walk to set up Cresse's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Cresse, who led the nation with 30 homers, had struggled in the
CWS with only one other hit in the Series. He said Bertman told him
even though there were no outs, he did not consider having Cresse
bunt the two runners into scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has trusted me all year long, and trusted me that I
would get the hit,'' Cresse said. ``When I hit the ball, I knew it
was in the outfield. I saw them waving him in and then I knew he
was going to score.''
</P>
<P>
   It was defense early in the game that kept the Tigers within
striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, LSU right fielder Ray Wright made a leaping
catch against the wall on what would have been a solo homer by
Stanford's Edmund Muth. In the sixth, LSU Barbier made a diving
stop behind third base on a grounder hit by Chris O'Riordan with
the bases loaded. Barbier made the cross-diamond throw to nip
O'Riordan at first for the inning-ending out to save at least one
more run.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford coach Mark Marquess said it was a great game, but a
tough one to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a call or a bad bounce that beat us, '' he said.
``They beat us. We didn't give it to them. The catch (by Wright)
and the two home runs came in big spots. They deserve it, they did
a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
