<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-OPEN-HNS &LR;      06-18 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Awed field gives Woods a perfect 10
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Tiger Woods is so far ahead in the U.S. Open
that he could let Jean Van de Velde pinch hit for him today and
still win.
</P>
<P>
   Woods survived his version of Van de Velde's British Open horror
show, shrugging off a triple bogey on No. 3 Saturday, then knuckled
down to shoot an even-par 71 in the third round and take an
astounding 10-stroke lead into the final round today.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is at 8-under-par 205 and his advantage is the biggest
54-hole spread in Open history, toppling the seven-shot lead Jim
Barnes had in 1921. There is nobody at Pebble Beach who isn't
impressed with what he is doing as he embarrasses the rest of the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Tiger is doing is incredible,'' Fred Couples said. ``I
don't see anyone catching him. We all know he's very good and this
proves it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's lapping the field on a very, very hard course, and
there's not any question by far who is the best player. If it (the
wind) blows Sunday, he can shoot 80 and still win.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't shoot 80. In fact, Woods seems on track to do
exactly what he did at the 1997 Masters when he was nine strokes
ahead after three rounds and cruised to a 12-shot victory for his
first major championship. Today, he will earn major No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   His lead is so outrageous, even Woods has never dreamed of
having it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a lead like this, even in fantasy golf,'' he
said. ``I've dreamed of winning the U.S. Open, but it's usually
against Jack (Nicklaus) or Arnie (Palmer) or (Ben) Hogan, and we're
always neck-and-neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is so far ahead that he likely has eliminated any fear of
coughing up the lead. He's three years wiser than he was at Augusta
in '97. And he didn't falter then, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Augusta, I had a nine-shot lead after three rounds,'' Woods
said. ``Now, I'm ahead by 10 shots. It's the same thing _ just go
out there and play one shot at a time. I did that in '97, stayed in
the present and I'm going to try to do the same thing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let your intensity deplete. If you give your
opponent some hope, they could turn the tide and get close to you,
if not past you.''
</P>
<P>
   Not likely. In fact, most everybody is talking like the only
tournament left is the one for second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I wasn't too impressed the first two
days, because he does it all the time,'' Rocco Mediate said. ``But
what he's doing today is just scary after making triple on one
hole. It's amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely mortal. We all are. He is not. Once in a while,
we can beat him. But nobody's going to catch him this week.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday when the scoring average was 77.124, Woods' 71
tied him for the second-lowest round of the day. Only Ernie Els,
who shot a remarkable 3-under 68, broke par.
</P>
<P>
   Els moved from a tie for 36th to second with his round and will
be paired with Woods today in the final 18-hole coronation.
</P>
<P>
   Els is talking a good game. But he seems to already know that it
will be mission impossible for him to track down Woods. He also
said it should make for great theater today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for golf,'' Els said. ``In the '60s, you had Palmer.
In the '70s you had Nicklaus. Then you had (Tom) Watson. Now it
seems like we've got a dominant figure in Tiger. He's probably the
most recognizable sportsman on the planet right now. It's good for
golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it would be even better for golf if someone could step up
and play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods showed his mettle Saturday by surviving the triple bogey
on No. 3. He hit his 7-iron approach shot on the 390-yard par-4
into the thick rough, and it took him five shots to negotiate the
remaining 20 yards to the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad swing on three that cost me three shots, but I
fought back,'' he said. ``That's what you need to do in the U.S.
Open. You're not going to hit every shot good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one bad break at three, but other than that, I played
well. If you put the ball in that rough, it's going to get you.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods added that he's a little surprised that he's 8 under par
and nobody else is better than 2 over through 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprises me that I was able to do it (get a 10-shot lead)
in a U.S. Open. because in an Open it's very difficult to go low,''
he said. ``I made my share of mistakes. But I've made a few putts
this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who started the round with a six-shot lead over Miguel
Angel Jimenez, never saw it go lower than five, which is what it
was after the triple bogey.
</P>
<P>
   But he turned things around at the par-5 sixth hole. His second
shot came to rest on the edge of a bunker 65 yards from the hole.
He had an awkward stance, with one foot in the sand and one on the
lip of the bunker. His ball was in hay-length grass, but with a
reasonable lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to hit a shot up there on the green or short of
the green and get my par and move on,'' Woods said. ``But the ball
rolled up to the hole and I had about 10 feet left, and Stevie
(Williams, his caddie) said it was an important putt and I hit that
thing right in the middle of the cup.''
</P>
<P>
   He also birdied the par-3 seventh from 10 feet to get back to 8
under, then mingled two bogeys with two birdies the rest of the
way. The only hole on which he had to avert another possible big
number was the 10th, where he hit his second shot onto the cliff
leading down to the Pacific Ocean and had to chop out. He took the
swing and wound up with a sore right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a rock right in front of my ball and I knew to hit
the shot I was going to have to hit the rock, too,'' he said. ``It
felt like one of my calluses ripped. But it's fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   Left in Woods' wake is Els, who knows he is virtually helpless
to play for anything but second place today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to shoot another score like this,'' he said after his
68, ``and see what happens. I have to feel like I'm in the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Woods, today's walk around Pebble Beach won't be any
different than the first three, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've woken up with the same game plan every day _ to keep the
ball in the fairway,'' he said. ``It's virtually impossible to get
the ball close if you're playing from the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were merely preparing their concession speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something dramatic happens, he's the winner already,''
said Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's always a dissenting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be caught,'' said David Duval. ``It's very easy to
shoot 6, 7, 8, 9 over and not really hit bad shots.''
</P>
<P>
   It has happened to just about everybody at the Open. Except one
person.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
