<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO MAKES NAME FOR HIMSELF _ THE PEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Orlando Palmeiro is known around the league as the
``other'' Palmeiro, but Rafael's cousin has quietly made a name for
himself in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro was a 33rd-round draft choice out of the University of
Miami in 1990, first reached the big leagues in 1995 and is making
a career for himself as a utility outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro is hitting .329, getting an occasional start in the
outfield or as the designated hitter, or serving as a pinch hitter.
He has no power - only one career homer - but he's a pest at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   His .425 on-base percentage is second on the team to Troy Glaus'
.427. His batting average is second to Darin Erstad's .367. He
makes a pitcher work, drawing walks and fouling off pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was his third start in five games, and he's started 17
overall (six in left, six in right, five as the DH). He's hit
safely in 15 of his 17 starts, batting .351 (20 for 57). But he
said he doesn't feel pressure to play his way into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of it as having to `earn' my starts,'' Palmeiro
said. ``When I get a chance to do what I can do, I want to be able
to perform. I want to help the team however I can, on or off the
field. If that means giving somebody a day off or picking somebody
up or even taking infield, that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for me is not to try to do too much. I'll never fill
Darin's shoes. I'll never fill Garret's (Anderson) shoes. What can
I do? See a lot of pitches, help tire a pitcher out. I can't hit
fourth or fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro has been consistent wherever or whenever he's playing.
He hit .320 in April, .320 in May and is hitting .350 in June. He's
hitting .300 in day games, .340 in night games. He's hitting .313
with runners in scoring position. And most importantly, he is
hitting .359 with two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Batting ninth Saturday, he led off the second inning and fell
behind in the count, 1-2. He fouled off three pitches, then was hit
by a pitch. Later in the inning he scored from second on a single
to left by Tim Salmon, using a nice slide to get past catcher Greg
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield throws: Pitcher Kent Bottenfield made 80 pitches
during a bullpen workout Saturday and is on track to return to the
starting rotation Saturday against the Twins in Anaheim.
Bottenfield, who went on the DL June 8 with shoulder tendinitis,
has one more test to pass a simulated game Tuesday in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   In a rehab start for Triple-A Edmonton on Friday night, Jason
Dickson gave up eight runs and eight hits in 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he needs a little more time,'' manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``His command was not as crisp as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson is trying to return from a strained left hip flexor.
</P>
</TEXT>
