<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-WOODS-HNS &LR;      06-18 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
National television audience witnesses Woods' profane outburst
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Hopefully, the kids weren't channel surfing
Saturday morning at about 10 a.m. expecting to get Bugs Bunny or
the Roadrunner on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   If they were, they got a big dose of expletives from Tiger Woods
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was on the 18th tee finishing his second round when he
pull-hooked his tee shot into the Pacific Ocean. If the first two
words out of his mouth wouldn't get a motion picture an `R' rating,
the third one most certainly would have. In the comics, they use
&AMP;%$ to say what Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods gathered himself, re-teed and went on to bogey the hole.
But the damage had been done. His foul language was beamed live and
uncensored throughout the country. NBC had added the morning
coverage of the U.S. Open mainly because of the allure Woods has.
He played seven holes Saturday morning to finish his second round.
</P>
<P>
   At the behest of his management team, Woods later would
apologize for his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the heat of the moment,'' said Woods, who finished
Saturday's third-round action with a 10-stroke lead. ``I was
frustrated to end a round like that. And unfortunately, I let it
slip out. I regret that it happened, and I can apologize until I'm
blue in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was a very frustrating moment and I just let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that most fans enjoy seeing Woods wear his emotions
openly on the golf course. Golf is in need of charisma, and Woods
has it. But he also has uttered many curse words on the course in
different tournaments. Usually, however, they don't end up on
national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first time,'' said Tom Kite. ``I just hate to see
Tiger do stuff like that. I hope he shows some remorse later for
what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   What irks some players and spectators is that Woods mutters
things that nobody else is saying on the PGA Tour _ not audibly,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard Jack (Nicklaus) say it,'' Kite said. ``I never
saw Arnold (Palmer) do it. I never saw (Tom) Watson do it. And I
doubt Bobby Jones ever did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that kind of language is more commonplace in our
society now. But it doesn't belong out here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, most PGA Tour players have a slip of the tongue
periodically. And they wonder if people who are driving in traffic
and get cut off can hold their emotions as well as golfers do on
most occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the worst thing Tiger does in 20 years out here,
that'll be great,'' said Fred Couples. ``He's no worse than anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument can be made that microphones shouldn't be within
shouting distance of the players, either. But the reactions of
professional athletes have become part of what fans expect to see
and hear during the course of competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the mike's not there, you're offending people standing at
the tee,'' Kite said. ``In my opinion, it just doesn't belong.''
</P>
<P>
   All PGA Tour players know that basic golf etiquette is expected
from them. Any time a player voices an obscenity and is reported by
a marshal or fan, he usually receives a fine from the PGA Tour
office.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, handling emotions is one of the toughest parts of
playing competitive golf, said Ernie Els.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take responsibility for your actions and
comments,'' Els said. ``Golf is not a contact sport. But when it
gets tense on the course and things don't go your way, you are
going to say some things. I've said some things and gotten away
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that emotions such as what Woods displayed Saturday
seem to boil over at just the wrong time?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the U.S. Open,'' Els said. ``You try to do the perfect
thing. But it's the U.S. Open, and it's very difficult to deal with
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
