<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ORIOLES-LA     06-18 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ORIOLES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER BACK, WELL-ARMED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ He's 38 years old and has a five-inch scar on his
right elbow, but Tim Belcher showed the Baltimore Orioles on
Saturday night there's more to pitching than a young, strong arm.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first start of the season after off-season elbow
surgery, Belcher held the Orioles to one run and five hits in 5
innings in the Anaheim Angels' 8-3 victory before 45,758 at Camden
Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher (1-0) got all the help he needed from Troy Glaus, Garret
Anderson and Mo Vaughn. Glaus hit a two-run homer (No. 19) in the
second inning, Anderson hit a three-run homer (No. 17) in the third
inning and Vaughn hit a solo homer (No. 20) in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive outburst came after they scored a total of six
runs during a three-game losing streak, but Belcher was the story
on this night.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was expected back in early May but suffered a setback in
his recovery and had to stop throwing. But he came back strong in
his first major-league start since Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled early as he needed 58 pitches to finish two
innings, but he made big pitches to get out of both innings
unscathed. In the first inning, he walked the first two batters
then struck out Delino DeShields to bring up Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `OK, dummy, you just walked two guys to get to
the hottest hitter on the planet,''' Belcher said.
</P>
<P>
   But Belcher got Belle to hit into a 4-6-3 double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, the Orioles had the bases loaded, two out
and a full count on Brady Anderson, who was caught looking at a
fastball for strike three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brady's a tough guy for me,'' Belcher said. ``I made a good
pitch on the outside part of the plate. He probably thought it was
off the plate, and maybe it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher settled down after the second inning, allowing only two
more hits until Belle led off the sixth with a home run. Belle has
six homers and 16 RBI in his past four games. But that was all the
Orioles could muster off Belcher, who left the game with one out in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belcher has a great history behind him,'' said Angels manager
Mike Scioscia, who caught Belcher with the Dodgers. ``He's pitched
in playoffs and the World Series. His stuff is not what it was 10
years ago, but he has great presence out there, and he's a true
competitor. He brings a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's fastball reaches only 88 or 89 mph, but his slider and
splitter worked well for him Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bench coach) Joe Maddon made the comment after the game that
stuff-wise, the break on my slider and the quality of my splitter
was as good as he's ever seen it,'' Belcher said. ``I need to do
that. Obviously, I'm not going to throw my fastball by too many
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher admitted that at this stage of his career there are no
guarantees he could still pitch at the major-league level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything held together,'' he said. ``I tried not to have too
unrealistic expectations. I told myself no matter what I do or how
it goes, if I get killed or pitch well, as long as I come out of
the game and feel well, I have to give myself a little bit of
credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure anybody my age, coming off an injury, to go out and
compete and get myself out of jams and throw 100 pitches and come
back in five days, is a small victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's teammates agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back and throw as well as he threw, it's almost like
the surgery made him stronger,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   For Anderson, the homer came after one day's benching and an
equipment adjustment. Scioscia gave Anderson the game off Friday so
his center fielder could relax a little after a 1-for-15 slump.
Anderson had only two RBI in his previous 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson went back to using a lighter bat (Orlando
Palmeiro's), making him quicker through the strike zone, and the
change paid off. The heavier bat might have helped him hit more
home runs, but it made his average suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to a much bigger bat (this season),'' Scioscia said.
``He came to the realization he has a lot more bat control (with a
lighter bat) and can be much more consistent as a run-producer in
the fifth spot with a bat he can handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia first intended to give Anderson a day off Saturday as
well, but Anderson talked Scioscia out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in there and told him I wanted to play,'' Anderson
said. ``I didn't give him any excuses, and he believed what I said
was true. I said I was fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
