<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-MOSLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY BEATS DE LA HOYA FOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the end, it didn't come down to who was bigger,
stronger, more experienced, quicker or more focused. It came down
to who was better.
</P>
<P>
   And, in spite of the opinion of one judge who will be criticized
by some in the days to come, it was Shane Mosley who was the better
fighter as he defeated Oscar De La Hoya by a split decision before
20,744 completely satisfied fans Saturday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lou Filippo scored it 116-112 while Pat Russell had it
115-113 in favor of Mosley. Marty Sammon certainly was in the
minority when he scored it 115-113 in favor of De La Hoya. The
Daily News had 116-112 Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   For Mosley, the victory gives him the WBC welterweight
championship and removes any doubt as to his place in the boxing
world: A great champion was born this day.
</P>
<P>
   He displayed all the things associated with such a fighter -
skill, speed, power and tremendous courage and determination.
Although he appeared to be ahead, he stood toe-to-toe with De La
Hoya in an unforgettable 12th round for the sole purpose of showing
how big his heart is, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley (35-0, with 32 knockouts) has some multi-million-dollar
paydays in his near future.
</P>
<P>
   For De La Hoya, this hurts. The Golden Boy, once the king of his
sport in many respects, has lost his last two big fights. He also
was outpointed by Felix Trinidad in September.
</P>
<P>
   If he had an aura of invincibility, it's long gone and we're
left to wonder where he goes from here.
</P>
<P>
   However, this certainly isn't the end for two reasons: the way
he lost and the fact Mosley is expected to give him an immediate
rematch.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times in recent years, De La Hoya (32-2, 26
KOs) did exactly what he said he'd do - go after Mosley throughout
the fight even if it meant risking his own well being.
</P>
<P>
   He absorbed considerable punishment as a result of his strategy,
mostly quick, straight right hands that rocked but never seriously
hurt him. Even when it became apparent that he was a beaten man, De
La Hoya kept coming. Those who have doubted his courage will have
to admit that.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch? Mosley said emphatically before the fight that
there would be one because De La Hoya had given !ital!him!off! a
tremendous opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Those who witnessed the first installment will be thrilled if it
actually happens. They got their money's worth in the first truly
big fight in Los Angeles in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Mosley said when asked if there would be a
rematch. ``A fight that close, there has to be. We showed there are
two great champions from California.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was diplomatic afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed,'' he said. ``It was a great fight. What
can I say? We put on a great show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, a rematch has to happen. I'll just rethink my game
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Again, De La Hoya, who had predicted he would knock out each of
his four opponents in 2000, executed his prefight strategy: He
stalked Mosley throughout.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mosley, the quickest fighter De La Hoya has seen, coped
wonderfully. Like a powerful cat, he leaped in, did his damage with
body shots and the rights and then quickly moved out of harm's way.
He also confused De La Hoya by switching to a left-handed stance on
several occasions, a testament to his ring acumen.
</P>
<P>
   And when he was in punching range, De La Hoya somehow was unable
land clean, telling shots consistently. Mosley, rarely in the wrong
place at the wrong time, was much better defensively than many had
believed.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley also removed any doubt about his strength. Many believed
De La Hoya would be too strong for the challenger because Mosley
had recently moved from 135 pounds to 147, De La Hoya's weight
class the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   However, this was never evident. He took many good shots and
while he couldn't put De La Hoya, it was his punches that did the
most significant damage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most impressive was Mosley's determination.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was very much in doubt going into the final three
rounds. And it was Mosley, not the supposedly stronger De La Hoya,
was looked fresher, stronger and more confident.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley won two of the final three rounds on two cards and all
three on the third to win the fight and the hearts of all those who
watched him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you I was stronger at 147,'' Mosley said. ``He hit me
with good, crisp shots but never dazed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I showed the world in the 12th round what kind of fighter
I am by standing in front of him and - win, lose or draw - fighting
like a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, CompuBox statistics were fairly even.
</P>
<P>
   De la Hoya connected on 257 of 718 punches, Mosley 284 of 678.
De La Hoya landed 165 power shots, Mosley 174.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was awarded the WBC championship when Felix Trinidad
vacated the title. He has held five titles in four weight classes.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley is the former IBF lightweight champion. He defended his
title - which he won by beating Philip Holiday in August of 1997 -
eight times before skipping the 140-pound class and moving to 147.
</P>
<P>
   All of his defenses ended in knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the fight, Mosley was believed to have the highest
knockout rate of any fighter to win a title: 94 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters turned pro around the same time, De La Hoya in
November of 1992, Mosley in February of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   However, De La Hoya, armed with the United States' only gold
medal in the 1992 Olympics, took the boxing world by storm.
</P>
<P>
   He fought in big-money, high-profile events from the start and
won his first title - the WBO junior lightweight championship - in
only his 12th fight. He stopped Jimmi Bredahl in March of 1994 to
win the belt.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, who failed to make the Olympic team and had a novice
promoter early in his career, beat Holiday in his 24th bout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
