<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-TIGERLEDE-BOS &LR;      06-18 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGERLEDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCH HIM IF YOU CAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ His ball was in thick rough, the stance
dictated he had to hit out sideways, the wind was howling, and
scores were soaring like desert temperatures in July. So after
taking three hacks at it and making triple bogey at the par-4 third
hole, Tiger Woods was in big trouble Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Right, and the price of real estate on 17 Mile Drive will go
down when this championship leaves town.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, if you are going to make a triple bogey, it's
advisable to do so when you have an eight-shot lead, which is the
scenario Woods faced as he did his Gil Morgan impression on No. 3.
But we know Tiger Woods, and Tiger Woods is no Gil Morgan, which
explains why he is in total control of the 100th US Open at Pebble
Beach Golf Links.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to play a safe shot,'' said Woods of the
travails at the third. He recovered with three birdies in four
holes, starting at the par-5 sixth, then added a little bit of
frosting by reaching the par-5 14th in two glorious shots _ a drive
of 320 yards and a 2-iron from 253. After he two-putted for his
fifth birdie of the day, Woods parred his way home to shoot 71_205,
at 8 under the only player in the field in red numbers. Oh, and he
has a 10-shot lead over his nearest competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor has it that player was Ernie Els, whose 68_215 was the
only subpar score handed in on a day when the wind howled at a
steady 20 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Was he back in it, at 2 over? Els, who passed 34 players, put on
the rose-colored glasses and said: ``I have to believe that,
yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   He has to say that because USGA bylaws require that 72 holes be
played to determine a US Open championship, so Els will join Woods
at the first tee in the final pairing Sunday. The only question is
how many records Woods will set as he marches toward something that
is quite similar to his 12-shot win at the 1997 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods negotiated his first hurdle by answering his early
wake-up call to get to the course at 6:30 and complete his second
round in 69_134, he tied a US Open record for lowest 36-hole score
and set a new mark for largest lead (six shots). Now he owns the
largest 54-hole lead and needs to shoot 66_271 to establish a US
Open victory standard.
</P>
<P>
   But that is all incidental stuff to Woods, whose performance on
the day _ when the field average was 77.124 _ had even him dancing
for joy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. ``I just tried to play safe, figuring if I kept
it around par I would pick up some shots,'' said Woods. ``The golf
course was not playing easy. The conditions were severe out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they did not reach the proportions that plagued the final
round of this event here in 1992 _ in which Morgan became the only
player in US Open history to reach double digits under par, before
collapsing to the fifth page of the leaderboard _ Woods was correct
as 16 players shot in the 80s.
</P>
<P>
   They included Thomas Bjorn (82), who was in the lead group with
Woods, but was quickly lost in a sea of bogeys, joining befuddled
colleagues such as Colin Montgomerie (79_226), Sergio Garcia
(81_227), Hal Sutton (83_225), Vijay Singh (80_223), and Lee Janzen
(79_223).
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods had his problems, though he recovered from his third
hole to make easy pars at the fourth and fifth, then a
scintillating birdie at the par-5 sixth.
</P>
<P>
   He had driven it well right, into thick rough, and pulled his
second shot to the left of the fairway, right to the edge of a
bunker, ``into the hay.''
</P>
<P>
   He planted his right foot in the bunker, his left leg up on the
bank, choked down on a wedge, and punched his shot 64 yards to the
front of the green. It came to rest 12 feet above the pin and Woods
got some input from his caddie, Steve Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me it was an important putt, to bury it,'' said Woods,
who followed orders.
</P>
<P>
   Woods then went up-and-down in the wind _ a birdie at the
seventh, a bogey at the eighth, a birdie at the ninth, then a bogey
at the 10th when an approach shot ``got away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended up in a hazard, on the cliff leading to the beach, and
as spectators strolling in front of a roaring ocean looked on,
Woods saw some problems. A rock in front of his ball. ``If you're
going to hit the shot,'' he said to himself, ``you're going to have
to rip out that rock.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did, punching his shot to the front of the green, from
where he made bogey. But it was what they call a good bogey, one
that calmed him for an incoming eight-hole stretch that featured
seven solid pars and that superb birdie at the 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who is in line to win his first US Open and third major
championship at the tender age of 24, has not joined Morgan as a
player to reach a double-digit red numbers in this championship _
but give him time, there are 18 more holes.
</P>
<P>
   They are 18 holes that promise to produce a bunch of guys who
feel like George Low, Val Fitzjohn, and W.H. Way. Those were the
gents who finished tied for second, 11 shots behind Willie Smith in
1899.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
