<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7479 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS &LR;      06-18 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY DETHRONES DE LA HOYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The crowd waited tensely in the long minutes after
the conclusion of 12 rounds of warfare Saturday night between Oscar
De La Hoya and Shane Mosley because no one knew for sure the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, ring announcer Michael Buffer read the scorecards
before finally saying ``. . . and new . . .'' When he did, De La
Hoya's head slumped to his chest for a moment and then anger showed
through.
</P>
<P>
   He had lost for the second time in three fights. Lost the World
Boxing Council welterweight title. Lost even the designation as the
finest fighter in Los Angeles. Lost everything to former
lightweight champion ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   But De La Hoya lost in spectacular fashion as he and Mosley put
on the kind of show that demanded what Mosley had already agreed to
and De La Hoya reminded him of.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a rematch,'' De La Hoya (32-2) said. ``Every
great fight deserves one.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this one did because this was a great night of boxing
and a great night for boxing, a night when both the performers and
the judges did their jobs well.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, judge Lou Filippo scored the bout, 116-112, for
Mosley, Pat Russell had it 115-113 for the undefeated former
lightweight champion, and judge Marty Sammon had it 115-113 for De
La Hoya. The Globe card had Mosley a 115-113 victor by virtue of
winning the final five rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close fight,'' Mosley said. ``We went toe-to-toe for
12 rounds. We went soul-searching in that last round. We showed
we're both great warriors. Oscar is a great champion. I was just
the better man tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The better man entered the arena first, with his son and two
companions sauntering alongside him as if they were all going to
the park for a Saturday night ice cream. Suddenly, Mosley bolted
down the aisle and up the three steps that separated him from
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   As Mosley slipped through the ropes, he looked like a guy in
complete agreement with Lou Gehrig. ``Tonight I consider myself the
luckiest guy on the face of the earth,'' Gehrig once said. Mosley
didn't say it but he looked it as he waited for De La Hoya to join
him.
</P>
<P>
   As he bounced up and down in his corner, mariachi music blared
and De La Hoya arrived, a red hood over his head and a serious look
on his face.
</P>
<P>
   While Mosley smiled to the crowd, De La Hoya raised a gloved
fist to acknowledge the packed house, but otherwise was all
business as an explosion of fireworks ignited overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, it was Mosley who was igniting the fireworks,
pressing De La Hoya hard from the opening bell and turning the left
side of the champion's face red with his sharp jabs and quick
counters.
</P>
<P>
   But De La Hoya quickly adjusted to Mosley's speed and began to
find him with his jab in the second round. He hurt Mosley with a
body shot on the inside that seemed to slow his aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley landed a right to the jaw early in the third that
momentarily slowed De La Hoya's jab. Mosley controlled most of the
third round with a sneaky lead right that twice landed, but a
left-right combination from De La Hoya was the most solid shot of
the round.
</P>
<P>
   Through four rounds, it was a back-and-forth affair but De La
Hoya appeared to be controlling the tempo, closing ground on Mosley
and forcing him to retreat over and over again after his initial
attack in Round 1. Mosley was scoring with his own jab and a lead
right but was unable to go to the body in the way he has done so
often in his eight lightweight title defenses.
</P>
<P>
   When De La Hoya had his jab working, Mosley was unable to attack
with ferocity, and late in Round 5, De La Hoya landed a
left-right-left combination that seemed to wobble Mosley before he
held on for the first time in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's face seemed less confident as he sat in his corner
after Round 6 listening to his father's instructions. For perhaps
the first time in his professional career, Mosley was now in a
fight in which he was not the boss, he was not dictating the terms
of the engagement, and he did not seem comfortable with his
circumstances, or willing to reassert his own will over De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth round, Mosley's best since the start of the fight,
he landed a jab with his left hand and then switched to southpaw
and landed a solid right a second later. For most of the eighth,
Mosley stayed southpaw and that switch slowed De La Hoya's jab and
turned him into a cautious observer.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley continued to come on in the ninth round as De La Hoya
appeared to tire as he had against Felix Trinidad in the only loss
of his career. Mosley's double jab and right hand did some serious
damage and when he rattled a combination off De La Hoya's face late
in Round 9, the crowd roared as the fight began to approach the
skilled savagery predicted for it.
</P>
<P>
   Rounds 10 and 11 were skillfully fought with Mosley now holding
his ground more often and landing more readily with a jab that
seemed to be bothering a tiring De La Hoya. As the final round
approached, both men knew these three minutes might decide who is
the pound-for-pound best fighter in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Both fought furiously in the center of the ring in the final
round for more than a minute. Blood dripped from De La Hoya's nose
after one exchange and Mosley then rocked him with a solid shot
with two minutes to go, but the champion responded not by holding
on but by firing back as the crowd screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley landed a big right hand with 1:20 to go that shook De La
Hoya, and then another, and the champion wobbled and held on but
refused to fall. The effort left Mosley breathing heavily with :35
left, but instead of De La Hoya charging him, it was Mosley who
landed the last big punch of the night, one more furious right hand
just before the final bell sounded.
</P>
<P>
   When it did, both men smiled widely and embraced. Two champions
in the ring on this night, but only one victor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
