<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS DOMINATING U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Tiger Woods proved the U.S. Golf
Association correct Saturday, demonstrating that par can be a
really great score in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in winds that gusted throughout his late-afternoon
round, the world's No. 1-ranked player overcame two bogeys, a
triple bogey and seemingly a week's worth of trouble shots to shoot
a third-round 71 at Pebble Beach Beach Golf Links - which all but
clinches the championship of the 100th Open.
</P>
<P>
   If the fat lady isn't singing yet, her vocal chords might never
recover by the time she starts belting this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' latest effort - perhaps his most impressive of the week,
given the conditions - left him 8-under-par 205, 10 strokes ahead
of second-place Ernie Els, establishing an Open record for
third-round margin and left Els (215) with this daunting
proposition:
</P>
<P>
   Should Woods match par again in today's final round, his closest
opponent would have to break the Open single-round record of 63 by
two strokes just to secure a share of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess tomorrow, when I go out there,'' Woods said, ``if I
play solid golf and play the way I know I can, then somebody is
going to have to shoot a really good number.''
</P>
<P>
   Els showed he was up for a challenge by shooting 68 Saturday -
best score of the third round by three shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my run-ins with Tiger in the past,'' Els said after
that round, which started nearly three hours earlier than Woods
teed off, enabling the South African to dodge much of the
third-round wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get more of those battles with Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   He got his wish, riding that 69 to a final-round pairing with
Woods today.
</P>
<P>
   Padraig Harrington of Ireland and Miguel Angel Jimenez of Spain
are a stroke back of Els at 216, trailed by Phil Mickelson and
Spain's Jose Maria Olazabel (both 217) in an event that rivals
Woods' record 12-stroke domination of the '97 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've played better this year (at the Open) than I did
(at the Masters) in '97,'' Woods said. ``Just because of the fact
it's so much more difficult off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to pay a price for every missed fairway Saturday, but
fought back impressively, digging himself out of deep rough and
bunkers for dramatic par-saves or birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one bad break on No. 3 but other than that I thought I
played pretty good,'' said Woods, who had to come out of the rough
three times during that triple bogey on the third hole.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his other rough rough escapes were magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   He came out of the thick stuff twice to birdie the par-5,
513-yard, severely uphill sixth hole, hitting arguably his best
shot of the tournament in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Standing awkwardly with one foot in a bunker and the other in
calf-length rough, Woods hacked the ball to within six feet of the
flagstick for his second of five birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was some hay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He later saved par from a greenside bunker on No. 17, then
hacked out of fairway rough on No. 18 to nearly pull off a sixth
birdie on what was his 24th hole of the day.
</P>
<P>
   As did more than a third of the field, Woods had to get up early
for a 6:30 a.m. resumption of Friday's darkness-suspended second
round.
</P>
<P>
   He finished that round at 69 to tie the best 36-hole total in
Open history. By the time he was finished for the day, Woods had
spent 14 hours on the course, much of it in wind that was at its
gustiest when he was playing Pebble Beach's most-demanding stretch
of holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played I guess the toughest stretch - 8, 9 and 10 - in a
pretty good wind,'' said Woods, who negotiated that trio in bogey,
birdie, bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind is such a factor on this golf course,'' said Els.
``It's taken all week for the wind to start blowing and you're
going to see some really high scores now. I had a really major good
break not to play with too much wind on the first nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods had no such break, nor did he break under the toughest
conditions he has faced all week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
