<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7482 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-MOSLEY-SIDEBAR-LA     06-18 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOSLEY-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY'S STEP TOWARD GREATNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the beginning of the 10th round of Saturday's
welterweight title fight between ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley and Oscar
De La Hoya, one veteran boxing writer said, ``He is a great
fighter.``
</P>
<P>
   But if Tony the Tiger had been speaking about Mosley, he simply
would have said, ``He's grrrrrrrreat.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mosley was all that - and then some in winning the World
Boxing Council and International Boxing Association belts from De
La Hoya on a split decision.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mosley's coming-out party, the one that brought him
greatness before a screaming Staples Center crowd of 20,744 that
watched what will certainly go down as one of the sterling fights
in L.A. history.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, of Pomona, was faster than East Los Angeles' De La Hoya.
He was just as strong, stronger even during a spectacular 12th
round where the two California warriors went toe-to-toe the entire
three minutes, Mosley nearly decking De La Hoya on two occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see in the 12th round, we went toe-to-toe and we did
some soul-searching to see who was the champion,'' Mosley said.
``And he went toe-to-toe with me the whole round. He was really
strong. He was fighting great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to show the world I was prepared to fight the whole
12 rounds. I had to show the world I was a true champion. I was
just the better man tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the fight, Mosley had said he was in search of
greatness. He said if he were ahead late, he would not turn his
back and run because he thought he had the fight won. Run, he did
not. Neither did De La Hoya, who may have lost, but while doing so
earned back some of the respect he forfeited after running from
Felix Trinidad Jr. in September.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Mosley's night. He was so good, it was scary. He
connected on 42 percent of his total punches, compared to only 36
percent for De La Hoya, who has never swung and missed so often
before. Mosley also had a 57 percent connect percentage on his
power punches, to just 37 percent to De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was very gracious, and appropriately complimentary
afterward. He even went so far as to say he was not disappointed
because the fans got a great fight.
</P>
<P>
   Even De La Hoya seemed to be in awe of ``Sugar'' Shane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed,'' De La Hoya said. ``We fought a great
fight. People wanted to see a war and they got it. He was very
fast. I give him all the credit in the world. More power to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a fighter who kept coming and was in great shape. I
gave a good effort and a great fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, there was a rematch clause in the contracts signed
for this fight. And both fighters said they definitely want to see
it come off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it has to happen,'' De La Hoya said. ``I am going to
have to change my game plan because Shane Mosley sidetracked me a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of a fight. Two classy L.A. guys giving a large
audience what it deserved, a slugfest with some of the most
beautiful work you'll ever see in a ring.
</P>
<P>
   And De La Hoya did not complain about the verdict. If anything,
he could have felt fortunate that one judge gave him the bout by
two points.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mosley, he, too, is looking forward to the rematch. When
he entered the ring, he had a big smile on his face, as if he was
about to go out onto the playground and join his friends. Fun, he
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in there warring and he was in there warring,'' Mosley
said. ``I showed I was the best in the world. He showed he was one
of the best in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't think for a moment that the great ``Sugar'' Shane
Mosley forgot about his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say hello to P-town,'' Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   You can also bet De La Hoya's promoter, Bob Arum, will get his
guy back into the ring with Mosley as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Arum said, ``that is the fight we will make
next.''
</P>
<P>
   If only it would be just as great.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
