<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7483 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-SIDEBAR-     06-18 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHOW WAS `SPECTACULAR'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Well, Oscar De La Hoya knows a good show when he
sees one, especially when he's one of the boxers involved.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he's less in tune with happy endings. For the
second time in nine months, he failed to close with gusto and lost,
this time surrendering the WBC welterweight championship on a split
decision Saturday night to Shane Mosley before 20,744 raucous fans
at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know I have heart, and I'm a warrior in the ring,'' De
La Hoya said. ``What can I say? We put on a great show and had a
great fight, but I guess it went his way.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's only other loss, a 12-round decision to Felix
Trinidad in Las Vegas last September, was much different than this
setback. Back then, De La Hoya purposely danced and avoided
Trinidad the last two rounds because he thought was far enough
ahead on points.
</P>
<P>
   This time, De La Hoya (32-2, 26 knockouts) again asserted
himself - he was ahead on two of three cards after nine rounds -
but the last three rounds proved utterly decisive.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya didn't have enough.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley (35-0, 32 knockouts) was too quick and too assertive on
inside exchanges. It was Mosley, not De La Hoya, who won over the
crowd and responded to the exuberant cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley hails from Pomona and De La Hoya from Los Angeles, but
the early crowd reaction made it seem like Pomona was awfully far
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give Shane all the credit in the world. He's a fast
fighter,'' De La Hoya said. ``I was really surprised the way he
kept on coming. I thought I gave a good effort and gave the crowd
their money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence is everything to a boxer. In Mosley's case,
confidence was enough for him to overcome an escalation in weight
class and to pocket De La Hoya's crowd with the ease of a man
picking up a quarter from the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I had to show I'm a true warrior,'' Mosley said.
``Oscar's a great champion, and we put on a spectacular fight. But
I was just a better man tonight. I showed the world who Sugar Shane
Mosley is tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya said a rematch !ital!has!off! to happen.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? This was a terrific night for boxing, a sport that
desperately needs such electrifying performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great fight like this deserves a rematch,'' De La Hoya said.
``It has to happen, but I also need to rethink my game plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 0226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
