A7484 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-MUTINY-LAD     06-18 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-MUTINY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FINALLY AWAKENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ You figure with a celebrity-filled mega-fight
nearby, a city nervously awaiting the Lakers' fate and a Tiger
roaring up north, the Los Angeles Galaxy could continue its
freefall down the Western Division standings, and all would be
forgotten by sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Galaxy players, who have grown tired of this
recent run of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Sigi Schmid admitted earlier in the week that panic hadn't
set in, but it was getting dangerously close.
</P>
<P>
   During this recent 1-3-4 stretch of eight games, Schmid said his
team lost focus after the allocation of Luis Hernandez. He said
they needed to regain their killer instinct, needed to find their
arrogance and that feeling of invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Simon Elliott, as hot as anyone on the roster,
provided a much needed early spark. It was just what Schmid was
looking for.
</P>
<P>
   And the Galaxy followed suit Saturday night, attacking in waves,
getting contributions everywhere in a confidence-boosting 2-1
victory over Tampa Bay before 14,603 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Lagos scored in the 90th minute for Tampa Bay, but it
wasn't enough to spoil the Galaxy's first win since May 20,
snapping a four-game winless streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a win, but more than anything, we created chances as
much as we have in the last five weeks,'' said Schmid. ``As long as
we can build on that, we'll continue to get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who's leaving to join New Zealand's national team, will
miss the next three games and possibly four. But not before he
notched his third goal since April 29.
</P>
<P>
   On a free kick from 25 yards, Greg Vanney and Mauricio
Cienfuegos both faked shots with Elliott running on the goal.
Elliott curled a shot to the upper right of the net for a 1-0 lead
in the ninth minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simon does a lot of work that people don't notice,'' said
Schmid. ``We decided on our first free kick to let Simon hit it.
Tampa Bay was going to expect Cienfuegos or Vanney to take it. If
you watch the goal, as Vanney approached, you see (Scott) Garlick
(goalkeeper) start to cheat a step because he thought Vanney was
going to hit it. Nobody has seen Simon hit one of those. It was a
perfectly placed shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was rookie Danny Califf's turn. From the right corner,
Vanney sent a cross into traffic, but Califf beat everyone to it,
heading his shot to the near post past Mutiny goalkeeper Scott
Garlick in the 39th minute, giving Califf his first career goal.
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be enough as the Galaxy (7-3-6, 27 points) crept
closer to Kansas City (10-2-3, 33 points). The West Division
leading Wizards lost 4-1 to Dallas earlier in the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
