<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-MOSLEY-R     06-18 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-MOSLEY-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY BEATS DE LA HOYA FOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the end, it didn't come down to who was bigger,
stronger, more experienced, quicker or more focused. It came down
to who was better.
</P>
<P>
   And, in spite of the opinion of one judge who will be criticized
in the days to come, it was Shane Mosley who was the better fighter
as he defeated Oscar De La Hoya by a split decision before 20,744
completely satisfied fans Saturday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lou Filippo scored it 116-112 while Pat Russell had it
115-113, both in favor of Mosley. Marty Sammon scored it a curious
115-113 in favor of De La Hoya. The Daily News had 116-112 Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   For Mosley, the victory gives him the WBC welterweight
championship awarded to De La Hoya when Felix Trinidad vacated the
title. And it removes any doubt as to his place in the boxing
world: A great champion was born this night.
</P>
<P>
   He displayed all the things associated with such a fighter
</P>
<P>
   skill, speed, power and tremendous courage and determination.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was still very much in doubt going into the final
three rounds, a time when great fighters find a way to win. And it
was a fiercely determined Mosley (35-0, with 32 knockouts) who had
more to offer when it counted.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mosley appeared to be ahead, he stood toe-to-toe with
De La Hoya in an unforgettable - and one-sided - 12th round that
clinched the victory and punctuated a fabulous performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I took my career to another level tonight,'' a beaming
Mosley said and no one would argue.
</P>
<P>
   For De La Hoya, this hurts. The Golden Boy, once the king of his
sport in many respects, has lost his last two big fights. He also
was outpointed by Trinidad in September, a highly criticized
performance in which he ran the final three rounds to lose a fight
he was winning.
</P>
<P>
   If he had an aura of invincibility, it's long gone and we're
left to wonder whether he'll ever again rise to the top of the
boxing world.
</P>
<P>
   However, this most likely isn't the end for at least two
reasons: the !ital!way!off! he lost and the fact Mosley is expected
to give him an immediate rematch.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times in recent years, De La Hoya (32-2, 26
KOs) did exactly what he said he'd do - go after Mosley throughout
the fight even if it meant risking his own well being.
</P>
<P>
   He absorbed considerable punishment as a result of his strategy,
mostly quick, straight right hands that rocked but never seriously
hurt him. Even when it became apparent that he was a beaten man, De
La Hoya kept coming. Those who have doubted his courage will have
to admit that.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch? Mosley said emphatically before the fight that
there would be one because De La Hoya had given him a tremendous
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Those who witnessed the first installment would be thrilled if
it actually happens. They got their money's worth in the first
truly big fight in Los Angeles in a generation, one of the better
fights in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Mosley said when asked if there would be a
rematch. ``A fight that close, there has to be. We showed there are
two great champions from California.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, his right eye bruised and puffy, was diplomatic
immediately after the fight, congratulating Mosley and seemingly
accepting the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   However, at a news conference 1 hours after the bout, he seemed
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed he won a close fight and strongly implied
that he was a victim of a calculated decision to give the Mosley
the victory so others could make money from a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't say the fight was fixed but said ``things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested he might retire but admitted he'll think about his
next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a business,'' he said. ``People want a rematch. ... If
they give me a decision, there's no (second) fight. ... It's tough
to live with what goes on around boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can't continue on like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, at the same time, he tried to give Mosley his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from Shane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, De La Hoya, who had predicted he would knock out each of
his four opponents in 2000, executed his prefight strategy from the
beginning: He stalked Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mosley, the quickest fighter De La Hoya has seen, coped
wonderfully. Like a cunning cat, he repeatedly pounced in, did his
damage with body shots and the rights, and then quickly moved out
of harm's way to admire his work.
</P>
<P>
   He also confused De La Hoya by switching to a left-handed stance
on several occasions, a testament to his ring acumen.
</P>
<P>
   And when Mosley was in punching range, De La Hoya somehow was
unable land clean, telling shots consistently. Mosley, rarely in
the wrong place at the wrong time, was much better defensively than
many had believed.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley also removed any doubt about his strength. Many believed
De La Hoya would be too strong for the challenger because Mosley
had recently moved from 135 pounds to 147, De La Hoya's weight
class the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   However, this was never evident. He took many good shots and
while he couldn't put De La Hoya down or out, it was his punches
that did the most significant damage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most impressive was Mosley's determination.
</P>
<P>
   In those final three rounds, the ``championship'' rounds, it was
Mosley, not the supposedly stronger De La Hoya, who looked fresher,
stronger and more confident.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley won two of the final three rounds on two cards and all
three on the third to win the fight and the hearts of all those who
witnessed his performance.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-De La Hoya crowd, which booed Mosley as he entered the
ring, could only admire him as he left it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you I was stronger at 147,'' Mosley said. ``He hit me
with good, crisp shots but never dazed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I showed the world in the 12th round what kind of fighter
I am by standing in front of him and, win, lose or draw, fighting
like a warrior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
