<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FIDDLER-GUY0619-COX     06-18 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDDLER-GUY0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    73-year-old fiddle player proves it's never too late to follow a
dream
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   May 6, 1997
</P>
<P>
   Dear Professor:
</P>
<P>
   My name is George Nance. I am 70 years old. Can you teach me to
play the fiddle?
</P>
<P>
   That's how George F. Nance started a letter to a local music
professor whom he'd hoped would help fulfill a lifelong dream _ to
be able to strum out his favorite melodies on the fiddle.
</P>
<P>
   When Nance was a child in the 1930s, he didn't just want to play
the fiddle. He wanted to entertain with the fiddle. He would study
and idolize the long-haired fiddlers performing between acts of
plays at his elementary school, the New Olive School, just outside
Oglesby, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to at least play some kind of musical instrument,''
he said, ``because the voice is the language of the body, but music
is the language of the soul.''
</P>
<P>
   But finances were tight for his farmer-parents. They couldn't
afford to buy a 19-cent harmonica, much less a fiddle.
</P>
<P>
   So his dream would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 17, instead of trying to graduate from high
school, I was working on the railroad in Roscoe. With my first
paycheck, I went to a pawn shop and bought a Stradivarius. Under
mother's bed, being the safest place in the house, I put it there.
One week later, the house burned down.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was ruled arson, he said. He's been told the $15 violin
that went up in smoke would be worth $30,000 now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize it then, but that's kinda disheartening
now,'' Nance said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he joined the Army and was sent to Germany to rebuild
railroads destroyed in World War II. While he was there, he
listened to violinists on the radio and attended professional
concerts, still dreaming of making music himself.
</P>
<P>
   But after the war, he brought home a German bride, reared two
children and worked as a postman for the city of Waco. He became
busy with activities at the Masonic Lodge, and then came grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife died and he married again, to Louise, who says
she never let her own kids take music lessons because she didn't
want the noise in the house.
</P>
<P>
   As Nance got older, he suffered heart attacks and underwent
by-pass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   So his dream would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I went to another pawn shop and bought a Yosef Lidle
fiddle, hand-crafted by Cremona, in Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   I must tell you I cannot read music. I can't tell a melody from
a malady. I can't tell a C-note from a hundred dollar bill.
</P>
<P>
   In holding the fiddle in the prescribed or usual manner, my
fingers are at constant odds over which one gets to push down the
next string. While the right hand draws the bow across the strings,
it emits sounds that would put a hyena to shame.
</P>
<P>
   Age, more than anything, made Nance drive to Waco Pawn Shop and
buy a $150-fiddle three years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting up to be 70, and, well, I just realized most of
my time had come and gone, and if I'm gonna do anything, I'd better
do it today 'cause tomorrow would be too late. I don't have the
agility of an 18-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance said he never thought he had any musical ability. He
thought the only ``instrument'' he could play was the radio.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``I just always had a real strong desire to play
the fiddle.''
</P>
<P>
   After 50 years, he finally had another fiddle. The next step
would be finding a teacher so he could finally play it.
</P>
<P>
   But his dream would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot teach me, please put me in touch with someone who
can. I would love to play like Johnny Gimble, but you and I both
know that's impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting your response, I remain, George F. Nance.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as of this day, I must say I have not heard a word back
from him,'' Nance said.
</P>
<P>
   So he started teaching himself. A note here, a note there, until
his wife saw a notice in the newspaper about a ``jam session'' at
Lacy-Lakeview Community Center about a year-and-a-half ago. There
he met Johnny Bradshaw, who agreed to take him on as a pupil.
</P>
<P>
   He learns melodies by taping the notes to the fiddle. The notes
on the strings spell the word ``AGED,'' Nance chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   He tries to practice two hours a day, but most days he just does
as much as he can, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can play a few notes that sound good, I just add to it
some more that may not sound so good,'' he said. ``It's like
building a building. Just a few blocks at a time and eventually
you'll get the thing finished.''
</P>
<P>
   He now has a repertoire of more than 15 melodies _ mostly old
hymn tunes he recognizes.
</P>
<P>
   Inside his notebook of tunes is taped a saying he said gives him
inspiration: ``No matter what you achieve in life, it takes a lot
less work to be a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance still can't read music, and his fingers, wrinkled and
spotted with age, don't move as quickly as they would if he were
younger. But he prefers his method of playing by heart.
</P>
<P>
   He said playing the fiddle has been good for his heart, too. He
hasn't had any serious health problems since he started playing
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this feeds my soul,'' he said. ``It gives me
strength and inspires me to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone else who might feel it's too late to fulfill a
lifelong dream, Nance said to start before it's too late. Then be
willing to have patience, take time and be persistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start now,'' he said. ``Don't worry about money or anything.
Do what you can in your own way. Do not put it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance pulls his fiddle and bow out of the case and rests it on
his left shoulder, below the patches of silver hair that peek out
of his ``1 Grandpa'' baseball cap. He announces he's going to play
``Rubber Dolly,'' a song he used to sing on the schoolbus when he
was young.
</P>
<P>
   As he starts to strum out the tinny melody, he taps the toe of
his worn-out left brown boot, which is hardly visible underneath
his oversized denim OshKosh overalls. It's easy to imagine him
playing the tune as a child, as if he hadn't had to wait until he
was 73 to fulfill his dream of playing the fiddle.
</P>
<P>
   After he's done, Louise Nance sits down in a chair across from
him in the living room and looks at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may never play in Carnegie Hall,'' she says. ``But he sure
does like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
