<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FREETHROW-DOCTOR0619-     06-18 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREETHROW-DOCTOR0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World's greatest free-throw shooter
 &HT;    By Dwayne Bray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dr. Tom Amberry, a 77-year-old retired California
podiatrist, woke up Thursday morning, headed to a local gym and
promptly knocked down 496 of 500 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not for this good doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad day,'' he grouses by phone from his Long Beach,
Calif., home. ``Yesterday, I was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Amberry is known as ``the world's greatest free-throw shooter.''
In 1993, he shot his way into the ``Guinness Book of Records'' by
sinking 2,750 straight free throws. In 1996, he co-authored the
book ``Free Throw: 7 Steps to Success at the Free Throw Line''
(HarperPerennial, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   With those credentials, he prefers to talk about the four misses
rather than the 496 conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sinking them and the minute you start to thinking you're
in trouble, you are,'' he says. ``I was thinking about things not
pertaining to what I was doing. Like my wife gave me orders to go
get her some baby spinach and some zucchini. That's how I missed
those four shots.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mental game, free-throw shooting is.
</P>
<P>
   That's the world's most-decorated free-throw shooter's message
to Los Angeles Lakers he-man center Shaquille O'Neal, the world's
most dominant basketball player who has a knack for misfiring from
the 15-foot stripe.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal bricked 48 percent of his shots from the charity stripe
during the regular season. Compare that to the stats of other
all-star big men: San Antonio's David Robinson (72.6 percent), New
York's Patrick Ewing (73 percent), Minnesota's Kevin Garnett (76.5
percent) and the Spurs' Tim Duncan (76 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In Games 2 and 3 of the NBA finals, Shaq missed an incredible 31
of 52 freebies, and his feebleness at the line has become a major
story line in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer at the pro summer league in Long Beach, Amberry awed
players, coaches and executives of NBA teams with a foul-shooting
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attempted 50 shots, and I made 50,'' he says. ``The Lakers
and Celtics and all their front office personnel and their coaches
, including (Lakers coach Phil) Jackson, were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olden Polynice (Utah Jazz, 31 percent free-throw shooter)
said, 'Doc, I sure would love to be able to shoot free throws like
you.' But he never asked me to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice is not alone. Millionaire NBA stars aren't willing to
set aside their pride and allow a graying foot doctor to teach them
how to put the ball in the net. A few even mock Amberry, contending
it's easy to sink free throws in a non-game situation. But to hit
2,750 of them?
</P>
<P>
   Amberry has taught at clinics in Tokyo, Hong Kong and Australia.
And, says wife Helen, ``I don't think he's missed a state in the
U.S. He's been everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   His prized pupil to date has been Kansas' center Eric Chenowith,
a 40 percent foul shooter in high school who finished last season
fourth best in the Big 12 with 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Amberry says he could do the same for Shaq. But the Lakers
haven't come calling. He sighs, ``The Lakers know who I am. But I'm
not really in their loop. I'm not in the clique.''
</P>
<P>
   Amberry says O'Neal's problems are mostly mental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have him focus only on the shot,'' Amberry says. ``Putting
the ball in the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Amberry suggests players square up at the line, bounce the ball
three times with the inflation hole facing up and hold the ball
with your thumb in the groove and your third finger pointing at the
inflation hole.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggest these mechanics: shooting elbow in, knees bent,
eyes on a target and good follow through.
</P>
<P>
   With Amberry's success, you would think NBA teams would be
knocking down this guy's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ego,'' Amberry says, ``is the drug of stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
