<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEDARIS-INTERVIEW0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sedaris comes clean
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More funny essays by David Sedaris. What else do
you need to know?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an explanation of the title?
</P>
<P>
   ``Me Talk Pretty One Day,'' also an essay, is Sedaris'
approximation of how adult language students sounded in French
class. Sedaris attended such a class when he and his boyfriend,
Hugh, first moved to Paris two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Every bit as funny as ``Naked,'' his 1997 book, this collection
describes Sedaris' IBM father, while the earlier one gave more
attention to his mother and grandmother. ``Me Talk Pretty One Day''
begins with deadpan essays about David's childhood speech therapy
and his guitar lessons taught by a midget, then moves on to
adulthood in New York and, eventually to Paris, where he still
lives. The humor relies on his offhand voice and the piling up of
the absurd details of ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   Sedaris talked to us by phone from Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You say you come back twice a year to lecture in theaters and
to our nation's young people?
</P>
<P>
   A: Those are the appearances that work out the worst, talking to
our nation's young people. I do better talking to our nation's old
people. Talking to our nation's middle-aged people, I tend to do
much better.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: People in college don't know who I am. Even when I'm in a
college town, the people who come aren't in college.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what's the gap between you and today's young people?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, gosh. I guess I never really thought about it. I'm 43.
I'm not young. I'm not hip. I'm not with it. I just try to write
about myself, and then people who are interested in what I have to
say about myself, you know, come.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think you'll stay in France?
</P>
<P>
   A: Um, yeah. I don't know how long. I Iike being a foreigner,
and I like not knowing what's going on. I like living with a
constant state of anxiety because it makes me feel more alive. I
tend to write better if I'm writing from a point of view where
people are giving me a hard time and where everything is a
struggle. . . . Well, I'm so set in my ways and so completely
resistant to changing anything because the world will fall apart if
I don't do my laundry on Sunday at 6 o'clock. If I do it at 7
o'clock, God knows what might happen. Or if I did it on Monday . .
. I can't take that chance. I've just really changed a lot since I
moved to France. Like I don't have glasses now . . . And sometimes
I do my laundry on a Tuesday. I've had so many changes in my
schedule and my environment that I think _ well, what if I made
even more? That might not sound very significant, but it's pretty
significant for me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are you working on now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have a play that's going to open in the fall. My sister and
I write plays together. So it's in the fall. Neither one of us has
any idea what it's about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You write about your father this time. Do you think you'll
ever exhaust your family as a subject?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think I have. So I've started in on my boyfriend's family .
. .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
