<HEADER>
A7551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GREIG-FILES0619-COX     06-18 1879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-FILES0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting ready for a summer trip
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Packing up your cares and woes is invariably
easier than packing for any trip. Ever since Adam loaded up his fig
leaves and half-eaten apple to hit the road, packing has been a
challenge. Think Moses wandered the desert for 40 years toting only
a backpack and shod in Tevas? Do you realize the astronauts are
allowed only 3 pounds of items in their PPKs (personal preference
kit) on a mission?
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to exotic locales does not mean going without one's
Lancome, orthopedic walking shoes, favorite jammies or the latest
best-seller. So travel has inspired the design of various carts,
barrels, trunks and suitcases to lug life's accoutrements.
</P>
<P>
   And now that wheels have been added to suitcases, even the
tiniest of travelers can drag a bag heavier than Jimmy Hoffa's
shoes onto an airline. The kitchen sink must be in some of those
bags. (My husband's rule: If you can't lift it into the overhead
bin alone, you should not be allowed to bring it on.)
</P>
<P>
   When packing, do you make sure every piece of clothing has at
least two uses? Appreciate that lace or silk underwear dries faster
than cotton? Know what interweaving a wardrobe means? Wonder what
to look for in good luggage? Daydream what you can buy besides a
loaded Jetta or PT Cruiser for $23,000?
</P>
<P>
   No?
</P>
<P>
   Then this edition of the Greig Files holds a few surprises.
Planning a trip? Read before you pack. Your clothes and your
traveling companions will thank you.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS THE FIRST RULE OF PACKING?
</P>
<P>
   Pack light. Followed closely by the second rule _ pack light.
</P>
<P>
   Packing light means freedom from tipping bell men, searching for
porters and making a fool of yourself as you compete for space on
trains and planes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most seasoned traveler will reduce the load after this
travel test. Pack your bags and carry them around the block (and up
a flight of stairs if possible). Return home. I guarantee that you
will find it easy to toss a few things back in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE DO I START?
</P>
<P>
   Make a list and designate a place to pack (dining room table,
bed, couch). Make sure both the luggage and clothes are clean
before you pack. Lay out the items on the list. Limit yourself to
what you need. For most people, this means one suitcase and one
carry-on bag. Remember, over-packing leaves no room for souvenirs
and strains luggage as well as backs.
</P>
<P>
   Carry-on items are those you cannot do without (toiletries,
itinerary, tickets, passport, medications). Some travelers add
anything needed to spend one night _ in case of car trouble or
flight delays. Simply grab the carry-on or daypack. No need to
disturb the main luggage containing clothing essentials and
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   ARE THERE DRUGSTORES ON BORA BORA?
</P>
<P>
   You bet. Wherever you are going _ barring the moon or Antarctica
_ supplies (socks to shampoo) are available. Why weigh yourself
down with ones from home? Some intrepid travelers pack a few almost
obsolete items (T-shirts or lingerie on its last legs) with the
intention of donating or ditching them along the way. Lightens the
load and creates an opportunity to make a local purchase _ batik
shirt, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Hotels, trains and airplanes offer basics such as mending kits
and mouthwash. Make the most of these freebies and leave the
20-ounce botanical face wash at home.
</P>
<P>
   IS THERE A METHOD TO PACKING MADNESS?
</P>
<P>
   Yep. Layer and roll.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the items on the ``to pack'' list? Place heavier things
such as shoes and appliances along the spine of the suitcase. Layer
the clothing beginning with the last day's outfit on the bottom and
continue upward to the first day's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Lay slacks horizontally across the suitcase. Turn jackets inside
out, folding arms inward before placing them vertically (collar
opposite the handle) in the suitcase. Interweave plastic bags (used
for wet items or dirty clothes) or tissue paper to reduce
wrinkling. Add rolled items (robes, shorts, skirts). After layering
clothing and accessories, fold the slacks legs and jacket bottoms
over the top of the stack in a weaving pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff shoes with socks, underwear and belts.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SHOULD BE ROLLED?
</P>
<P>
   Almost anything can be rolled for packing ease. Rolled clothing
has a good chance of arriving without wrinkles. Who wants to look
like an unmade bed on vacation?
</P>
<P>
   Lay skirts flat and fold sides inward to create a rectangle.
Roll from the hem to the waistband. Place a shirt face down on the
bed and fold sleeves inward. Roll from the shirttail to the collar,
ending with the collar on top.
</P>
<P>
   THINK EMPRESS EUGENIE REALIZED WHAT SHE STARTED?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. The empress, the love of Napoleon III's life, made
the career of the young Louis Vuitton. During France's Second
Empire, the women of the noblesse sought Vuitton for his talent _
building and packing custom trunks. When Vuitton was dubbed sole
trunkmaker to the Empress, he was able to open his own shop close
to Paris' Place Vendome.
</P>
<P>
   In this shop, Vuitton revolutionized packing by redesigning the
trunk. The traditional barrel-topped stagecoach trunk was flattened
by Vuitton. Voila! Several trunks could be stacked _ one on top of
the other_ allowing dukes and duchi to wander the globe with more
finery than ever. (How could Vuitton have known he simultaneously
provided every college student with a coffee table?)
</P>
<P>
   WHAT MAKES VUITTON'S LUGGAGE SO EXPENSIVE?
</P>
<P>
   Could be poplar wood used to construct the trunks (lightweight
and sturdy) or the signature monogram cotton canvas or the brass _
or gold-plated _ hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling piece of luggage? The Pegase, a carry-on for
$1,260. The most popular trunk? The Wardrobe, for a mere $19,100.
The Vuitton trunk containing a secretary (furniture, not person)
goes for $26,600.
</P>
<P>
   Even Imelda Marcos might balk at spending $22,900 for the
armoire trunk, designed to tote shoes from continent to continent.
The armoire holds about 1ned to Some Persons Which Have Transported
Themselves from England to Virginia'' _ sort of a ``Colonizing for
Dummies,'' if you will.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU HAVE ROOM . . .
</P>
<P>
   Card-size calculator (figure exchange rates and restaurant
bills)
</P>
<P>
   Flip-flops (shower shoes)
</P>
<P>
   Birthday candle or other small candle
</P>
<P>
   (fix zippers, light in a pinch)
</P>
<P>
   Rubber door stop (wedge under hotel room doors for added
security)
</P>
<P>
   Small folding scissors or pen knife
</P>
<P>
   (uses too numerous to mention)
</P>
<P>
   Moleskin (blister repair)
</P>
<P>
   Dryer sheets (suitcase deodorant also reduces static cling)
</P>
<P>
   Plastic sheet or large garbage bag (protects from bed bugs or
sudden rainstorms)
</P>
<P>
   Large envelopes (mail info home)
</P>
<P>
   Small flashlight (under pillow in case the electricity or your
spouse goes out)
</P>
<P>
   Plastic bags that seal
</P>
<P>
   (for wet laundry, bathing suits)
</P>
<P>
   Folding umbrella
</P>
<P>
   THAT WILL BE ALL, JEEVES
</P>
<P>
   How can you tell if your traveling companion has a butler from
the way a suitcase is packed? Is the woman's clean lingerie bundled
in white tissue and tied with a colorful ribbon for easy
identification? Have shoe heels been wrapped in protective tissue
or shoe bagsHas tissue paper been stuffed in suit jacket sleeves to
reduce wrinkling Are breakables swathed in bubble wrap?
</P>
<P>
   BAGGING THE PERFECT BAG
</P>
<P>
   Construction: Hard, semi-soft or soft-sided? Hard-sided luggage
protects contents and has the added security of built-in locks and
handles. Semi-soft cases are lighter and offer some impact
protection. Soft-sided cases are the most expandable and
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   Leather exterior: Genuine leather (top made of all grain) is
durable, strong and made from the outermost layer of the animal
skin. Split leather is the underlayer split from the top grain.
Processed leather is one type of leather made to look like another,
such as faux alligator. Bonded or laminated leather is pulverized
scrap leather bonded with glue
</P>
<P>
   Fabric exterior: Nylon comes in a variety of thicknesses (known
as the denier). Durable, tight, construction nylon should be a
minimum of 400 denier or supported by a thicker material. Vinyl is
stain-resistant and often treated to look like leather. Molded
materials are poured into forms to make hard, seamless cases, which
may be covered with vinyl. Molded suitcases are very durable.
</P>
<P>
   Edges: Luggage protection and style are provided by edges which
may be turned (where materials meet is turned completely over all
edges), bound (separate material sewn completely over all edges),
welt (material sewn between seams and covers all edges) or
burnished (all edges cut off evenly and polished).
</P>
<P>
   Handles: The most durable handle is mounted with screws or
rivets to the suitcase frame or metal base and recessed for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware and accessories: Shoulder straps should be reinforced
and attached at stress points with protective padding. Zippers may
be metal molded or coil. The more screws or rivets used to mount a
lock, the more secure the lock. Check wheels for stability and
handling. Examine special features such as accordion side-pleats
for flexibility, outside pockets and wet packs.
</P>
<P>
   PACKING POINTERS
</P>
<P>
   Do not pack the same day you leave.
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt, leave it out.
</P>
<P>
   Never pack brand-new shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Bring less; wash more often.
</P>
<P>
   Get a pedicure and pack sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Do not over or under pack _ your clothes will wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Stick to wrinkle-resistant fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Bring clothes to layer and mix for warmth and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Unpack as soon as you arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Share items (who needs two hair dryers?!).
</P>
<P>
   Wear any jewelry you take (except costume) all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Wear bulkier garments on travel days.
</P>
<P>
   Pack just one of anything _ except underwear and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Include your itinerary and a contact number (office, not home)
in case you and your bag are separated.
</P>
<P>
   CHECK PLEASE: WHAT THE AIRLINES ALLOW
</P>
<P>
   All inch counts are luggage circumference, not length. Some
flights are subject to stricter regulations. Always check with the
airline before you load those 16 tons.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines
</P>
<P>
   (800) 433-7300
</P>
<P>
   Two carry-on, one checked (or vice-versa _ three total)
</P>
<P>
   Carry-on: 23-by-13-by-9 under seat dimensions; no more than 45
inches/40 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Checked: No more than 62 inches/ 70 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines
</P>
<P>
   (800) 231-0856
</P>
<P>
   One carry-on, three checked (four total)
</P>
<P>
   Carry-on: No more than 45 inches/40 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Checked: Your three bags _ one no more than 62 inches, the
second less than 55 inches, the third less than 45 inches _ can
weigh no more than 70 lbs. each.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines (800) 221-1212 Two carry-on; one checked (or
vice-versa _ three total)
</P>
<P>
   Carry-on: 22-by-9-by-14; 45 inches/40 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Checked: 62 inches/70 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines (800) 435-9792
</P>
<P>
   Two carry-on; three checked (five total)
</P>
<P>
   Carry-on: 16-by-10-by-24
</P>
<P>
   50 inches/no weight limit
</P>
<P>
   Checked: 62 inches/70 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines (800) 241-6522
</P>
<P>
   Two carry-on; two checked (four total)
</P>
<P>
   Carry-on: 22-by-14-by-9; 45 inches/combined weight 50 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Checked: 62 inches/70 lbs.
</P>
