<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surround sound is improving
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At first our home televisions and radios pumped
their sound through a single speaker. The speaker count jumped to
two for stereo, then four, and for the past couple years it's been
six speakers for 5.1 channel Dolby Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Now the latest is Dolby Digital 6.1 Extended Surround, which
requires seven speakers to bring the movie theater sound experience
home.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood America, a California-based home and car audio
specialist, won an Innovation Award at the International Consumer
Electronics Show in January for its design of the Newcastle R-956
receiver, which is capable of reproducing the 6.1 channel movie
theater sound environment at home.
</P>
<P>
   Dolby Digital 5.1 channel programming divides the soundtrack of
a movie into five surrounding channels plus a sixth channel to send
bass tones to a subwoofer.
</P>
<P>
   Theatrical movies recorded in that format include ``Star Wars,''
``Episode One: The Phantom Menace;'' ``The Bone Collector;'' ``The
Haunting;'' ``End of Days'' and ``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The R-956 has six 120-watt-per-channel discrete amplifiers to
drive its speakers. The receiver also features an on-screen
display, a dedicated audiovisual output to send signals to a home
theater in a second room and digital outputs for a compact disc or
mini disc recorder.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver has not yet been shipped to audiovisual equipment
retailers, but within the next week you'll be able to order it
directly from Sherwood for $1,499.95. For additional information,
you can visit the Sherwood America Web site at
www.sherwoodamerica.com.
</P>
<P>
   To place an order, call (714) 870-5100 or e-mail
sales(at)sherwood
</P>
<P>
   usa.com.
</P>
<P>
   And the betting can start now on whether the next movie sound
wrinkle (Super Digital 8.2, perhaps?) will add speakers on the
ceiling or on the floor directly under each seat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
