   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-III (New Haven, Conn.) _ Born at the earliest fringe of
the baby boom, Bush was pressed during his years at Yale to take
sides in the great battles then unfolding over politics, civil
rights, drugs and music. Mostly he was a noncombatant in those
upheavals, but when forced to choose he ultimately retreated to the
values and ideals established by his parents' generation. Unlike
others of his generation, like Clinton or Gore, Bush never wore his
hair long, agonized over Vietnam, wrestled with existentialism or
cranked up Rolling Stones songs to annoy his parents (instead of
hard rock music, he listened to soul). Even today, Bush thunders in
his stump speeches against boomer-style self-indulgence and appeals
for a ``responsibility era'' that in some respects sounds like the
1950s; he likes values as clean-cut as his hair. 4000 words. By
Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-VP (Austin, Texas) _ With little more than a month to go
before Gov. George W. Bush, the de facto Republican presidential
nominee, settles on the person with whom he wants to share the
ticket, the list of possibilities seems to be getting shorter. But
that does not mean it is getting a whole lot clearer, because Bush
is holding his cards so close to the vest that even his most
trusted advisers insist they have not been able to sneak a peek.
1150 words. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Washington) _ New details on Gore's Social Security
proposals emerge in a briefing; meantime, Bill Daley, Gore's new
campaign manager, goes on the Sunday talk show circuit to plant the
flag, something his predecessor, Tony Coelho, could not do because
he was afraid to be asked about his financial problems. 1000 words.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MEDIA (Scranton, Pa.) _ A series of incidents last week
illustrates what is, in the view of some Democrats and Republicans
alike, Al Gore's surprisingly tough struggle to get out a message
that clicks with voters. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   COVERDALE-PROFILE (Washington) _ Ask just about anyone in the
U.S. Senate and they will say this about Paul Coverdell, the
Republican senator from Georgia: If you want something done, and
done well, and you don't want the person hogging all the glory,
call Coverdell. It is one reason he ascended into the Senate
Republican leadership so quickly, as a mere freshman. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
