<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arm of the law stops at branch of tree
 &HT;    By Brett Thurman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I hope you can answer my question. Our neighbor's tree has
branches that grow into our yard, and into a pine tree growing in
our yard. It dumps leaves and branches we have to clean up. We are
an older couple, so the branches are too high for us to clip off by
ourselves. We have talked to these neighbors several times about
this problem but they refuse to do anything about it. Is there
anything we can do to make them clip these branches off?
</P>
<P>
   A: When your Realtor told you these neighbors would ``grow on
you,'' this isn't what you had hoped for, was it?
</P>
<P>
   Before we branch into more bad puns that will only leaf you
hanging from a limb, let's go over some basics of what might be
called ``neighbor law.''
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of issues that can arise from neighbors
owning property adjoining or near to one another. The issues very
generally can be classified according to whether the neighbors
themselves are the active agent in making something move across
property boundaries, or whether Mother Nature is really to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Wind, water, and most growing things move naturally around in
nature without much regard to the property boundaries we humans
might draw. The law takes this into account. You can't usually hold
your neighbors responsible for such natural things.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, you might reasonably expect that your property
line will affect how your neighbors act. And the law will back you
up if the parties next door are too loud (and you are not invited),
their dog keeps chasing you into your house, etc. But it is
unreasonable for you to expect your property line to change how
Mother Nature acts.
</P>
<P>
   Even the law knows it is not nice to fool with Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Now this is very general advice. And there can be a world of
difference between a new, poisonous plant positioned a few inches
from the property line, and a 100-year- old oak whose 50-foot
branches hang 10 feet over.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, neighbors are expected to know trees sometimes
express shocking indifference to property lines when the chance
arises to spread its roots or branches, shed an old branch or drop
its leaves in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you get the benefit of some shade from a tree you don't
own, so can you be burdened with some leaf and branch removal from
that same tree. Just be glad its roots are not in your plumbing
(which also gives you little or no recourse against the tree's
``owner.'')
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time no court is going to make your neighbors do any
branch removal they do not wish to do. If the tree is dead and
presents a significant threat of damage from falling branches, then
under certain circumstances you can call the police or go to court
and force the hazard be abated. In obvious hazard situations, you
might even be able so sue for damages that might result.
</P>
<P>
   In most situations you are free to perform (or pay to have
performed) routine trimming and maintenance on overhanging
branches. But be careful. You could be liable to the tree's owners
if the maintenance performed is not approved by them and actually
results in damage to their tree or the value of their property
generally.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting with an experienced tree-trimming company is a good
idea on how proceed here before taking any action. They usually
know how to manage the issues that arise in these situations.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Thurman is general counsel for Cox Ohio Publishing. If you
have a general legal question, send it to him c/o Dayton Daily
News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton 45402 or via e-mail to
brettthurman(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
