<HEADER>
A7584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FREETHROW-DOCTOR0619-     06-18 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREETHROW-DOCTOR0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World's greatest free-throw shooter
 &HT;    By Dwayne Bray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dr. Tom Amberry, a 77-year-old retired California
podiatrist, woke up Thursday morning, headed to a local gym and
promptly knocked down 496 of 500 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not for this good doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad day,'' he grouses by phone from his Long Beach,
Calif., home. ``Yesterday, I was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Amberry is known as ``the world's greatest free-throw shooter.''
In 1993, he shot his way into the ``Guinness Book of Records'' by
sinking 2,750 straight free throws. In 1996, he co-authored the
book ``Free Throw: 7 Steps to Success at the Free Throw Line''
(HarperPerennial, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   With those credentials, he prefers to talk about the four misses
rather than the 496 conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sinking them and the minute you start to thinking you're
in trouble, you are,'' he says. ``I was thinking about things not
pertaining to what I was doing. Like my wife gave me orders to go
get her some baby spinach and some zucchini. That's how I missed
those four shots.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mental game, free-throw shooting is.
</P>
<P>
   That's the world's most-decorated free-throw shooter's message
to Los Angeles Lakers he-man center Shaquille O'Neal, the world's
most dominant basketball player who has a knack for misfiring from
the 15-foot stripe.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal bricked 48 percent of his shots from the charity stripe
during the regular season. Compare that to the stats of other
all-star big men: San Antonio's David Robinson (72.6 percent), New
York's Patrick Ewing (73 percent), Minnesota's Kevin Garnett (76.5
percent) and the Spurs' Tim Duncan (76 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In Games 2 and 3 of the NBA finals, Shaq missed an incredible 31
of 52 freebies, and his feebleness at the line has become a major
story line in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer at the pro summer league in Long Beach, Amberry awed
players, coaches and executives of NBA teams with a foul-shooting
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attempted 50 shots, and I made 50,'' he says. ``The Lakers
and Celtics and all their front office personnel and their coaches
, including (Lakers coach Phil) Jackson, were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olden Polynice (Utah Jazz, 31 percent free-throw shooter)
said, 'Doc, I sure would love to be able to shoot free throws like
you.' But he never asked me to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice is not alone. Millionaire NBA stars aren't willing to
set aside their pride and allow a graying foot doctor to teach them
how to put the ball in the net. A few even mock Amberry, contending
it's easy to sink free throws in a non-game situation. But to hit
2,750 of them?
</P>
<P>
   Amberry has taught at clinics in Tokyo, Hong Kong and Australia.
And, says wife Helen, ``I don't think he's missed a state in the
U.S. He's been everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   His prized pupil to date has been Kansas' center Eric Chenowith,
a 40 percent foul shooter in high school who finished last season
fourth best in the Big 12 with 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Amberry says he could do the same for Shaq. But the Lakers
haven't come calling. He sighs, ``The Lakers know who I am. But I'm
not really in their loop. I'm not in the clique.''
</P>
<P>
   Amberry says O'Neal's problems are mostly mental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have him focus only on the shot,'' Amberry says. ``Putting
the ball in the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Amberry suggests players square up at the line, bounce the ball
three times with the inflation hole facing up and hold the ball
with your thumb in the groove and your third finger pointing at the
inflation hole.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggest these mechanics: shooting elbow in, knees bent,
eyes on a target and good follow through.
</P>
<P>
   With Amberry's success, you would think NBA teams would be
knocking down this guy's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ego,'' Amberry says, ``is the drug of stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ENGLE-EQUESTRIAN0     06-18 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ENGLE-EQUESTRIAN0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everything riding on this one
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, N.J. _ The 2000 U.S. Olympic Trials for show jumping
begin Wednesday at a beautifully manicured equestrian center in New
Jersey, but that is far too tight a focus for a story on Margie
Goldstein Engle. Her personal Olympic trials, and tribulations too,
began eight years ago with a quirky injury to a trusted teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Even now Engle displays the name of that teammate on the
personalized Florida license plate of her car, a red Cadillac
dusted white by the dirt roads of Wellington's horse country.
Saluut II is the name, and their partnership as rider and Grand
Prix mount seemed destined for a shot at Olympic gold at the 1992
Barcelona Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great horse,'' said Engle, five times the American
Grandprix Association rider of the year, ``but I've learned that
there are a lot of things you can't control in this sport. Your
horse could step on something in training or get an abscess or go
colicky on you. We've got chiropractors for the animals and
acupuncturists and ultrasound and magnetic blankets and massage
therapy, but still you can do everything right and have it come out
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Saluut II, living out a luxurious retirement in
Maryland these days, it was an injury sustained in what can only be
described here as a breeding accident. Four years later, while
Engle was leading the early stages of the Olympic team selection
process, her best horse, Caribbean Queen, got hurt while being
transported in a van.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there was that other little accident, the one Engle
doesn't bring up herself because it involved her own physical
problems rather than those of her beloved horses. In 1992 she broke
several ribs and had a deep gash torn in her back by a mount that
fell during a competition and got tangled up in a fence trying to
regain its feet. At 104 pounds, Engle doesn't stand much of a
chance when something unexpected causes a 1,200-pound animal to
lose its regal Grand Prix bearing and leap into a royal panic.
</P>
<P>
   TRIALS PROCESS CAN BE TRYING
</P>
<P>
   Engle, 41, may get several more shots at representing the U.S.
at the Olympics, as winter Wellington resident Norman Dello Joio
did with a bronze-medal performance at the 1992 Barcelona Games.
One unsabotaged run through the six-week selection process this
summer would be an important victory in itself, however. About 90
horses are qualified to begin the trials Wednesday at Gladstone,
N.J. In the course of five days the field will be whittled to 12
horses, a group by August will yield four Olympic horse-rider
combinations and one alternate following a series of further
competitions in California.
</P>
<P>
   Riders may enter more than one horse and gain a place in the
points standings on each of them. For that reason, Engle may go the
trials with as many as five horses, a numerical advantage in terms
of qualifying chances but not, in her mind, the most desirable
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather have one really top horse,'' she said, ``than
four that are about equal. You could have a situation where you
have a clean run every day of the competition but still don't
qualify because you did it on a different horse each time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidden Creek's Perin, a young horse newly acquired by
Wellington's Michael Polaski for Engle to ride, might be the best
choice, but only if Engle feels totally comfortable with the
communication between them. Hidden Creek's Alvaretto is a safer
choice and a steady competitor but may not be able to match Perin's
raw power on the jumps. When the challenge is to clear 15-20
obstacles without a touch, some nearly 6 feet tall, athletic
ability cannot be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   LIVES HERE YEAR-ROUND
</P>
<P>
   Engle, a Wellington resident for 10 years and a product of Dade
County's public school system, is a rarity among elite show jumpers
in that she keeps her year-round headquarters in South Florida
rather than leaving at the end of the winter equestrian season. The
business degree she earned at Florida International University
helps in the running of Gladewind Farms, its 30-stall stable and a
staff of 14 trainers. Margie's father, Irvin Goldstein, a retired
CPA, does the books. Husband Steve Engle, a veterinarian who
originally met Margie at a horse show, is readily available for
consultation.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a team, but in the end it all comes down to Engle's
ability to steer a horse faultlessly through a virtual minefield as
a running scoreboard clock demands brevity and bravery in equal
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Few thrive in this environment. Engle lives for it. She's been
living for it since elementary school, when a classmate invited her
to a riding party. Margie loved it so much at the horse barn that
she begged to return, earning permission to do odd jobs, riding a
bus home at the end of the day when carpool rides fell through.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was laughing the other day,'' Engle said, ``because she
remembered the day I called home all excited to tell her that I got
to muck out the horses' stalls. All I wanted was to be around the
horses. The trainers used to kid me that I would ride a donkey if
they'd let me. I actually never owned my own horse until my early
20s.''
</P>
<P>
   That little girl's dream could reach its fullest expression at
Sydney this September, but only if she makes it through the U.S.
trials. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
