<P>
   AIR-CONSOLIDATE (Undated) _ Major airlines argue that
consolidating into three mega-carriers in America (and an equal
number of global giants) would be good for consumers. They say the
mergers would create coast-to-coast airlines offering more
destinations and more competition than any of the six major
American airlines. But studies of individual airports have shown
that fares increase when the number of airlines serving an airport
decreases. Now, with customer complaints at an all-time high, and
the industry heading into what looks like another summer of
record-breaking delays, many industry analysts, politicians and
consumer advocates question whether airline consolidation will
benefit consumers. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PARENTS (Undated) _ In the world of Internet startups,
where many chief executives are under thirty and a labor shortage
continues even as some dot-coms fail, not only are dot-commers
hiring siblings and spouses, but, in more than a few cases, they
are recruiting their own parents. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-TEXTING (Manila, Philippines) _ All over the
Philippines, people are ``texting'' _ exchanging short typed
messages over cell phones. Texting is possible on most digital
networks and is gaining popularity in Europe and a few East Asian
nations. But nowhere does it seem as popular as in the Philippines,
where it has spawned not only a verb but an entire subculture,
complete with its own vocabulary, etiquette and tactical uses. By
Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   TALENT-AGENT (Los Angeles) _ Since taking the president's job at
the Beverly Hills headquarters of William Morris last August, the
talent agent Jim Wiatt has not just sought to fix William Morris
but has shaken up the talent agency business with a relentless
effort to lure stars from his old employer, only two miles away.
Even by the brass-knuckle standards of two former William Morris
agents, Michael Ovitz and Ron Meyer, who used similar tactics 20
years ago to turn Creative Artists into the town's dominant agency,
Wiatt's efforts have been surprising, dramatic and fast-moving. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MESSAGES (San Francisco) _ Despite the explosive
popularity of instant-messaging programs on the Internet, it became
apparent last week that one facet of the service may not be instant
at all: It may be a year or more before users of competing
instant-message services can send missives to one another. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL-CANADA (Undated) _ Nortel, the Canadian
telecommunications equipment giant, has become a company for the
Americas. It is growing so rapidly outside Canada that doubts are
being expressed at home about its corporate citizenship. Its
headquarters remains in Brampton, Ontario, but more of its 75,000
employees live and work south of the Canada-U.S. border than north
of it. And these days, just 9 percent of its $18 billion in
revenues comes from Canada. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   PC-FUTURE (San Francisco) _ As Microsoft prepares to announce
its Next Generation Windows Services initiative this week, an
influential computer scientist is circulating a thesis that must be
music to Bill Gates' ears. Countering the industry's common wisdom
that we're entering the post-PC era, David Galernter of Yale
University says there are still many years left in the desktop PC.
And some other serious thinkers agree. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-WEB-TV (Undated) _ America Online will announce its answer
to Web TV. What's the plan and what are its chances? By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-SECURITY (Undated) _ The latest on the security breach at
AOL: AOL continues to say that the incident last week in which
several hundred records on users were obtained by outsiders caused
no damage and was an isolated incident. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Online sweepstakes are migrating
with increasing frequency from informational Web sites to the front
pages of Internet merchants. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Soon, perhaps within days,
researchers expect to say they have completed the decadelong
project of mapping the human genome. Stand by for the New Genomics
to become the next big thing in the New Economics. By Tim Race.
</P>
<P>
   COINSTAR-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A new campaign for Coinstar, the
nation's largest manufacturer of self-service coin-counting
machines, uses humor to exhort consumers to dump the contents of
their piggy banks into the company's machines and become empowered
by their ``new found'' money. By Courtney Kane.
