<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HEARTLAND-OHIO0619-CO     06-18 2490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-OHIO0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohioans know how fish feel
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner and Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Harry Ruzicka's quiet morning on a pier in
Sandusky Bay is interrupted by a tug on his fishing line and the
thought of giving his vote to Al Gore or George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ruzicka, struggling a bit to land a big sheephead, struggles
even more over who he wants to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush comes from a good family, but I think he'll ruin Social
Security and do nothing to make health care better,'' Ruzicka said.
``Gore will do more for the average guy, but he'll have us paying
more taxes and he's as real as my $3 bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picking a president is about like what I'm doing with these
fish, trying to figure out which one to keep and which one to toss
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruzicka is 89, a lifelong independent and the kind of guy who
liked Harry Truman because he wasn't afraid to curse on the radio.
He has voted for 18 presidents, some Democrat, some Republican, and
this year he isn't sure which way to cast.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio voters like Ruzicka are the real prize catch of campaign
2000. They bring with them 21 electoral votes and are the reason
Vice President Gore, the Democrat, and Texas Gov. Bush, the
Republican, will continue barnstorming the state over the next five
months.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do early polls show the race getting closer, history
shows Buckeye voters are as fickle as the fish in Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1932, the first presidential election of the Great
Depression, Ohio has voted Republican nine times, and Democratic
seven. President Clinton took Ohio twice, but in 1992 against
incumbent George Bush, he won by only 2 percentage points. If not
for third-party candidate Ross Perot, Clinton might have lost Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   This year's fight for the White House could be even closer.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has ever captured the presidency without winning
Ohio. And the Democrats haven't won the Buckeye State in three
consecutive elections since Franklin Roosevelt did it in 1932, '36
and '40.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't paying attention right now. It's summer, we
haven't gotten to the conventions,'' said Allan Lichtman, chairman
of American University's Department of History. ``But both Bush and
Gore are paying a lot of attention to Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with more than 100 likely voters across Ohio found
few beyond the fiercely partisan who have already made up their
minds. Ohioans are more likely to say the Reds or the Indians _ not
Bush or Gore _ when asked who will win this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have concerns the candidates can speak to. Tax cuts,
health care, gun issues, abortion rights and deteriorating schools
all were repeatedly mentioned, with one issue, character, cutting
across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my children thinking it's OK to lie or deceive
people,'' said Kelly Vincent, a single mother of two and lab
technician from Dayton. ``I don't care too much about their
politics or what party they are from, I just want a decent man to
be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't have to be perfect, but he should
respect the people who elected him.''
</P>
<P>
   OHIO CONSIDERED NATIONAL BELLWETHER
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is the nation's seventh most populous state and one of its
most culturally diverse. It still has a strong agriculture and
manufacturing base, along with a growing technology sector and some
of the nation's best medical facilities and universities.
</P>
<P>
   It leans slightly Republican, but neither party can take it for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio has long been considered a national bellwether, and for
good reason. In the last century, Ohio voted the same way the
nation voted in 23 of 25 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Republican rule of thumb for winning in Ohio
involved heavily Democratic Cuyahoga County _ but it did not
include winning there. Republicans just had to lose there by fewer
than 100,000 votes, a margin that could be offset by Republican
areas elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Republicans say gains in other metro regions,
including Dayton, mean the 100,000-vote threshold no longer
matters. They can get creamed in Cuyahoga County, according to the
new Republican math, and still carry the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lot more votes to get now in places like Dayton and
Columbus,'' said Ohio Republican Chairman Robert Bennett. ``It's
not all about Cleveland any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County politics illustrate the point. Once
significantly blue collar and solidly Democratic, the county now is
politically balanced, a Republican vote having grown with suburban
development.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, claim new inroads as well, and cite Columbus
Mayor Michael Coleman, the city's first Democratic mayor in 28
years, to prove their point.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft said Ohio voters have become much less
predictable. ``I think the electorate is more volatile and less
historic in its allegiance to either party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Dimora, the Cuyahoga County Democratic chairman and a
county commissioner, knows he's in for a tougher fight this year.
Bush is striking a chord with some traditional Democratic voters,
Dimora said. And he wishes Gore would take it more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore spent nothing here (for the primary). That concerns me
that they are taking this county for granted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Leland, chairman of the Ohio Democratic Party, doesn't
share Dimora's concerns. Leland says Gore and the Democrats won't
take Cuyahoga County or any other area for granted when the
campaign gets rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win this state and win this election by not conceding any
area,'' Leland said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats won't carry Republican Hamilton County, he said, ``but
we might be able to pick up 5,000 votes there. That's the kind of
effort it will take to win a close race like this one.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cuyahoga County holds a big key for Ohio Democrats, then the
key to the county, Dimora said, is solidifying the vote in
Cleveland and getting out early and often to the more ethnic,
inner-ring suburbs such as Parma, Lakewood and Euclid.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-six-year-old Helen McFarland of Brookpark, another of
the blue-collar suburbs, is typical of voters found there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived during the Hoover depression and my Dad pounded it
into our heads,'' McFarland said. ``We almost lost our home. We
went to school with cardboard in our shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad's message: Republicans take care of the rich; everyone else
needs the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland backs Gore for the simple reason he is not Bush.
</P>
<P>
   MANY VOTES IN THE MIDDLE
</P>
<P>
   If McFarland were typical of Ohio voters, there would be no race
here. But Ohio is filled with swing voters who inhabit the
political middle, which is where the presidential fight will really
take place.
</P>
<P>
   Ohioans like Tim Williams, Israel Morales and Charles Buckley
represent Taft's less predictable electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 49, is an assembly line worker at Ford Motor Co.'s
massive engine plant in northeastern Ohio. He voted for Clinton
twice and has considered himself a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, he said, ``(My vote) is still up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't followed either candidate right now because
when you get down to it, there isn't much difference between the
Democrats and the Republicans,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bennett, a political scientist from University of
Cincinnati, said both Bush and Gore are trying to convince Ohio's
moderate and swing voters that they are one of them. Bush is trying
to shake off the conservative image he created to beat Arizona Sen.
John McCain in the primaries; Gore is seen by many as a liberal
environmental and labor union activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing extreme in the Midwest is the extreme middle,''
Bennett said. ``Most people in the Midwest tend to be very moderate
and so these candidates are trying to be what these people want.
Bush has done a better job of getting to these people so far.''
</P>
<P>
   When campaigning in Ohio, Bush has conspicuously gone to urban,
traditionally Democratic neighborhoods, including two Hispanic
areas on Cleveland's west side.
</P>
<P>
   In Clark-Fulton, a historically Italian neighborhood now seeing
an influx of Latinos, Israel Morales has voted for Democrats in
every presidential election except 1988. That year, he backed
Bush's father, former President George W. Bush, and this year he
likes Bush the son.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bush) addresses Hispanic issues more,'' said Morales, 48, a
truck driver who was born in Puerto Rico but has lived in the
United States for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include Bush's position in the custody fight over
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez. Bush criticized the government's armed
intervention to remove Elian from Miami relatives and reunite him
with his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   Downstate in the Perry County seat of New Lexington, a town of
5,100 on the edge of the Wayne National Forest, it would be
inaccurate to call Charles Buckley a swing voter. But he is someone
who's less comfortable than he once was with the party of his
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, 73, is in the midst of a personal transition.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported Republican candidates with his time and money
for years. He crankily calls the ACLU the American Communist
Lawyers Union. He doubts he would vote for Al Gore if Gore ran
unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   But last year the fund-raising letters from Republican
politicians all over the nation started to weigh on his mind. They
came in from California, Kansas, Wisconsin . . . he stopped
counting at 280 letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My postman said 'You're kind of popular,' `` Buckley said. ``I
said, no, they just want a piece of the pie, and I'm the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley feels stuck with Bush. He has seen politicians preach a
welcome, conservative message, then do little to advance it once in
office. They do whatever they need to preserve their jobs, then do
what is necessary to take care of their party, Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, if there's anything left, you take care of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH A SHOO-IN IN ALLEN COUNTY
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ohl of Lima, a conservative voter in what may be the
state's most conservative county, shares no such ambivalence this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ohl, 39, a mother of three, is among the best women
sharpshooters in the nation, and this day she's at the Lima Sabres
Shooting Club, exercising her M-16.
</P>
<P>
   At 200 yards, she doesn't miss.
</P>
<P>
   Ohl despises gun control. She wants to have the country's first
Girl Scouts who earn their rifle shooting merit badge, just like
the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this year, she and other Allen County residents took
aim at Gov. Taft's safe storage gun bill. Statehouse offices were
flooded with phone calls and letters from the Lima area, more than
from any other single region, to protest the bill, which died in
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a cinch to carry this northwest Ohio county which last
voted for a Democratic presidential candidate when it choose Harry
Truman in 1948. The only way Bush could lose support here is if he
doesn't stop to visit (every Republican presidential candidate
since Dwight Eisenhower in 1952 has stopped in Lima) or if he
changes his position on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, they have the right to carry and conceal, the right
to protect themselves and their families, Bush will push to give
all Americans that same right,'' Ohl said. ``My rights as a gun
owner, the constitutional right I cherish most, would be stripped
away by Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohioans list education as their top issue on polls. In
interviews, other issues also emerge, including tax cuts, health
care and abortion rights, with different regions emphasizing
different topics.
</P>
<P>
   In Lima, gun control and abortion rights are hot. In Democratic
Youngstown, it's organized labor and foreign trade. Around
Columbus, voters talk about the economy and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money for me. Are they going to give some back
to us or are they going keep taking what I make?'' asked Kenneth
Broughman, a Republican banker and father of three from Dublin, a
northwest suburb of Columbus. ``I know the schools are in bad
shape, but when were they ever in good shape? If we don't get some
tax relief now when times are good, we may never get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere is a single issue more important than in
southeastern Ohio's Perry County, a former coal-mining area that's
hit hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Residents there have seen overcrowded school buildings continue
to crumble while state lawmakers and the Ohio Supreme Court fight
over how Ohio should pay for public education. The lawsuit that led
to Ohio's funding system declared unconstitutional started here, in
the Northern Local School District.
</P>
<P>
   An odd conglomeration of buildings, trailers and temporary sheds
make up the district's high School, middle school and school board
offices. Everyone in the area knows someone who had to sit on the
floor in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember my daughter sitting on the floor of the
cafeteria to eat lunch,'' said Susan Miller, 50, a legal secretary
from Somerset.
</P>
<P>
   Voters here _ retired truckers, barbers or legal secretaries _
know the responsibility for school lies with the state. But if Bush
or Gore could show a direct link between their proposals and
getting local kids off the floor during lunchtime, they would find
an attentive audience.
</P>
<P>
   FROM NOW UNTIL NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   A poll in May by the American Research Group showed Bush with a
6-point lead. But Democrats note Gore has been closing the gap in
polls. Last October, Bush's lead in the University of Cincinnati's
Ohio Poll was 24 points. In January it was 13, and more recently,
9.
</P>
<P>
   But its too early for poll numbers to mean much. Too many
political questions linger.
</P>
<P>
   How much impact will Gov. Taft have campaigning for Bush? Will
Columbus Mayor Coleman help Gore pick up support in a traditionally
conservative city? Will the criminal investigation of U.S. Rep.
James Traficant, D-Youngstown, hurt Gore in a Democratic
stronghold?
</P>
<P>
   ``This state is up for grabs, both parties know that and it has
both sides a little nervous heading into the real part of the
campaign season,'' said Staci Rhine, a political scientist from
Wittenberg University in Springfield. ``What happens with the
economy as far as interest rates, gas prices and the stock market
will also have an impact on voters between now and November.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the pier in Sandusky Bay, Harry Ruzicka thought about
what it would be like to go fishing with Gore and Bush. He said
Gore would probably talk too much and scare away the fish, and Bush
would probably drink all of his beer.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ruzicka got serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to make fun of guys running for that office, but one
of them is going to be president, for God's sake. One of them will
end up reeling me in, I just don't know which one yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HEARTLAND-OHIO0619-CO     06-18 2490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-OHIO0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohioans know how fish feel
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner and Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Harry Ruzicka's quiet morning on a pier in
Sandusky Bay is interrupted by a tug on his fishing line and the
thought of giving his vote to Al Gore or George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ruzicka, struggling a bit to land a big sheephead, struggles
even more over who he wants to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush comes from a good family, but I think he'll ruin Social
Security and do nothing to make health care better,'' Ruzicka said.
``Gore will do more for the average guy, but he'll have us paying
more taxes and he's as real as my $3 bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picking a president is about like what I'm doing with these
fish, trying to figure out which one to keep and which one to toss
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruzicka is 89, a lifelong independent and the kind of guy who
liked Harry Truman because he wasn't afraid to curse on the radio.
He has voted for 18 presidents, some Democrat, some Republican, and
this year he isn't sure which way to cast.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio voters like Ruzicka are the real prize catch of campaign
2000. They bring with them 21 electoral votes and are the reason
Vice President Gore, the Democrat, and Texas Gov. Bush, the
Republican, will continue barnstorming the state over the next five
months.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do early polls show the race getting closer, history
shows Buckeye voters are as fickle as the fish in Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1932, the first presidential election of the Great
Depression, Ohio has voted Republican nine times, and Democratic
seven. President Clinton took Ohio twice, but in 1992 against
incumbent George Bush, he won by only 2 percentage points. If not
for third-party candidate Ross Perot, Clinton might have lost Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   This year's fight for the White House could be even closer.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has ever captured the presidency without winning
Ohio. And the Democrats haven't won the Buckeye State in three
consecutive elections since Franklin Roosevelt did it in 1932, '36
and '40.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't paying attention right now. It's summer, we
haven't gotten to the conventions,'' said Allan Lichtman, chairman
of American University's Department of History. ``But both Bush and
Gore are paying a lot of attention to Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with more than 100 likely voters across Ohio found
few beyond the fiercely partisan who have already made up their
minds. Ohioans are more likely to say the Reds or the Indians _ not
Bush or Gore _ when asked who will win this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have concerns the candidates can speak to. Tax cuts,
health care, gun issues, abortion rights and deteriorating schools
all were repeatedly mentioned, with one issue, character, cutting
across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my children thinking it's OK to lie or deceive
people,'' said Kelly Vincent, a single mother of two and lab
technician from Dayton. ``I don't care too much about their
politics or what party they are from, I just want a decent man to
be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't have to be perfect, but he should
respect the people who elected him.''
</P>
<P>
   OHIO CONSIDERED NATIONAL BELLWETHER
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is the nation's seventh most populous state and one of its
most culturally diverse. It still has a strong agriculture and
manufacturing base, along with a growing technology sector and some
of the nation's best medical facilities and universities.
</P>
<P>
   It leans slightly Republican, but neither party can take it for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio has long been considered a national bellwether, and for
good reason. In the last century, Ohio voted the same way the
nation voted in 23 of 25 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Republican rule of thumb for winning in Ohio
involved heavily Democratic Cuyahoga County _ but it did not
include winning there. Republicans just had to lose there by fewer
than 100,000 votes, a margin that could be offset by Republican
areas elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Republicans say gains in other metro regions,
including Dayton, mean the 100,000-vote threshold no longer
matters. They can get creamed in Cuyahoga County, according to the
new Republican math, and still carry the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lot more votes to get now in places like Dayton and
Columbus,'' said Ohio Republican Chairman Robert Bennett. ``It's
not all about Cleveland any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County politics illustrate the point. Once
significantly blue collar and solidly Democratic, the county now is
politically balanced, a Republican vote having grown with suburban
development.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, claim new inroads as well, and cite Columbus
Mayor Michael Coleman, the city's first Democratic mayor in 28
years, to prove their point.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft said Ohio voters have become much less
predictable. ``I think the electorate is more volatile and less
historic in its allegiance to either party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Dimora, the Cuyahoga County Democratic chairman and a
county commissioner, knows he's in for a tougher fight this year.
Bush is striking a chord with some traditional Democratic voters,
Dimora said. And he wishes Gore would take it more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore spent nothing here (for the primary). That concerns me
that they are taking this county for granted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Leland, chairman of the Ohio Democratic Party, doesn't
share Dimora's concerns. Leland says Gore and the Democrats won't
take Cuyahoga County or any other area for granted when the
campaign gets rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win this state and win this election by not conceding any
area,'' Leland said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats won't carry Republican Hamilton County, he said, ``but
we might be able to pick up 5,000 votes there. That's the kind of
effort it will take to win a close race like this one.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cuyahoga County holds a big key for Ohio Democrats, then the
key to the county, Dimora said, is solidifying the vote in
Cleveland and getting out early and often to the more ethnic,
inner-ring suburbs such as Parma, Lakewood and Euclid.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-six-year-old Helen McFarland of Brookpark, another of
the blue-collar suburbs, is typical of voters found there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived during the Hoover depression and my Dad pounded it
into our heads,'' McFarland said. ``We almost lost our home. We
went to school with cardboard in our shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad's message: Republicans take care of the rich; everyone else
needs the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland backs Gore for the simple reason he is not Bush.
</P>
<P>
   MANY VOTES IN THE MIDDLE
</P>
<P>
   If McFarland were typical of Ohio voters, there would be no race
here. But Ohio is filled with swing voters who inhabit the
political middle, which is where the presidential fight will really
take place.
</P>
<P>
   Ohioans like Tim Williams, Israel Morales and Charles Buckley
represent Taft's less predictable electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 49, is an assembly line worker at Ford Motor Co.'s
massive engine plant in northeastern Ohio. He voted for Clinton
twice and has considered himself a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, he said, ``(My vote) is still up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't followed either candidate right now because
when you get down to it, there isn't much difference between the
Democrats and the Republicans,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bennett, a political scientist from University of
Cincinnati, said both Bush and Gore are trying to convince Ohio's
moderate and swing voters that they are one of them. Bush is trying
to shake off the conservative image he created to beat Arizona Sen.
John McCain in the primaries; Gore is seen by many as a liberal
environmental and labor union activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing extreme in the Midwest is the extreme middle,''
Bennett said. ``Most people in the Midwest tend to be very moderate
and so these candidates are trying to be what these people want.
Bush has done a better job of getting to these people so far.''
</P>
<P>
   When campaigning in Ohio, Bush has conspicuously gone to urban,
traditionally Democratic neighborhoods, including two Hispanic
areas on Cleveland's west side.
</P>
<P>
   In Clark-Fulton, a historically Italian neighborhood now seeing
an influx of Latinos, Israel Morales has voted for Democrats in
every presidential election except 1988. That year, he backed
Bush's father, former President George W. Bush, and this year he
likes Bush the son.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bush) addresses Hispanic issues more,'' said Morales, 48, a
truck driver who was born in Puerto Rico but has lived in the
United States for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include Bush's position in the custody fight over
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez. Bush criticized the government's armed
intervention to remove Elian from Miami relatives and reunite him
with his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   Downstate in the Perry County seat of New Lexington, a town of
5,100 on the edge of the Wayne National Forest, it would be
inaccurate to call Charles Buckley a swing voter. But he is someone
who's less comfortable than he once was with the party of his
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, 73, is in the midst of a personal transition.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported Republican candidates with his time and money
for years. He crankily calls the ACLU the American Communist
Lawyers Union. He doubts he would vote for Al Gore if Gore ran
unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   But last year the fund-raising letters from Republican
politicians all over the nation started to weigh on his mind. They
came in from California, Kansas, Wisconsin . . . he stopped
counting at 280 letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My postman said 'You're kind of popular,' `` Buckley said. ``I
said, no, they just want a piece of the pie, and I'm the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley feels stuck with Bush. He has seen politicians preach a
welcome, conservative message, then do little to advance it once in
office. They do whatever they need to preserve their jobs, then do
what is necessary to take care of their party, Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, if there's anything left, you take care of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH A SHOO-IN IN ALLEN COUNTY
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ohl of Lima, a conservative voter in what may be the
state's most conservative county, shares no such ambivalence this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ohl, 39, a mother of three, is among the best women
sharpshooters in the nation, and this day she's at the Lima Sabres
Shooting Club, exercising her M-16.
</P>
<P>
   At 200 yards, she doesn't miss.
</P>
<P>
   Ohl despises gun control. She wants to have the country's first
Girl Scouts who earn their rifle shooting merit badge, just like
the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this year, she and other Allen County residents took
aim at Gov. Taft's safe storage gun bill. Statehouse offices were
flooded with phone calls and letters from the Lima area, more than
from any other single region, to protest the bill, which died in
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a cinch to carry this northwest Ohio county which last
voted for a Democratic presidential candidate when it choose Harry
Truman in 1948. The only way Bush could lose support here is if he
doesn't stop to visit (every Republican presidential candidate
since Dwight Eisenhower in 1952 has stopped in Lima) or if he
changes his position on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, they have the right to carry and conceal, the right
to protect themselves and their families, Bush will push to give
all Americans that same right,'' Ohl said. ``My rights as a gun
owner, the constitutional right I cherish most, would be stripped
away by Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohioans list education as their top issue on polls. In
interviews, other issues also emerge, including tax cuts, health
care and abortion rights, with different regions emphasizing
different topics.
</P>
<P>
   In Lima, gun control and abortion rights are hot. In Democratic
Youngstown, it's organized labor and foreign trade. Around
Columbus, voters talk about the economy and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money for me. Are they going to give some back
to us or are they going keep taking what I make?'' asked Kenneth
Broughman, a Republican banker and father of three from Dublin, a
northwest suburb of Columbus. ``I know the schools are in bad
shape, but when were they ever in good shape? If we don't get some
tax relief now when times are good, we may never get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere is a single issue more important than in
southeastern Ohio's Perry County, a former coal-mining area that's
hit hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Residents there have seen overcrowded school buildings continue
to crumble while state lawmakers and the Ohio Supreme Court fight
over how Ohio should pay for public education. The lawsuit that led
to Ohio's funding system declared unconstitutional started here, in
the Northern Local School District.
</P>
<P>
   An odd conglomeration of buildings, trailers and temporary sheds
make up the district's high School, middle school and school board
offices. Everyone in the area knows someone who had to sit on the
floor in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember my daughter sitting on the floor of the
cafeteria to eat lunch,'' said Susan Miller, 50, a legal secretary
from Somerset.
</P>
<P>
   Voters here _ retired truckers, barbers or legal secretaries _
know the responsibility for school lies with the state. But if Bush
or Gore could show a direct link between their proposals and
getting local kids off the floor during lunchtime, they would find
an attentive audience.
</P>
<P>
   FROM NOW UNTIL NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   A poll in May by the American Research Group showed Bush with a
6-point lead. But Democrats note Gore has been closing the gap in
polls. Last October, Bush's lead in the University of Cincinnati's
Ohio Poll was 24 points. In January it was 13, and more recently,
9.
</P>
<P>
   But its too early for poll numbers to mean much. Too many
political questions linger.
</P>
<P>
   How much impact will Gov. Taft have campaigning for Bush? Will
Columbus Mayor Coleman help Gore pick up support in a traditionally
conservative city? Will the criminal investigation of U.S. Rep.
James Traficant, D-Youngstown, hurt Gore in a Democratic
stronghold?
</P>
<P>
   ``This state is up for grabs, both parties know that and it has
both sides a little nervous heading into the real part of the
campaign season,'' said Staci Rhine, a political scientist from
Wittenberg University in Springfield. ``What happens with the
economy as far as interest rates, gas prices and the stock market
will also have an impact on voters between now and November.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the pier in Sandusky Bay, Harry Ruzicka thought about
what it would be like to go fishing with Gore and Bush. He said
Gore would probably talk too much and scare away the fish, and Bush
would probably drink all of his beer.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ruzicka got serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to make fun of guys running for that office, but one
of them is going to be president, for God's sake. One of them will
end up reeling me in, I just don't know which one yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
