<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHIO-BAR0619-COX     06-18 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BAR0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. usually goes with Montgomery County's political flow
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner and Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Gov. Bob Taft, talking about why Ohio is
important for presidential hopefuls, explained that the state has
all aspects of American life _ big cities and small towns, farms
and businesses, a significant labor presence, and ``mainstream
values that are reflective of the middle of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   He could as easily have been talking about Montgomery County.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts and party officials say there may not be a
better place to take the country's political temperature than the
Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery County is the ultimate political measuring stick
for both parties,'' said Robert Bennett, chairman of the Ohio
Republican Party. ``If you can win over voters in Montgomery
County, you have a pretty good chance to win the state and the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, the county has supported the winning
presidential candidate in 11 of 13 elections. Only in 1960, when
the county narrowly favored Richard Nixon over John F. Kennedy, and
in 1980, when Jimmy Carter barely carried the county over Ronald
Reagan, did local voting results failed to mirror Ohio and the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   That's not lost on the campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Already, Gore has been here twice and
Bush once. And Tipper Gore, the vice president's wife, has been to
Dayton twice more in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County has just about every kind of voter a
presidential candidate must connect with to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Its work force wears blue and white collars. More than 20,000
auto workers here make everything from SUVs for General Motors to
air conditioning parts for Chrysler. Thousands of engineers and
technicians drive the area's technology base at Wright-Patterson
Air Force Base and at large companies such as NCR, Reynolds &AMP;
Reynolds and Mead Corp. There are farmers, college students, and
minority communities; a central city on the rebound and a new
political mix fed by suburban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   But swing voters are what really make Montgomery County the
state's political hot potato.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're the most volatile place in the state and we
generally go with the winner,'' said Montgomery County Republican
Chairman Jeff Jacobson. ``I think Montgomery County has always had
a strong tradition of independent voting. What it lacked for so
many years was a strong Republican base. . . . Now we are much more
50/50.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Republicans now outnumber Democrats in the county,
75,335 to 57,137, but those numbers were set by the March 7
primary, when party affiliation is determined in Ohio, and were
driven by a hot Republican contest between Bush and Arizona Sen.
John McCain. The county supported Clinton in the past two
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County does not have the sheer number of voters that
will pull the candidates regularly to bigger metropolitan areas
such as Cleveland, Cincinnati and Columbus. But it may count as
much as those cities because it doesn't dramatically lean toward
the left or right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery County is critical more from the perception that
the state goes the way the county goes,'' said Montgomery County
Democratic Chairman Dennis Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   It's much too early to say which way the county might in
November. Both Bush and Gore have support here.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Linda Wafer, a 52-year-old mother of three from West
Dayton, are already sold on Gore. Wafer doesn't care about Gore's
image problems or how he differs from President Clinton. She is a
Democrat and believes Gore will do more for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is trying hard to be black or Hispanic, but that
ain't working on me,'' Wafer said. ``I'm black and I know a rich
white guy when I see one.''
</P>
<P>
   Other voters like Tiffany Becker, a 20-year-old Wright State
University student from Vandalia, are set on Bush. She is still
ashamed of President Clinton's fling with an intern and can't
forgive Gore for calling Clinton one of the nation's greatest
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gov. Bush has good ideas for schools and has a strong
faith. I see him being a stronger leader than Gore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters just haven't made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what kind of president either of these guys will
make,'' said Tom Sandstrom, a 41-year-old engineer and Kettering
resident. ``We'll see what they do between now and the election.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
