   Montgomery County does not have the sheer number of voters that
will pull the candidates regularly to bigger metropolitan areas
such as Cleveland, Cincinnati and Columbus. But it may count as
much as those cities because it doesn't dramatically lean toward
the left or right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery County is critical more from the perception that
the state goes the way the county goes,'' said Montgomery County
Democratic Chairman Dennis Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   It's much too early to say which way the county might in
November. Both Bush and Gore have support here.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Linda Wafer, a 52-year-old mother of three from West
Dayton, are already sold on Gore. Wafer doesn't care about Gore's
image problems or how he differs from President Clinton. She is a
Democrat and believes Gore will do more for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is trying hard to be black or Hispanic, but that
ain't working on me,'' Wafer said. ``I'm black and I know a rich
white guy when I see one.''
</P>
<P>
   Other voters like Tiffany Becker, a 20-year-old Wright State
University student from Vandalia, are set on Bush. She is still
ashamed of President Clinton's fling with an intern and can't
forgive Gore for calling Clinton one of the nation's greatest
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
