   FOR MONDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted): &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Top lede)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVIOR-RATINGS _ ``Survivor,'' a breakout hit in every
way, has stunned the television industry by generating for CBS the
kind of ratings with young viewers that normally are associated
with shows on the Fox network or ABC. Last week, ``Survivor''
pulled in the most viewers under the age of 50 of any series CBS
has played on a Wednesday night at 8 p.m. in the entire 13-year
history of the Nielsen people-meter system. By Bill Carter and
Allison Fass.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 5 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   TALENT-AGENT (Los Angeles) _ Since taking the president's job at
the Beverly Hills headquarters of William Morris last August, the
talent agent Jim Wiatt has not just sought to fix William Morris
but has shaken up the talent agency business with a relentless
effort to lure stars from his old employer, only two miles away.
Even by the brass-knuckle standards of two former William Morris
agents, Michael Ovitz and Ron Meyer, who used similar tactics 20
years ago to turn Creative Artists into the town's dominant agency,
Wiatt's efforts have been surprising, dramatic and fast-moving. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 6 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Right Center)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MESSAGES (San Francisco) _ Despite the explosive
popularity of instant-messaging programs on the Internet, it became
apparent last week that one facet of the service may not be instant
at all: It may be a year or more before users of competing
instant-message services can send missives to one another. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 6 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL-CANADA (Undated) _ Nortel, the Canadian
telecommunications equipment giant, has become a company for the
Americas. It is growing so rapidly outside Canada that doubts are
being expressed at home about its corporate citizenship. Its
headquarters remains in Brampton, Ontario, but more of its 75,000
employees live and work south of the Canada-U.S. border than north
of it. And these days, just 9 percent of its $18 billion in
revenues comes from Canada. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
