<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-SURVIVOR-RATINGS-A     06-18 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-RATINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS FINALLY LURES COVETED YOUNG VIEWERS WITH `SURVIVOR'
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BILL CARTER with ALLISON FASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zach Apter, a 23-year-old management consultant in San
Francisco, is hardly the typical CBS viewer; he cannot remember
watching anything on CBS since he was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   That was before ``Survivor.'' Now Apter is so involved with the
hit CBS series about survival and relationship tests on an tropical
island near Borneo that he has organized a pool with his friends
($100 each) to select which contestant winds up as the final
survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most over-the-top thing on TV that I've ever seen or
heard of,'' Apter said. ``I'm not going to miss a single one.''
</P>
<P>
   These are words from a man who is less than half the median age
of a viewer of CBS _ long identified as the network of the rural
and the retired.
</P>
<P>
   And Apter is far from alone. ``Survivor,'' a breakout hit in
every way, has stunned the television industry by generating for
CBS the kind of ratings with young viewers that normally are
associated with shows on the Fox network or ABC. Last week,
``Survivor'' pulled in the most viewers under the age of 50 of any
series CBS has aired on a Wednesday night at 8 p.m. in the 13-year
history of the Nielsen people-meter system, which breaks down
viewers into demographic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The show's success has enormous financial implications for CBS.
Young viewers usually translate into high prices for commercials
because many advertisers pay a premium to reach the young, who
watch less television than older viewers and are more likely to be
willing to change brands. One reason CBS' revenues have lagged
behind those of other networks has been its inability to attract
that premium money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' was sold in advance to a group of full sponsors,
including Reebok, Budweiser and the Army. But the show does have
two 30-second commercials available for sale in the rest of its
episodes and these are being quickly snapped up by advertisers like
movie companies, which always look to reach young viewers. An
executive connected to the negotiations said CBS is charging as
much as $300,000 each for these commercials, 50 percent more than
the full sponsors have been paying.
</P>
<P>
   And in what will almost certainly create another windfall, CBS
is considering expanding the ``Survivor'' finale on Aug. 23 from
one hour to two, which would open up an hour's worth of high-priced
commercials. The network may charge as much as $600,000 for the new
spots. (In the final episode, the last four contestants will first
be narrowed to two and then to one final survivor.)
</P>
<P>
   Many of the young viewers CBS is hoping to cash in on simply had
not been available to it before. Eric Robinson, a motion picture
talent agent in New York, who is also 23, said, ``What other shows
are on CBS?'' But he is watching ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see the type of drama that would unfold with these
people stuck on an island,'' he said. ``It's like `Real World'
meets `Lord of the Flies.' And I wanted to see people eat rats.''
And so they did on last Wednesday's third episode of the 13-episode
summer series.
</P>
<P>
   Elise Hartley, also 23, a government consultant in Washington,
said she had heard about the show on a radio commercial _ not
because she had been watching CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Hartley heard about the show through radio was not
an accident. CBS, realizing it was unlikely to reach a young
audience using only its own airwaves, began promoting ``Survivor''
last year on the Internet. Then it started buying time on outlets
it knew young people would be plugged into: cable channels like MTV
and Comedy Central, and rock radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Later, of course, that became much easier when Viacom merged
with CBS, bringing along those two cable channels. CBS already had
numerous radio stations in its corporate family through its
subsidiary Infinity Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   But now CBS may not need MTV as much. The success of
``Survivor'' gives it an opportunity to speak directly to an
audience it has not been able to reach for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had this goal for years, trying to get younger,'' said
Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television. Three years ago he
bought the comedy ``Family Matters'' away from ABC, where it had a
big audience among children and teen-agers. They did not watch it
on CBS. He tried police dramas like ``Easy Street'' and youthful
comedies like ``Grapevine.'' They died quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But now the news is better, thanks to what CBS is calling the
halo effect created by ``Survivor.'' Last week, for example, CBS
had six of the top 10 shows among viewers between the ages of 18 to
49, a feat it had not achieved in any season in memory that did not
include the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And a host of CBS shows have scored big gains from last year
among viewers under 35: ``King of Queens'' is up 39 percent;
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' is up 34 percent; and the Monday
edition of ``48 Hours'' is up 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most telling is that in the last two weeks, CBS has plugged the
two-hour slot after ``Survivor'' on Wednesday nights with repeats
of theatrical movies; they were up 110 percent with viewers under
35.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is moving as best it can to capitalize on the access
``Survivor'' is providing to the young crowd. It already has
announced that it would change the start date of its follow-up
reality series, ``Big Brother,'' from Thursday, July 6, to
Wednesday, July 5, to take advantage of the ``Survivor'' lead-in.
(CBS has hopes that ``Big Brother,'' a 90-night documentary of the
lives of 10 people locked together in a house, where every move is
on camera, will have similar fascination for younger viewers.)
</P>
<P>
   Now CBS is revamping its Wednesday schedule for the summer. On
June 28, the network will broadcast repeats of its two best
comedies, ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' and ``King of Queens,'' from
9 to 10 p.m. after ``Survivor.'' Later this summer it will put
shows like ``Judging Amy'' and ``JAG'' in that time period, hoping
to showcase them for young viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans reflect Moonves' overall strategy of letting young
viewers see the CBS shows they may have liked all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason why the median age for `Raymond' is 49 and
the median age for `Frasier' is 41,'' he said. ``Other than the
fact that one is on CBS and the other is on NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said CBS would use ``Survivor'' to promote some new
shows for fall, including ``Yes, Dear,'' which is about younger
married couples, and the remake of ``The Fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Studios that have been reluctant to sell their better shows to
CBS because they did not think they could appeal to young viewers
may also come calling now _ as long as they think they have a shot
at the time period after ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they are watching the show, at least some of the young
viewers are not taking it too seriously. One of the participants in
Apter's ``Survivor'' pool, Ben Decker, a 24-year-old management
consultant from San Francisco, called the program ``sort of
ludicrous'' and questioned whether it was going to work for CBS in
the long run. But for now he is totally committed to CBS _ at least
one night a week. After all, he has a serious rooting interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we really find funny is watching CBS drum up suspense and
contention between the contestants,'' he said. ``I think if CBS
could, they would set these people against each other with swords
and tridents in a pit full of tigers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
