u f BC-COINSTAR-AD-COLUMN-NY     06-18 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COINSTAR-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CAMPAIGN CAPITALIZES ON FIENDISH AND FUNNY USES FOR
LOOSE CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Converting the loose change on the bedroom dresser into ``real
money'' is probably on the bottom of most people's ``to do'' lists,
right up there with organizing the sock drawer.
</P>
<P>
   But a new campaign for Coinstar, the nation's largest
manufacturer of self-service coin-counting machines, seeks to
reverse those sentiments by using humor to exhort consumers to dump
the contents of their piggy banks into the company's machines and
become empowered by their ``new found'' money.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million brand-building TV campaign is the first for
Coinstar by the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of the Omnicom Group since the
agency's office in Playa del Rey, Calif., was awarded the account
in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new Coinstar campaign represents a notable evolution, both
strategically and creatively, from previous advertising efforts,''
said Rich Stillman, vice president for marketing at Coinstar in
Bellevue, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, our ads focused on the rational benefits of our
service, such as convenience and ease of use. To better connect
with consumers the new ads are designed to strike an emotional
chord, conveying a brand personality for Coinstar that is human,
empathetic, inspiring and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Coinstar estimates that two-thirds of Americans accumulate on
average over $600 worth of change every year. Research found,
however, that only about 12 percent have ever tried using the
Coinstar service.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, our main strategy is to build awareness and trial of our
service,'' Stillman said, asserting that ``125 million Americans
live within two miles of a Coinstar machine.''
</P>
<P>
   The bright green and purple self-service coin-counting machines
are in more than 7,500 groceries nationwide, including Albertson's,
Food Emporium, Kroger and Safeway. The machine is a PC that counts
coins and reimburses consumers after subtracting an 8.9 percent fee
for the service, with the supermarkets collecting 1 percent of
that. In addition, the machine issues vouchers and dispenses
discount coupons from other marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Coinstar's research found that the predominate experience when
using its machine is that most customers go into a supermarket with
a jar of coins expecting to collect $25 to $30, but have severely
underestimated how much money they actually have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling that people get is a little bit like winning the
lottery,'' Stillman said. ``It's just a fun experience. And that
was the part we wanted to capture.''
</P>
<P>
   Two 30-second humorous television commercials demonstrate how
coins can be changed into something useful in unusual ways by
featuring everyday situations and exaggerating them for effect into
``what if'' situations.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one spot, which unfolds the story without
dialogue, features a 12-year-old boy sauntering down a city
sidewalk when two older boys torment him by tossing coins at him
from a second-story window. Day in and day out the boy simply picks
up the coins without missing a beat. The spot then cuts to the
tormented boy at a Coinstar machine converting a large jar of
coins. As an announcer states, ``Turn your change into something
useful,'' the two bullies are shown hanging out the tenement window
waiting to throw coins at the boy when they hear ``Beep. Beep.
Beep.'' As a shadow appears, they look down to the street and see
the younger boy operating a wrecking ball he has rented to get
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   A second commercial features a waitress in a cocktail lounge
dealing with a troublesome regular customer played by the character
actor Mike Hagerty, who is known for bit parts on television shows
that include ``Friends.'' In the spot, the heavyset sleazy
businessman comes in daily for a beer and harasses the waitress. He
cheaply tips her by placing coins in the front pocket of her apron,
invading her personal space at the same time. After suffering the
final indignity of a slap on the buttocks, the waitress visits the
Coinstar machine. The next night as the customer places his hand in
the waitress' apron his fingers are zapped. The scene then cuts to
the waitress putting her newly purchased Stun King stun gun in her
locker. The spot was unscripted with the dialogue ad-libbed by
Hagerty.
</P>
<P>
   Both spots end with the announcer stating the tagline,
``Coinstar. How much do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the campaign will get people to start looking at
that change as being a lot more than what they think it is and
here's an easy way to get rid of it and get cash for it,'' Jerry
Gentile, managing partner and creative director at TBWA/Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   Using humor as a vehicle is certainly not unusual for
TBWA/Chiat/Day, which is known for work that entertains, in
particular its campaigns for longtime clients like Energizer,
Nissan and Taco Bell. The Coinstar effort is yet another campaign
to fall into Madison Avenue's long-running, contentious debate over
just how effective humorous advertising is in peddling products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that people's lives are just constantly being
bombarded with stuff, and I think you have got to find a way that
doesn't strangle people with messages,'' Gentile said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key with something like this, when it's a low
interest product _ something you don't think about everyday _ you
have to bring something to it to put a little more importance or a
little more interest in the subject,'' he added. ``I think humor
seems to be universal. It just seemed like an obvious way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots began running last month in 12 markets, including
Chicago, Denver, Philadelphia, San Francisco and Washington.
Coinstar will add additional markets later this year while three
radio commercials, with a similar creative format, began running
this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
