<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WHITTLING DOWN VP PROSPECTS, BUT MUM'S STILL THE WORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mo., Pa., Okla., Tenn., Neb., Ohio)  By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two of the biggest names, Gen. Colin L. Powell
and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, have emphatically proclaimed their
lack of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Another widely rumored contender, former Sen. John C. Danforth
of Missouri, recently bowed out. And the governor on whom the early
speculation centered, Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, is giving more
Republicans pause.
</P>
<P>
   With little more than a month to go before Gov. George W. Bush
settles on the person with whom he wants to share the Republican
presidential ticket, the list of possibilities seems to be getting
shorter.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean it is getting a whole lot clearer,
because Bush is holding his cards so close to the vest that even
his most trusted advisers insist they have not been able to sneak a
peek.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, the Bush campaign's director of communications,
said that Bush leaves the room when he gets a call from former
Defense Secretary Richard B. Cheney, who is supervising the
selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out a Ouija board,'' said another adviser when asked about
the status of Bush's thinking on the matter. ``I'm not kidding, I'm
totally clueless.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Texas governor told reporters that he was making
progress and talking frequently with Cheney. But he said he had no
intention of divulging the content of their conversations or
bringing too many people into the loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need a committee to figure out who's best to be the
vice president,'' Bush said, adding, ``I'm going to take my time.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, has not prevented fellow Republicans from
handicapping the race. And some of the buzz they are generating
seems to have a grounding in reality, because both Republican
officials who have no direct link to the Bush campaign and those
who interact frequently with Bush's advisers keep coming up with
the same handful of names.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost among them is Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma,
whose aides have acknowledged that he received a questionnaire that
Cheney sent out to prospective vice presidential nominees.
Republican officials noted that Keating is Roman Catholic,
performed well on a national stage during the Oklahoma City
bombing, has a squeaky-clean image and has long been friendly with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, also Catholic, is said to remain in the running, although
his support of abortion rights _ and the grief it has caused him
with Catholic leaders in his state _ makes him a riskier, more
controversial choice, some Republican strategists contend. They
said that if Bush, who opposes abortion, were doing poorly with
voters in the political center, Ridge might make more sense.
</P>
<P>
   But polls suggest that the Texas governor is doing well with
independents and moderates and would be wiser to avoid any possible
alienation of religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most basic rule of picking a vice president is `first, do
no harm','' said one adviser to the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This adviser, and other Republican officials, said that other
politicians who seem to be getting at least some degree of genuine
consideration include Elizabeth Dole, Sen. Fred Thompson of
Tennessee and Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska. These sources put less
stock in Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, whose name occasionally gets
bandied about.
</P>
<P>
   But they cautioned that the final pick could be someone who is
generating absolutely no discussion, especially if recent history
is any guide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Bush's father took even members of his inner circle by
surprise when he hitched himself at the last moment to Dan Quayle.
Bob Dole's selection of Jack Kemp in 1996 also came out of left
field.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Republican officials and several of Bush's
advisers said, the Texas governor is freer than recent Republican
nominees to let his eye wander, or to go ultimately with his heart
and his gut.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, when Ronald Reagan selected Bush's father, who had
opposed him in the primaries, he was working to unite the
conservative and moderate wings of a fractured Republican party. In
1996, Dole's unexpected choice of Kemp was partly an attempt to
inject some excitement into an underdog effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party's united now,'' said one of Bush's advisers,
alluding to recent polls showing that nine out of 10 Republicans
support Bush. The adviser added that because of Bush's advantage
over Vice President Al Gore in most of those surveys, ``He's not in
the position of having to throw the long ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers and Republican strategists agreed that
geography, which would favor someone like Ridge, the governor of a
swing state, was increasingly unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the 24-hour media outlets and all the different outlets
today, people can become known nationally instantly,'' said Bill
Dal Col, who managed Steve Forbes' presidential campaign. Others
said that the country's regional differences were no longer as
pronounced as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   A more important criterion to Bush may simply be choosing
someone with whom he is extremely comfortable. He has said over and
over that he wants a running mate with whom he shares a reciprocal
affection, and while that may sound like a stock platitude, people
who know him well note that he is a stickler for loyalty and puts
great value on the ease and pleasantness of his interactions with
associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Bush's top priority, far more than any tactical,
geographical or political consideration,'' said one Republican
official who interacts with the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's advisers said that Bush does not want to replicate
the situation between Reagan and his father, who were not that
close when they entered the White House, and whose staffs regarded
each other warily.
</P>
<P>
   That concern favors candidates like Keating and Ridge, both
longtime friends of Bush's. And because both of them are governors
and not members of Congress, Republican officials said, they would
also help Bush underscore his pledge to eradicate Washington's
partisan acrimony and gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   To a lesser extent, officials said, Hagel and Thompson could fit
into that pitch. Neither has served in the Senate for long. Both
have exhibited some maverick tendencies, as their support for
McCain in the primaries demonstrated. And both had long careers
outside politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the qualities that Bush has so successfully capitalized
on is his outsider status,'' said Scott Reed, who managed Dole's
presidential campaign. ``As he picks a running mate, I believe he
will be looking for someone from outside of Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
