<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TALENT-AGENT-ART-1000     06-18 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALENT-AGENT-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALENT AGENT MOVED, AND THE TALENT TAGGED ALONG
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In its heyday, the venerable William Morris agency
dominated Hollywood, representing legends like Marilyn Monroe,
Elvis Presley, Frank Sinatra, Charlie Chaplin, Will Rogers, Fannie
Brice, Al Jolson and Mae West. But by the late 1980s, the agency
had stumbled and was hemorrhaging clients and agents, the result of
its board's apathy and old-guard ways coupled with the death of its
top Hollywood agent, Stan Kamen, in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, William Morris was dwarfed by two
agencies, Creative Artists and International Creative Management,
which represented a sizable chunk of movie and television stars and
directors. ``The movie division needed some fixing,'' said Jim
Wiatt, the former co-chairman of International Creative Management
and now president and co-chief executive of William Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt spoke with considerable understatement. Since taking the
job at the Beverly Hills headquarters of William Morris last
August, the 53-year-old agent has not just sought to fix William
Morris but has shaken up the talent agency business with a
relentless effort to lure stars from his old employer, only two
miles away. Even by the brass-knuckle standards of two former
William Morris agents, Michael Ovitz and Ron Meyer, who used
similar tactics 20 years ago to turn Creative Artists into the
town's dominant agency, Wiatt's efforts have been surprising,
dramatic and fast-moving.
</P>
<P>
   The agency business itself is in the grip of change in
Hollywood. Facing a studio system relying mostly on star vehicles,
television networks nervous about declining audiences, competition
from talent managers and even lawyers, agents are involving
themselves _ and their clients _ in the world of the Internet and
high technology as they seek ways to expand their financial base.
But success and failure in the agency business hinges on a question
that has remained the same since the 1920s: How many high-priced
clients does an agency represent?
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, seven talent agents have joined Wiatt from
ICM. The most recent arrival, Steve Dontanville, one of ICM's top
agents, brings with him, among others, Meg Ryan, Sigourney Weaver,
Julianne Margulies, Courtney Love, Alfre Woodard and Patrick
Stewart. Other former ICM agents have brought to William Morris
clients like Russell Crowe, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Emily Watson and
Spike Lee. Wiatt himself has signed up Michael Douglas from
Creative Artists. And former clients of his at ICM like Eddie
Murphy, Sylvester Stallone, Tim Allen, Nora Ephron and Penny
Marshall have joined him at William Morris.
</P>
<P>
   The reason so many agents have moved out of ICM, which remains
very powerful despite the losses, is, to some degree, loyalty to
Wiatt, who was a mentor and friend to them. But, more important,
money was a driving factor. Agents are well paid. A veteran and
second-tier talent agent could earn $750,000 to $1 million a year,
perhaps more with bonuses. By all accounts, William Morris
increased the ante to lure the agents. An ICM agent said that a
former colleague, who earned $550,000, was being paid nearly double
that figure at William Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, agents at ICM are outraged at Wiatt, who worked in
top jobs there for 23 years and seems intent, they said, on hurting
the agency. (Wiatt personally tried to lure a British film director
away from one of his old friends at William Morris.) Publicly,
executives at ICM _ an agency with clients like Mel Gibson, Julia
Roberts, Denzel Washington, Jodie Foster, Cameron Diaz, Michelle
Pfeiffer, Chris Rock and Rosie O'Donnell _ said the exodus of
agents and stars to join Wiatt was, essentially, the nature of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win some, you lose some,'' said Ed Limato, co-president of
ICM, who represents numerous movie stars. ``We're cushioned against
such things. We have a great bench, we have reserves. Jim's an old
friend. I'm sorry he's gone. So we start a new era. Just look at
our client list.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Berg, chairman of the agency, said he had expected some
agents to follow Wiatt. Although partners with Berg, Wiatt was
known to have had a distant, chilly relationship with him and to
have been eager to leave, especially after William Morris offered
him a contract far more lucrative than his $1.5 million pay package
at ICM.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a senior leader, after 23 years, who left and became a
competitor,'' Berg said, adding that Wiatt's departure would have
no financial impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business for the last 10 years has been on a growth
trajectory,'' he said, and he added that he was certain that would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, a well-liked figure in Hollywood who is known for his
friendliness and approachability, has surprised his close friends
with the tough tactics. He has overhauled the New York office of
William Morris, and trimmed the London unit. About 18 agents have
departed. In the process, William Morris has also lost important
clients, mostly to Creative Artists. These include performers like
George Clooney, Brendan Fraser, Joseph Fiennes, Gillian Anderson
and Matthew Perry, and directors like Anthony Minghella (``The
English Patient'') and John Madden (``Shakespeare in Love'').
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, seated in an office at William Morris with his former
colleague at ICM, David Wirtschafter, who is head of worldwide
motion pictures at William Morris, said: ``The priority was the
movie division. It needed some new blood. And I think from a morale
standpoint it probably wasn't operating as well as it should have
been.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Wirtschafter, who represents mostly writers and
directors, said he had joined Wiatt out of ``enormous personal and
professional loyalty to him.'' A somewhat distant and intense
figure, Wirtschafter has, according to one agent, unnerved some of
the veteran William Morris agents working for him with his biting
comments. ``What's happened here in terms of the change in profile,
and the absolutely extraordinary agent and client migration, is, in
large part, due to Jim,'' Wirtschafter said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The last time such an exodus of clients occurred _ and it took
place over several years _ began in 1986 when Stan Kamen, who ran
the movie division of William Morris and was Hollywood's top agent,
died. Kamen's client list was a Who's Who of Hollywood stars of the
1970s: Goldie Hawn, Barbra Streisand, Jane Fonda, Robert Redford
and Warren Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   What followed over the next few years was an exodus of agents
and their clients to Creative Artists and ICM, and a steady decline
in the film unit of an agency that had been founded in 1898 by a
German immigrant, William Morris, and had its start placing singers
and comics on the vaudeville circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, the company's mailroom employed aspiring agents
like Barry Diller, David Geffen and Michael Ovitz. The company's
wealth was based not only on its client base, but substantial real
estate holdings in Beverly Hills and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company's leadership is dominated as it always was by
businessmen representing few, if any, clients. The result was an
agency _ and an 11-member board _ that was, until recently, the
most buttoned-up in town, rooted in tradition and conservative by
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Zifkin, chief executive at William Morris, said Wiatt's
performance so far had been ``beyond expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's considerable and it's strengthened us,'' Zifkin said.
``He's brought over some very good people with very good clients.
He's bought over good people who are very compatible with our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt replaced Arnold Rifkin, who represented Bruce Willis and
others, and who struggled in the mid-1990s to put William Morris on
a par with Creative Artists and ICM. But Rifkin damaged his career
at William Morris when he negotiating secretly for a top movie job
at Sony in 1996: by all accounts the William Morris board never
forgave him once the news was leaked. William Morris executives
said they were also unhappy that Rifkin had failed to sign up many
high-priced stars.
</P>
<P>
   The agency shifts are taking place against a backdrop of
unusually intense turmoil, even for a business where turmoil is the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the agency business was basically like a high
school club _ you were judged how cool and important you were
depending on what club had you as a member,'' said Jim Berkus,
president of the United Talent Agency, a significant player now in
the agency business. ``During the Stan Kamen era at William Morris,
it was cool to be in the Morris club. During the height of Mike
Ovitz's power, it was cool to be in the CAA club.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now there are four or five different agencies in town, and
clients are less concerned about the name of the agency and the
number of times the agents get their picture in `Vanity Fair,''' he
said. ``Clients are asking, `What level of service am I getting for
my commission?''' (Clients generally pay 10 percent of their
earnings to agents.)
</P>
<P>
   Berkus' United Talent Agency, once a secondary player, now has
such high-priced clients as Jim Carrey, Harrison Ford, Kevin
Costner, Madonna and Drew Carey and the television writer-producers
David Chase (``The Sopranos'') and Dick Wolf (``Law and Order'').
</P>
<P>
   Other agents agree with Berkus.
</P>
<P>
   Although Creative Artists lost some clients after Ovitz abruptly
quit in 1995 to briefly become president of the Walt Disney Co. _
and there were predictions in newspapers that the agency would
splinter _ it remains the No. 1 agency in Hollywood, representing
stars like Tom Cruise, Will Smith, Meryl Streep and Tom Hanks, and
directors such as Steven Spielberg, Robert Zemeckis and Michael
Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the most stable game in town,'' said Bryan Lourd, one of
the managing partners of Creative Artists. ``Five years ago,
everyone said we were going down. Look at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lovett, the agency's president, echoed the view that the
current warfare between William Morris and ICM helps Creative
Artists, which has deliberately sought to soften its image as the
town's bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a company that people were afraid of,'' he said. ``It
was a fear-based company. We don't believe in that kind of company.
Maybe with the change of image it appears that we're not the
fearsome machine we were. But we would argue that the results are
better.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of factors behind the shifts in the agency
business. Agencies are competitively struggling to gain a foothold
in the Internet world, to satisfy cable television's hunger for
material, to arrange film financing deals for clients' movies. The
result is that smaller agencies like Endeavor and
Broder-Kurland-Webb-Uffner are substantial players in the Hollywood
arena, alongside the bigger ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency business has not changed so much over the years,
but everything around us has changed,'' said Bob Broder, one of the
founders of the respected agency with a heavy clientele of writers
and directors.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Zimmer, a top agent at the United Talent Agency, was more
blunt. ``In a weird way, all of the major agencies are spending a
lot of time coping with the same problems as opposed to each other
as the problem,'' he said. Except in the case of the William Morris
agency and International Creative Management.
</P>
</TEXT>
