<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND POLITICAL PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   PART 2 of 5 PARTS
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-OHIO _ Ohio has been fickle when picking presidents.
Since the Great Depression started in 1929, the state has supported
nine Republicans and seven Democrats. President Clinton won Ohio in
in both his bids for the White House, but in 1992 against George
Bush he won by only two percentage points. If it weren't for Ross
Perot, Clinton might have lost the state. The race in Ohio between
Vice President Gore, the Democrat, and Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
may be even closer. Both men need Ohio and its 21 electoral votes
as much, if not more, than any other state. No Republican has ever
captured the presidency without winning Ohio. And the Democrats
haven't won the Buckeye state in three consecutive elections since
Franklin Roosevelt did it in 1932, 1936 and 1940. (Wagner, Dayton
Daily News). 75.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-BAR _ The bellwether of Ohio is still Montgomery County,
whose half-million residents are split roughly 50-50 between
Republicans and Democrats. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-ASSAD _ DAMASCUS, Syria _ In an important step on his
march to the presidency, Bashar Assad, the 34-year-old son of late
President Hafez Assad, was named secretary-general of Syria's
ruling Baath Party on Sunday. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   APPALACHIAN -CINEMA_ For the first time since the 1920s, this
Appalachian foothills town will have no movie theater this summer.
Town leaders meet Monday to consider a proposal by local developers
to reopen one of the town's two theaters which were closed in April
by Columbus, Ga.-based Carmike Cinemas. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MEASURE _ Earl Babbitt is tired of bumping his knees on the
backs of airplane seats and squeezing his six-foot-three-inch frame
into cars made for smaller people. Last week he did something about
it. Babbitt joined hundreds of people participating in a body
measurement study at Georgia Tech this month. Tech is the final
stop on a 12-city U.S. tour which has drawn thousands of people
providing personal statistics that companies can use to make
clothes fit better and cars more comfortable. (McCosh, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ There was something about my husband
bending over the rain gauge after a recent sprinkle _ not enough
rain to call it a shower _ that reminded me of his dad. The only
difference in their anxious reactions during a drought is John
yells back at the Weather Channel, while W.T. Ezzard surely would
have blamed the Farmer's Almanac. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
