u i BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-     06-18 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA AND ERITREA SIGN CEASE-FIRE TO END `USELESS' WAR 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The war between Ethiopia and Eritrea came to an
official halt Sunday, closing two years of fighting in one of the
fiercest wars in Africa, as the nations signed a preliminary
cease-fire and agreed to work toward a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The two foreign ministers, who did not speak to each other
during the negotiations, shook hands after the 15-point document
was signed in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   Haile Woldansae, the Eritrean foreign minister, said it was
``the first concrete step toward peace between the two countries
after a useless war.'' His Ethiopian counterpart, Seyoum Mesfin,
called the agreement ``historic.''
</P>
<P>
   Woldansae's characterization of the war as ``useless'' has often
been used to describe a border war that has crippled two
economically developing countries and killed tens of thousands of
its young men and women. It has also uprooted hundreds of thousands
of Eritreans and destroyed, for perhaps many years, the once-close
relationship between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   The document signed Sunday is not a final cease-fire, but it
does provide detailed plans for disengaging the two armies and
devising a lasting solution. Most important, the plan calls for
creation of a 15.5-mile buffer zone along the border, all in
Eritrean territory, acknowledging Ethiopia's gains on the
battlefield since the latest round of fighting began on May 12. But
in a concession to Eritrea, its officials and citizens may return
to the buffer zone as negotiations progress on the final accord.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for U.N. peacekeepers to patrol parts of the
zone, as well as the main areas of contention. These areas are
likely to include Zalambessa, Bure _ to the east, and Badme, where
the hostilities began in May 1998. Eritrea has claimed pockets
along the 620-mile border as its own, under colonial treaties, and
had moved troops into those zones. They have been pushed back by
Ethiopian troops, though, in the last month of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has not yet approved a peacekeeping mission
and so there are no estimates of its size, duration or timing. But
this is a time of increasing skepticism about peacekeeping missions
in Africa. Peacekeepers were taken hostage in Sierra Leone, and a
cease-fire in Congo _ where such a mission has already been
approved but no soldiers deployed _ has been repeatedly violated by
all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lake, the American former national security adviser who
helped broker Sunday's agreement, echoed remarks by other foreign
officials that this proposed peacekeeping mission was different
from others. He noted that the armies of the two participating
countries were ``highly disciplined'' and that both nations'
leaders were committed to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that each of them _ repeatedly over the last
two years and again today _ said they were very serious once they
signed about implementing it,'' Lake said in a telephone interview
Sunday from Algiers, where he attended the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a very strong reason to believe this will not
be like other cessation of hostility agreements on other parts of
the continent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most important element of the final peace accord will be the
demarcation of the border _ which was never settled when Eritrea,
for a generation the northernmost province of Ethiopia, gained its
independence in 1993. The question will be settled technically by
U.N. cartographers, using old colonial treaties and other
documents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like other officials, Lake portrayed Sunday's signing as a ray
of hope for Africa, at a time when the continent is torn by so much
conflict, in places like Sierra Leone, Angola, Congo and Burundi.
He and others noted that the accord was largely the product of the
Organization for African Unity, which will also oversee its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
   And if the peace accord works, Ethiopia and Eritrea, which had
been seen generally as two stable nations with promising economies,
may be back on track for economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing stereotype that what Africans do is kill
each other,'' he said. ``That simply is not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that most Africans want to live in peace, just
like most Americans and everyone else,'' he added. ``I worry that
the stereotype to the contrary is going to damage our ability to
work with them in the coming years. So I hope this is one ripple of
reality against this stereotypical current.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
