<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SYRIA-ASSAD18-COX     06-18 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-ASSAD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BASHAR ASSAD CHOSEN TO HEAD COUNTRY'S RULING PARTY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Syria's ruling Baath Party unanimously chose
Bashar Assad to be its leader Sunday, giving him an expected but
important boost toward replacing his father as the country's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's appointment as the party's secretary general continued
the almost mechanical execution of political steps meant to ensure
a smooth transfer of power in this country of about 17 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   The move also places him on the party's Regional Command
Council, a membership required of all presidents.
</P>
<P>
   President Hafez Assad, 69, died June 10 after nearly 30 years in
power. Though he had chronic health problems, the death came
suddenly, and Syrian leaders quickly made clear that Bashar Assad
would ascend to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Assad is just 34 years old and was training in ophthalmology in
London until 1994. That was when his older brother, Basil, who had
been groomed for the presidency, died in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's leaders have been quick to fortify Assad's rise to
power. After his father's death, the parliament rushed to remove
the constitutional requirement that presidents be at least 40 years
old. Then, Assad was appointed head of the army.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Hafez Assad's death, the Baath Party had been
expected at this meeting to give his son his first government post,
likely vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The party, which has dominated Syrian politics for nearly 40
years, is rooted in socialist ideology and largely followed the
dictates of the late president. It had not held a party congress
for 15 years before this week.
</P>
<P>
   In another move Sunday, the party voted reaffirm the late
president's stand on making peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   That position is based on Syria recovering all of the Golan
Heights, a strategic highland that Israel captured in 1967. Peace
talks with Israel broke off in January, and U.S. officials have
been trying to restart them.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of his political beliefs, Assad's positions on peace
with Israel are little known accept that they track those of his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Since he began preparing for the presidency, Assad has headed a
campaign to root out government corruption. He also appeared to
support, through his attendance at conferences and heading of
special committees, business reform and the spread of modern
information technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's economy is rife with government monopolies and
inefficiencies. Internet use is limited by a system of licensing
and restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Baath Party may officially nominate Assad as their
presidential candidate on Monday, repeating a move already taken by
the Syrian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament may appoint him president June 25, and Syrian
voters are expected to ratify that choice in a referendum around
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Assad can hold power remains to be seen. Before his
father, Syrian politics were characterized by turmoil, coups and
short-lived governments.
</P>
<P>
   Assad will face resistance from those in power opposed to his
anti-corruption campaign. He will also have to win the respect of
those skeptical of the dynastic handing over of power from father
to son.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Assads are from the minority Alawite religious
sect, and Assad could face resistance from the Sunni Muslim
majority, which arose against his father in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow's e-mail address is larryk(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
