u f BC-INTERNET-MESSAGES-840     06-18 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MESSAGES-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE ASPECT OF MESSAGES ON THE INTERNET TO BE DELAYED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Mass.) By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the explosive popularity of instant-messaging programs
on the Internet, it became apparent last week that one facet of the
service may not be instant at all: It may be a year or more before
users of competing instant-messaging services can send missives to
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than a year of wrangling between America Online,
the industry leader by far, and its competitors, the fate of this
service, which permits users to send messages over the Internet
that quickly pop up on a recipient's screen, remains mired in
technical and political snags.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday was the deadline for proposals to an industry
committee charged with creating standards to permit instant
messages to be sent among users of the dozen or so competing
programs. Six proposals came in. But the one that carried the most
immediate weight was from AOL, which controls roughly 90 percent of
the instant-messaging traffic and which has stymied efforts of
competitors seeking to communicate with its 90 million
instant-messaging users.
</P>
<P>
   Given the growing popularity of instant messaging, which now has
between 100 million and 120 million users all told, the stakes are
profound for consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The competitors have asked the federal government to look into
AOL's dominant market position in instant messaging as part of its
review of the company's proposed merger with Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers say that the current situation, in which
there is no interoperability, could be compared to a telephone
system in which different services, like Sprint and AT&AMP;T, would be
unable to place telephone calls to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the initial reaction from competitors to AOL's
proposal submitted Thursday was cautious skepticism, but in the
days following it has become more hostile. AOL's rivals contend
that its proposal is general, providing little technical detail or
time frame about how and when a standard will be achieved _ in
effect, the proposal is a stall tactic.
</P>
<P>
   And some proponents of interoperability say it may now be more
than a year before instant message users from different services
will be able to communicate if they wait for a protocol to be
created.
</P>
<P>
   The submission, ``is very high-level and esoteric,'' said Ross
Bagully, chief executive of Tribal Voice Inc., an instant messaging
service based in Denver. ``There is no hard time frame of what AOL
will do and when,'' he said, adding, ``It could be 18 months before
there is interoperability.''
</P>
<P>
   The standards were proposed to the Internet Engineering Task
Force, a group in which participation is voluntary and findings are
nonbinding. V.J. Saraswat, co-chairman of the instant messaging
committee, said AOL's 18-page submission is a ``document of value''
that requires serious analysis. But he conceded that the deadline
was for specific technical protocols, while AOL only sent in a
framework for creating protocols.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, AOL said it published issues that it says must be
addressed as part of any solution that will let hundreds of
millions of Internet users send instantaneous messages. Among its
concerns, AOL says it wants to safeguard security for its users by,
for example, ensuring ways they can block messages from senders
they deem undesirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely sincere'' about achieving interoperability,
said Tricia Primrose, an AOL spokeswoman. She said that the
document submitted Thursday was ``a significant first step toward
developing detailed protocols.''
</P>
<P>
   If this debate sounds familiar _ with AOL saying privacy and
security must be guarded, and competitors saying AOL is stalling to
prevent true interoperability _ that is because it has raged for
more than a year. Last summer, AOL was battling with competitors,
including Microsoft, which used technical loopholes to contact AOL
instant messaging users, causing AOL to accuse competitors of
hacking into its system and to continually patch those holes.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth has been a theme during the year. In fact,
Odigo, a New York-based messaging service with 800,000 members,
said that seven times this year it had found a way to direct
messages from its users to AOL users, but that each time it had
been blocked, including twice in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Now the debate has taken on newfound impetus in light of AOL's
proposed merger with Time Warner. Competitors, including Tribal
Voice, have asked for an investigation from federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are political, but they also touch a growing number
of users, both individual and corporate. Forrester Research, a
market research group in Cambridge, Mass., reports that 36 percent
of Fortune 1000 companies use instant messaging, known in the
industry as ``IM,'' and project the number will grow to 46 percent
by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Navi Radjou, an analyst with electronic business applications
for Forrester, said the debate is taking on newfound significance
because of the business users, noting that ``the next battleground
in the IM space is the corporate world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Radjou said that, even under an optimistic scenario, it will be
March or April of next year before there are protocol standards to
permit interoperability. This analysis was echoed by Saraswat, from
the task force, who projected it will take six months to a year for
his group to come up with a protocol gleaned from the various
proposals, including submissions from a group at Fujitsu and one
from a group at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Bagully, from Tribal Voice, said that if the industry truly
was committed to reaching interoperability, it could do so ``in a
couple of months.'' And, in fact, he said a number of AOL's top
competitors are in discussions to open their own systems to one
another, which, he said the group could do ``in a heartbeat'' if
everyone was committed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, people within the industry said that if AOL or other
companies were willing to embrace a temporary solution, they could
enable messages to be sent to one another in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Avner Ronen, chief executive of Odigo, said simple
interoperability could be achieved almost immediately, but creating
fully functional systems could take a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions that would have to be answered are not just
the technical specifications of how to enable communication, but
also the privacy and security safeguards the industry decides are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires the cooperation of all companies,'' Ronen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
