<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will surround a slow-moving front
stretched from the Mississippi Valley to southern Virginia. A few
of the thunderstorms will cause flooding as the front undercuts and
lifts very humid air. The risk for flooding will be heightened from
northeast Texas to southern Missouri, where a jet stream
disturbance passing overhead will augment the ascent of the sultry
air mass.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Southeast will be partly sunny and humid, with
isolated thunderstorms, while clouds depart the Northeast and Ohio
Valley as high pressure directs drier air into the area.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty breezes from the south will draw higher humidity into the
Plains, setting the stage for late-day storms in northern sections.
The Pacific states will be dry and very warm, though onshore
breezes will bring patchy clouds and cooler air to the coast.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: IT'S THE HUMIDITY
</P>
<P>
   On a warm day, more than 10 million sweat glands moisten the
human body with as much as two quarts of water per hour. As
perspiration evaporates from the surface of the skin, the skin is
cooled. This evaporation of sweat is the body's main mechanism for
dissipating heat. However, the rate of evaporation slows as
humidity increases. When humidity and heat are high, body moisture
begins to collect on the skin in beads, with little or no
evaporation taking place. At this stage, the body's cooling system
is operating at very low efficiency, leaving people feeling very
uncomfortable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
