<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-2     06-18 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ELECTION REFORMS, VOTE-BUYING CHARGES PLAGUE MEXICO'S
RULING PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Much has changed in Mexico to make the current
campaign for the presidency the fairest and most competitive in the
country's history.
</P>
<P>
   The media have been opened up to broadcast free-wheeling
debates, better election monitoring has reduced the governing
party's margin for fraud, and for the first time it looks as if an
opposition candidate may actually be given a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   What has not changed is what opposition leaders say are the
governing party's long-entrenched practices of vote-buying,
coercion and doling out of pork. In fact, some election observers
say, such things are worse than ever, perhaps because in a
stunningly close race in which so much else has been altered, they
remain the party's most reliable, time-tested tools.
</P>
<P>
   Instances of irregularities, from the artful to the absurd, have
been documented all across Mexico in recent days as the election,
now just two weeks away, approaches.
</P>
<P>
   In one Yucatan village last week, the state governor himself
handed out 1,003 washing machines to poor women.
</P>
<P>
   In Tabasco state, officials appeared suddenly with disaster
funds _ delayed since flooding in October _ and paid homeowners who
support the governing party $600, and paid those who support the
opposition $200.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare mothers and corn farmers in 13 states have reported
being told that they will be cut off from cash payments unless they
pledge to vote for Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the
governing party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, civil servants from a string of government
ministries and state-run institutions, like the national oil
company Pemex, have stepped forward to complain that superiors are
threatening to dismiss them unless they campaign for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not seen a campaign before this in which such vast
resources have been spent to buy votes, and such tremendous efforts
made to twist voters' arms,'' said Rogelio Gomez Hermosillo,
director of Alianza Civica, a watchdog group that has monitored 50
federal and state elections in Mexico since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's tactics have provided an extraordinary demonstration
of the still-robust powers of the aparato, the nationwide machinery
of political control exercised by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party during its seven decades in power.
</P>
<P>
   Recent election polls have shown Labastida to be locked in a
close race with Vicente Fox, a former governor who has attracted
opposition votes from across the political spectrum. Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, a leftist former mayor of Mexico City, is running a
distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas and Fox have been trading bitter attacks, but last week
the deluge of vote-buying reports so angered both men that they
signed a pact to coordinate efforts to prevent further vote
coercion.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, accusing the PRI of ``blackmailing citizens for
votes,'' warned he might not accept the election results as
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of incidents of voter coercion, many with an eerily
similar ring suggesting a systematic effort coordinated from Mexico
City, have been documented by a congressional elections oversight
committee, and by at least three independent watchdog groups.
</P>
<P>
   Some hard-line PRI leaders have acknowledged that a central PRI
strategy has been to persuade officials who administer government
social programs to use them to benefit the Labastida campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government's social programs are PRI programs, and
we're going to use them to win the presidency,'' Manuel Bartlett, a
former interior minister working in the Labastida campaign, said
last month.
</P>
<P>
   But Marco Provencio, a spokesman, said President Ernesto Zedillo
had insisted that members of his government obey laws barring
officials from using government resources on behalf of candidates.
``If opposition parties believe programs have been used in illegal
ways, let them turn over their evidence to the authorities,''
Provencio said.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional committee monitoring the presidential campaign
has received 86 complaints about the use of government resources to
benefit mostly PRI candidates. It has drawn up a dozen complaints
for presentation to the special prosecutor for election crimes,
said Rep. Elodia Gutierrez, the congresswoman from Fox's National
Action party who heads the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buying of votes has been flagrant,'' she said last week.
But in an interview, she held out little hope that officials
suspected of electoral crimes would be charged.
</P>
<P>
   The special prosecutor, who has had law enforcement
responsibilities in dozens of elections since his office was
founded in 1994, has never indicted a single person on charges of
vote-buying, vote-coercion or diverting government resources to a
political campaign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In several recent cases, law enforcement officials in states
governed by the PRI have themselves been discovered in what
opposition leaders say are election-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Merida, Yucatan, officials at the local headquarters of Fox's
campaign, after hearing noises, waited at night with a videocamera.
They filmed uniformed Yucatan state police officers on their roof,
tampering with telephone wires. Other intruders had penetrated into
the National Action Party's offices.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Alberto Castaneda, the party's state president, filed a
complaint, but the Yucatan authorities brushed the matter aside,
saying the police had been investigating a burglary, Castaneda said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In Morelia, the capital of Michoacan, another state controlled
by the PRI, doctors from the state attorney general's office handed
out medicines, confiscated by the state police from criminals, to
voters in poor neighborhoods who agreed to sign a pledge to vote
for PRI candidates, according to a complaint filed by Rep.
Guadalupe Sanchez, a congresswoman from Cardenas' party.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of abuses began emerging in May, shortly after
Labastida stumbled in the first candidate debate. To strengthen his
faltering campaign, he met with dozens of federal officials and
state governors to plead for help.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential aides said public servants would campaign only in
their free time, but subsequent events have suggested that many
bureaucrats responded to Labastida's call by virtually abandoning
official duties to campaign full time, often from their offices.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, senior officials from the System for the
Development of Families, a taxpayer-financed welfare agency, called
its 150 top bureaucrats to a meeting during working hours in an
auditorium at headquarters, Maria del Refugio Montoya, a senior
researcher at the agency, said in an interview. The bureaucrats
were told to organize gatherings with friends and neighbors at
which they were to present a Labastida video and elicit vote
pledges, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya's supervisor ordered her to organize one of the
Labastida events. ``Do we have to do this?'' Montoya asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes we have to _ or do you want to have problems?'' her
supervisor responded, Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Another civil servant to complain was Ramiro Berron, a senior
technician at Pemex, the government oil monopoly. Last week, he
said in a public letter to his colleagues at Pemex that he and
other employees had been ordered to campaign for Labastida using
government cars, telephones and other resources, on threat of
dismissal. He noted that civil service laws bar public servants
from using state resources for political activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bosses are threatening to fire you, but don't be tricked
into committing crimes,'' his letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Progresa, which channels cash payments from the Social
Development Ministry to 2.6 million poor women, is the government
program used most systematically to favor the PRI, said Gutierrez,
the oversight committee chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Jarque, the secretary of social development, said last
week that his agency was working energetically to keep Progresa
free from political manipulation. A letter distributed to Progresa
beneficiaries reminded them that the program did not obligate them
to vote for any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Jarque's two predecessors resigned from the Zedillo Cabinet
to work for Labastida, and this spring the senior official in
charge of Progresa's computerized list of beneficiaries also joined
the campaign. Progresa beneficiaries in dozens of villages in 13
states have since complained that they have been told by the
program's village-level organizers that unless they pledge to vote
for Labastida they will be cut from Progresa.
</P>
<P>
   In the Yucatan village of Cuzama, for instance, a Mayan mother
of four who receives a $106 government check every two months said
her neighborhood Progresa coordinator convoked a May 23 meeting at
which Labastida pamphlets were distributed to 80 women. The
coordinator, Gladys Arjona, told them to put their names and voter
identification numbers on a Labastida sign-up sheet, three who
attended said in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't, you'll lose your Progresa,'' Arjona announced,
the three women said. Arjona, who lives in a house shaded by banana
trees, acknowledged that she was host for the Labastida meeting.
``But everything was voluntary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby town of Uman, preparations began two days in
advance for the June 11 rally with Yucatan's governor, Victor
Cervera, at which he distributed 1,003 portable washing machines.
PRI supporters who had signed up to receive the washers were called
to city hall to make an $11 down payment and to turn over their
voter identification cards to a local PRI leader. The town's 200
town workers were told that they had to attend the governor's rally
or forfeit three days' pay, a municipal employee said.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the rally, the police blocked streets around
Uman's central plaza, and municipal workers unloaded the washers
from trucks, stacking them in front of city hall. After dark, PRI
squads fanned out through the town, splashing whitewash on walls
painted with Fox advertisements. At 8 a.m. Sunday, the governor's
convoy arrived, and Cervera officially handed out the washers, to
chants of ``Long Live the PRI!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
