A7641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JACKET-THEATER-REVIEW     06-18 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKET-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROAD-BRUSH HOLLYWOOD SATIRE COULD USE A MORE SKILLFUL HAND 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Straight-Jacket,'' a comedy by Richard Day, is set
in Hollywood in the 1950s, a setting it uses to suggest a parallel
between anti-gay bias and the House Un-American Activities
Committee. The show, which opened Sunday at Playhouse 91 in New
York, concerns a gay matinee idol who, to keep up appearances, is
coerced by the head of a movie studio into marrying a ditzy
secretary; at the same time the McCarthyites are threatening to
shut down the studio unless a big-name star confesses to being a
Communist.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of loopy, contrived setup that a Capraesque touch,
sophisticated and warmhearted, might exploit to advantage. But Day,
a first-time playwright, has created a dull-witted script that
exhausts any sympathy one might feel for his characters long before
they are declared to live happily ever after. Compounding the
problem, Day, a television producer and writer by trade, has
directed his own script here, employing an unwieldy, twin-turntable
set by Ray Recht, and a pacing that emphasizes exit lines before
each of the many scene changes, as if the show were about to cut to
a commercial. Gail Brassard's vivid costumes stand out as
anomalously bright.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the plot do not warrant critical recounting.
Suffice it to say that the intention is broad satire, which takes
the form of mere exaggeration, and that a celebrity's vanity, an
innocent girl's naivete, a mogul's corruption, an agent's cynicism
and a love object's good heart are pounded to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist, Guy Stone (played by John Littlefield, who was
cast, evidently, for his resemblance to Rock Hudson), is the
embodiment of sex-obsessed promiscuity, which is communicated with
a parade of smutty double-entendres and bluntly suggestive
embraces. His wife, Sally (Carrie Preston), believes Guy's sudden
declaration of love even though he has ignored her entirely until
then, and she's blind to his homosexuality until she finds dirty
magazines and an obscene sex toy hidden in the bedroom armoire. Her
every aesthetic _ in clothing, home design, movies and music _ is
held up to ridicule for its conventional artlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The studio executive (Mal Z. Lawrence), a manipulative penny
pincher, is a Jew in hiding; he's changed his name to Goldbergini
(yuk yuk), which serves only to illustrate how ham-handed attempts
to send up foolish bias end up reinforcing it instead. And Rick
(Adam Greer), the writer (and Communist _ such complications!) whom
Guy falls for with no perceivable provocation, is wont to say
things like, ``If you told me two months ago that the person
keeping my faith in humanity alive would be Guy Stone. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   You can't help feeling for the actors, who are hard pressed to
charm. With the exception of Jackie Hoffman, a veteran of Second
City, the Chicago improvisational troupe, whose practiced comic
hyperbole surfaces in her role as the agent, the cast seems
perilously close to suffocation by stereotype. At one point Rick is
at work on a new script, and Guy, looking over his shoulder,
counsels him not to use the word ``sex''; the studio censors won't
allow it. But Rick is a reluctant screenwriter, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play,'' he tells Guy. ``You can say whatever you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, 'tis true.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STRAIGHT-JACKET'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Richard Day; sets by Ray Recht; costumes
by Gail Brassard; lighting by F. Mitchell Dana; sound by Peter J.
Fitzgerald; composer, Stephen Edwards; production stage manager,
Tamara K. Heeschen; general manager, Soloway/Levy. Presented by
Mike Sullo. At Playhouse 91, 316 E. 91st St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ron Mathews (Trick, Mike, Jeff, Josh, Salvation Army man,
furniture delivery man, Ray Verrine and Ron), John Littlefield
(Guy), Jackie Hoffman (Jerry), Carrie Preston (Sally), Mal Z.
Lawrence (Saul), Adam Greer (Rick) and Stevie Ray Dallimore
(Freddie).
</P>
</TEXT>
