<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, June 19. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Washington) _ By relaxing rules and applying only a
spotty enforcement of travel restrictions, the Clinton
administration is opening Cuba to American travelers at a rate not
seen in more than 40 years. While administration officials deny
that the increased travel is intended to undermine the 38-year-old
embargo against Cuba, the new flow has given rise to a flurry of
business, personal and political contacts and there is a renewed
push in some circles _ both Democratic and Republican _ to relax
the commercial boycott, one of the last relics of the increasingly
distant Cold War. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Much has changed in Mexico to
make the current race for the presidency the fairest and most
competitive in the country's history. What has not changed,
opposition and election officials say, is the ruling party's
long-entrenched system of vote-buying and coercion. 1700 words. By
Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-III (New Haven, Conn.) _ Born at the earliest fringe of
the baby boom, Bush was pressed during his years at Yale to take
sides in the great battles then unfolding over politics, civil
rights, drugs and music. Mostly he was a noncombatant in those
upheavals, but when forced to choose he ultimately retreated to the
values and ideals established by his parents' generation. Unlike
others of his generation, like Clinton or Gore, Bush never wore his
hair long, agonized over Vietnam, wrestled with existentialism or
cranked up Rolling Stones songs to annoy his parents (instead of
hard rock music, he listened to soul). Even today, Bush thunders in
his stump speeches against boomer-style self-indulgence and appeals
for a ``responsibility era'' that in some respects sounds like the
1950s; he likes values as clean-cut as his hair. 4000 words. By
Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-SECURITY (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ The government was
already facing hurdles in its efforts to prosecute a scientist
accused of mishandling nuclear secrets at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory, but last week's disclosures that two hard drives filled
with highly sensitive weapons data had inexplicably vanished have
potentially made it far more difficult for prosecutors in what had
once been described as a major national security case. The
scientist, Wen Ho Lee, has insisted from the time he was indicted
last year that security breaches at the laboratory are common, and
that the kind of downloading he did -- moving classified data, in
the open, from a secure to unsecured computer, then downloading it
to tapes -- was done frequently by other experts protecting data
from an unreliable computer system. 1500 words. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-U.S.-OPEN (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ The U.S. Open. By Clifton
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   NY-EGAN-INSTALL (New York) _ Edward Egan was officially
installed as New York's archbishop during a simple prayer service
on Sunday at St. Patrick's Cathedral. Egan replaces the late
Cardinal John O'Connor as spiritual leader of 2.4 million Catholics
in New York's archdiocese. An installation Mass scheduled for
Monday will feature a more elaborate ceremony, including a
45-minute procession of 700 priests and an audience filled with
dignitaries and politicians.
</P>
</TEXT>
