<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIO-III-ABRIDGED     06-18 1687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIO-III-ABRIDGED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S TALENT AT YALE WAS THAT OF MAKING FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (A Special Report)  
(Eds: This is the abridged version of BUSH-BIO-III. It is one of a
series of articles on the lives of the presidential candidates.) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ The first time George W. Bush was arrested,
he had just stolen a Christmas wreath.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, then a 20-year-old junior at Yale, was head of a
notoriously rambunctious fraternity, and with the Christmas
holidays approaching, he and some of his buddies had declared
themselves the ``decorating committee.'' They took off for a
festive shopping street, where Bush spotted the wreath in a hotel _
and stole it.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the perfect crime. Bush later recalled that he and
his friends had perhaps had a few beers and were loud and
boisterous. In addition, a police car was approaching.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested Bush and charged him with disorderly
conduct. Eventually the charges were dropped, but the episode
underscored Bush's path through the uproar of the late 1960s: At a
time when many university students risked arrest for their
vociferous political protests, Bush broke the law not out of
principles but for a prank. Others denounced the police as
``pigs,'' while Bush instinctively stood with the establishment, at
the same time that he casually and apparently drunkenly breached
its law.
</P>
<P>
   Born at the earliest fringe of the baby boom, Bush was pressed
in his years at Yale, 1964 to 1968, to take sides in the great
battles then unfolding over politics, civil rights, drugs and
music. Mostly he was a noncombatant in those upheavals, but when
forced to choose he ultimately retreated to the values and ideals
established by his parents' generation.
</P>
<P>
   In short, while some students took to the barricades, Bush took
to the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike others of his generation like Bill Clinton or Al Gore,
Bush never wore his hair long, agonized over Vietnam, wrestled with
existentialism or cranked up Rolling Stones songs to annoy his
parents (instead of hard rock music, he listened to soul).
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Bush thunders in his stump speeches against
boomer-style self-indulgence and appeals for a ``responsibility
era'' that in some respects sounds like the 1950s; he likes values
as clean-cut as his hair.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a rabble-rouser of sorts, but only in the high-spirited
way that fraternity boys a generation earlier had swallowed
goldfish or sat on flagpoles. For all the buffeting that late-night
television has given Bush over questions of drug use, he was in
most respects a very conventional young man, and classmates say
they do not recall him ever using marijuana or other illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yale years can help address one of the fundamental questions
often raised by critics of Bush: Is he smart enough to be
president?
</P>
<P>
   The answer among those who knew him best is overwhelming and
indignant _ absolutely. Many friends are angry that people even ask
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is very smart,'' said Lanny J. Davis, a former
special counsel to President Clinton and a supporter of Al Gore, as
well as a fraternity brother of Bush at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This notion of lightness is totally missing the point. There
are many smart people, intellectually smart as well as
street-smart, who don't have the energy or motivation at times to
act smart, but that doesn't mean they're not smart. There are times
when George coasted through Yale courses or through exams or seemed
overly facetious. But don't mistake that for not being
intellectually acute.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Bush is a low-wattage leader seems to be based
on two factors. First, Bush never was a strong student. His
transcript at Yale, leaked to The New Yorker, shows that he was a
solid C student.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Bush is determinedly nonintellectual. He never seems to
want to play with ideas and hold them up to the light; at parties
he drops the names of baseball teams, not Kierkegaard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would agree that he's not contemplative or reflective,''
said Michael M. Wood, a friend at Yale and at Phillips Academy in
Andover, Mass. ``He's not a guy who would go off by himself
thinking of something. He's more likely to be hiding in a tree to
jump down on somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush rose to be president of the Delta Kappa Epsilon fraternity.
This was a significant achievement, and those who came before and
after him as president did well in the business world, largely
because of the same people skills that propelled them to the top of
DKE.
</P>
<P>
   For a leading presidential candidate, Bush has an unusually
testy relationship with the Eastern establishment, even though he
also has an unusually intimate relationship with it. His
grandparents on both sides were card-carrying members of that
establishment, yet ever since he showed up at Yale as a freshman in
1964, Bush has resolutely cultivated anti-intellectualism and
chafed at what he describes as the arrogance of liberal
intellectual elitists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tension with what he sees as an arrogant Eastern elite,
and his perception of himself as outside it, seem to have arisen
initially from the clash of generations that occurred while he was
at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Bush entirely subscribed to his parents' and grandparents' view
of absolute and immutable values, of privilege balanced by duty.
But at Yale this solid, straightforward world turned upside down. A
moral universe of stark blacks and whites became colorized,
ambiguous and, for young George, disorienting.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates began to feel guilty about their privilege, angry at
their parents, distrustful of business and defiant at the system
itself. For somebody like George W., who was entirely comfortable
in his own skin, all this guilt and upheaval were incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   Kingman Brewster Jr., the legendary president of Yale, moved to
transform the university by admitting women beginning in 1968 and
by restructuring admissions so that young men like George W. Bush _
mediocre students who were children of alumni _ would no longer be
admitted. Indeed, with his grades and college boards Bush might not
have been admitted if he had applied a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   Young George watched wistfully from afar as his father, in the
different political universe of Texas, basked in public respect and
bounced back in 1966 to win a congressional seat and be named
president of the freshman class in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But as the elder Bush became more prominent as a Republican
congressman who supported the Vietnam War and opposed some civil
rights legislation, he also became a target of criticism at Yale,
which deeply offended young George.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's loyalty to his father in the Yale years was filial rather
than political. For a son of a politician, Bush was remarkably
oblivious of current affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Other undergraduates at the time _ like the future New York
governor George Pataki, the future Massachusetts senator John Kerry
and the future federal judge J. Harvie Wilkinson III _ were active
in campus politics, while at the law school the future senator
Joseph Lieberman was launching his own political career.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was the opposite kind of student: He never joined the
Yale Political Union and rarely spent time talking about civil
rights, the Vietnam War or other upheavals of the day.
</P>
<P>
   u pxxnt06 nt22 nt26 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
upxx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-BUSH-BIO-III-ABRIDGED-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW HAVEN, Conn.: the day. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Race riots erupted in New Haven between Bush's junior and senior
years, anti-war ``teach-ins'' and protests multiplied, and students
burned draft cards. The upheaval may have left George W. Bush
uncomfortable, but friends remember him as cheerful, vigorously
involved in intramural sports at Davenport, his residential
college, and laughing with friends over beers. Roommates recall him
studying the class register and memorizing names of classmates, and
he clearly made friendships a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``George probably knew 1,000 of the 4,000 undergraduates at
Yale,'' said Betts. ``There probably was no one else who knew
200.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's junior year, he was admitted to Skull and Bones, a
secret society then made up of 15 of the most promising, talented
or socially prominent men in each class. There have been reports
that he was ``tapped'' by his father, who himself was a Bonesman,
but an outgoing senior and Bonesman, David Alan Richards,
acknowledges that it was he who tapped Bush that night.
</P>
<P>
   For a man like George W. who complains about elitism, Skull and
Bones was an odd group to enter. It was the epitome of exclusivity,
carefully choosing its members each year to undergo an elaborate
initiation procedure in a windowless ``tomb'' that only members
were allowed to enter.
</P>
<P>
   If entry into Skull and Bones opened Bush to accusations of
snobbery, it also meant association with a community of gifted
people with whom Bush would form lifelong friendships _ and Bush's
strategy at Yale was clearly to build up not a great transcript but
great friendships. It was also a perfectly reasonable strategy, for
one could argue that Yale graduates in the 1960s went further on
the networks they made than on the grades they earned.
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly true of Bush. He was not quite John Belushi
in ``Animal House,'' but like many of his DKE fraternity brothers
he did manage what could politely be called a full life. For
starters, DKE was notorious for its rowdy weekend parties _
attended by Yale men and by women from nearby women's colleges _ in
which alcohol was so plentiful that party-goers periodically threw
up or passed out.
</P>
<P>
   So young George Bush floated along through the turbulence of the
1960s and into the 1970s, unsure about what he might do in life.
When he received his Yale diploma in 1968, he had third-rate
grades, second-rate accomplishments and no firm career prospects.
There was just one area where he had excelled: He had a huge number
of very close friends, and long after course grades were forgotten,
those friends would stand by him, reach into their pockets for him
and help propel him into politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
