<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA ACCUSES U.S. TROOPS OF INCREASING RISK OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Shattering the calm brought by last week's
historic reconciliation talks, North Korea on Sunday accused the
United States, which has 37,000 troops stationed in South Korea, of
increasing the danger of war in the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States imperialists pretend to be interested in
peace and detente in the Korean peninsula, but their actions only
result in increasing the danger of war and escalating tensions,''
said the Rodong Shinmun, the leading newspaper for the North Korean
Worker's Party.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation, which was carried by the North's overseas news
outlet, the Korean Central News Agency, came just two days after
the United States said that it had no plans to withdraw American
troops from South Korea, despite a landmark agreement between the
two Koreas to pursue peace and reunification.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has long demanded the removal of U.S. troops based
in the South, arguing that the Americans were preparing to go to
war.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of the historic meeting last week, however,
Sunday's denunciation seemed intended to thrust the United States
firmly into the middle of the Korean peace process _ a position
that Washington has long sought to avoid, encouraging, instead,
that the Koreas negotiate their own peace.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has repeatedly tried to strike its own diplomatic
accords with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now that North and South are inching closer together, the United
States appears unwilling to give up its foothold in the Korean
peninsula, a development North Korea seems willing to exploit,
particularly in light of apparently increasing resistance among
South Koreans to having the Americans stay forever in their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's pointed statement from North Korea did not specify how
the United States was increasing tensions in the peninsula.
However, the Communist country _ and its allies in China and Russia
_ object both to the strong American presence here and to American
plans for a missile defense shield that Washington says is
primarily intended to guard against attack from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence and defense officials say that North Korea
is developing its own long-range ballistic missiles and nuclear
weapons. North Korea is concerned, regional analysts say, that the
United States will share its missile defense system with
Washington's allies in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Korea plans to use the issue of the troops and the
theater missile defense as a bargaining chip, which has the
potential to derail the entire process,'' of reconciliation between
the two Koreas, said Park Young Ho, director of the Center for
North Korean Society and Human Rights, a research institute funded
by the South Korean government. ``In the aftermath of the Korean
summit, North Korea is hardening its position through peace _ it
wants more positive security assurances from the United States,''
Park said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have welcomed the summit as a positive step
toward easing tensions and expressed support for further talks, but
they have ruled out discussion of withdrawing American troops as
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years of tension on the Korean peninsula will not
evaporate in one meeting,'' a spokesman for the National Security
Council, Lt. Col. David B. Stockwell, said Sunday. ``Any discussion
of troop strengths or any number of other issues will have to be
addressed as the process moves forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN on Saturday, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman
of the Foreign Relations Committee, said the summit should force a
reconsideration of the deployment of troops in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to consider it,'' he said. ``And after deliberation,
we can determine whether it's time to bring them out. It's too
early for anybody to say we ought to bring them out now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first face-to-face meeting between Korean heads of state,
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim
Jong Il signed a broad pact last week calling for an end to
decades-long aggression on the peninsula, reuniting of families
separated by war, and economic and other ties.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return to Seoul, South Korean President Kim declared
that the ``danger of war on the Korean peninsula had disappeared.''
But tensions remain high along the demilitarized zone, a heavily
fortified buffer that divides North and South. North Korea has
close to 1 million troops situated in the DMZ, while South Korea
has stationed half a million soldiers there, backed by the 37,000
American troops.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean military officials have long argued that their
troops alone cannot deter an invasion by North Korea. They also
depend on the United States for military intelligence. A recent
South Korean military report concluded that North Korea had
stockpiled between 2,500 and 5,000 tons of biological and chemical
weapons it planned to use in the event of an invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Kim Dae-jung said that during the Pyongyang talks, he
had explained to Kim Jong Il exactly why a continued U.S. military
presence was necessary for regional security, but the officials
declined to say how the North Korean leader responded.
</P>
<P>
   The United States spends about $3 billion a year to maintain its
troops in South Korea. To help shoulder the burden, South Korea
pays the United States about $315 million a year in cash, and
provides $1.3 billion in tax breaks, free use of land and other
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls taken since the summit meeting indicate
that a majority of South Koreans surveyed believe that war is now
highly unlikely on the peninsula and that reunification will take
place within five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the summit meeting, there were growing voices of
opposition to U.S. military bases in South Korea. On Saturday,
hundreds of people demanding a withdrawal of U.S. troops clashed
with riot police near an American Air Force bombing range about 50
miles southwest of Seoul. The anti-American protests have increased
since early March when a U.S. fighter jet with engine trouble
dropped six bombs on the range. United States and South Korean
investigators said that the bombs caused no injuries, but local
villagers said that six people were hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
