u a BC-APPALACHIAN-CINEMA061     06-18 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPALACHIAN-CINEMA0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Closed N.C. theater mourned, but town hopes for revival
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORGANTON, N.C. _ With arms crossed and dripping wet from the
swimming pool, sixth-grader Amanda Scott had just one thing to say
about life after the closing of the Mimosa Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be real boring,'' the 11-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 88 years, Morganton, N.C., has no movie
theater.
</P>
<P>
   The shock has worn down in the nearly three months since one of
the nation's largest theater chains, Carmike Cinemas Inc. of
Columbus, Ga., pulled out of town. But now with children out of
school, facing another seven weeks without a local theater, people
in Morganton, in Appalachia's foothills, are longing for a summer
tradition as familiar as fireflies after dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked to eat the popcorn and watch the movies,'' said Austin
Phipps, a freckle-faced 7-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Kids in the town 60 miles east of Asheville are tugging on
grown-ups to drive them to out-of-town movies. In Hickory, 20 miles
to the east, Carmike operates two theaters. One is a 12-screen
complex that since opening in 1998 has drawn some of Morganton's
moviegoers, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer can people, such as sisters Janelle and Michala
Michaux, walk to the Mimosa, the run-down theater across from Burke
County's courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rent movies, but that is not the same,'' said Melodie
Michaux, mother of Janelle, 14, and Michala, 12. ``The Mimosa was a
social gathering spot. Home is not as much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mimosa opened in 1939, with a flashy Art Deco facade in a
town built on native gray stone. Old-timers remember a quarter
covering admission, popcorn and a drink. Afterward, in the cool
evenings, they sat on the rock wall around the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   When it closed in late March, with a final showing of ``Snow
Day'' and ``The Next Best Thing,'' the two-screen Mimosa theater
smelled rank. The floor was sticky with spilled soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the joke of the town, but it was still a theater,''
said Sharon Jablonski, the city official in charge of redeveloping
Morganton's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The Mimosa charged $1.50 for admission to first-run movies that
arrived in Morganton a few weeks after their release. Carmike also
closed a two-screen theater on Morganton's bypass highway.
</P>
<P>
   But the pieces appear to be falling in place for a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Morganton officials and local developers are meeting today,
hoping to nail down a deal to preserve the Mimosa's historic facade
and lobby, gut the remainder and enlarge it for eight screens, an
arcade and a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   If the Morganton City Council approves loaning $500,000 to the
$2.6 million project, developer Brad Norvell said work could start
as soon as this week. It should be completed before another summer
rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to fathom no theater. We all grew up with them,''
Jablonski said. ``But we will certainly wind up with something much
nicer than we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
