<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GILBERTO-MUSIC-REVIEW     06-18 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILBERTO-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOAO GILBERTO: A QUIET SIGH AT THE HEART OF BOSSA NOVA  

</HEADLINE>
   By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joao Gilberto began his Carnegie Hall concert on
Friday night in a rather agitated state, as did his audience. He
was an hour late getting to the stage. Looking a little bit like
Hunter S. Thompson in a pair of dark glasses, he explained that he
had locked his regular spectacles in his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors and guesses that preceded this simple explanation
were proof of the enduring fascination with Gilberto, who has a
Greta Garbo-like reputation for hermitism and perfectionism. First
it was announced that President Clinton's motorcade had slowed down
traffic in Midtown Manhattan, making it hard for Gilberto to get to
the show. But word got around that he was staying at a hotel less
than a block away, and another part of the myth clicked in among
aficionados: since he reputedly doesn't go anywhere by foot, he
must have been snagged in traffic while simply riding around the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   What's truly fascinating about Gilberto is the length of time he
has spent working on the same songs in the same way. His first
bossa novas, in the late 1950s, were perfect distillations lasting
two minutes or less; the clever pushing and pulling between his
stammering guitar rhythms and his voice, and the shrewd, quiet,
no-vibrato blankness of his singing style helped create a
languorous, innocent mood in popular culture shared by the Western
world: James Dean, ``The Red Balloon,'' Chet Baker, bossa nova.
</P>
<P>
   Since then his recorded output has remained small. And if he
isn't always playing his early repertory _ his first new album in
nine years, ``Joao Voz e Violao'' (Verve/Universal) contains seven
songs he hasn't recorded before _ the style of his music sounds to
all but the most trained ear like a continuing extension of his
first eureka moment.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday night's concert, part of the JVC Jazz Festival, he
lingered over this slowly widening battery of songs. He has written
only a few of them; the rest were composed by Antonio Carlos Jobim,
Carlos Lyra, Dorival Caymmi and other Brazilian songwriters of the
1950s. But Gilberto has rather radically personalized them all and
made them uniform, so that his versions are the ones you tend to
hear in your head.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's concert offered some famous numbers and withheld
others. (``Desafinado,'' ``Corcovado,'' ``Wave,'' ``Samba de Uno
Nota So,'' yes; ``The Girl From Ipanema,'' ``Chega de Saudade,''
``A Felicidade,'' no.) Unlike Willie Nelson or Louis Armstrong, two
other singers who worked out comparably original rhythmic concepts
in popular music, Gilberto uses barely any improvisation in his
performance. It is ritual by re-enactment, the purpose of which is
to arrive at a place of concentration where his tiniest vocal
susurations _ his pronunciation of P's and B's, the opening of his
lips to sing a line, the single word ``janela'' (window) _ become
jolts.
</P>
<P>
   Other than apologizing for being late and wearing dark glasses,
his only spoken words were requests to the sound crew for more bass
in his voice and more guitar. His concern paid off: By the song
``Estate,'' halfway through, the show was a seance.
</P>
<P>
   Gilberto possesses the definition of a ``head'' voice, and much
of his singing has a nasal quality suggesting a muted trombone.
Almost conversationally, he connected phrases for several bars at a
time; there were the slightest changes here and there, like the
elongation of syllables in ``Corcovado'' and the rushing of lyrics
in ``One Note Samba'' that left the guitar lines lagging behind.
Positioning his picking hand above the strings, like a classical
guitarist, he kept a steady bass line with his thumb on the first
and third beat; the rest of his hand played syncopated havoc with
time.
</P>
<P>
   He played a set that included bossa novas, an older samba-cancao
(once sung in a 1940s croon but refigured to suit him), and George
Gershwin's `` 'S Wonderful.'' Gilberto is drawn toward poems of
observation and memory: on waiting for a woman (``Rosa Morena,'')
his home state of Bahia (Gilberto Gil's ``Eu Vim da Bahia''), the
ineffable effect of samba on ducks (``O Pato'') and humans (``Samba
da Minha Terra'').
</P>
<P>
   It's all a long sigh, originating from somewhere deep inside.
Toward the end of a nearly two-hour concert, the opening jitters
long gone, it seemed as if he had found his way to that place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
