<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7665 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     06-18 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTER OSCAR PLAYS VICTIM CARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oscar De La Hoya the coddled has become Oscar De
La Hoya the victim, at least in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The now-former WBC welterweight champion had been beaten fairly
and squarely by Shane Mosley on Saturday at Staples Center but
lashed out afterward as if the boxing world that has warmly
embraced him his entire career has suddenly turned against him.
</P>
<P>
   He stunned those at a post-fight news conference by implying he
was the victim of a calculated decision to give Mosley this fight
so others involved in the promotion could cash in on a rematch and
possibly a third fight.
</P>
<P>
   And, he would point out, this comes after he was cheated in his
loss to Felix Trinidad in September.
</P>
<P>
   He's so frustrated, so bitter, he said he'd consider retirement
rather than subject himself again to the evils of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to rethink my whole game plan in life,'' he said. ``I
know the (boxing) business. People want a rematch (with Mosley). I
have to think about my health and career and my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I trained very hard. When I see things like this happen,
it turns me off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they give me the decision, there's no (second or) third
fight. Now, there has to be a rematch. ... It's tough to live with
what goes on around boxing. Maybe tomorrow I'll feel different.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the point, however misguided it is.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, De La Hoya, who believes he won a close fight, didn't
have a grasp on reality when he made these statements.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is that the majority of people at ringside saw the fight
along the lines of Lou Filippo (116-112) and Pat Russell (115-113),
the judges who gave Mosley the victory. The Daily News and
Associated Press both scored it 116-112 Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is that this fight was in no way a repeat of De La Hoya-
Trinidad in Las Vegas, in which almost everyone who saw the fight
believes De La Hoya did enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is that De La Hoya could've kept his belt had he won the
terrific 12th round. Had Russell scored the round for De La Hoya,
his final tally would've been 114-114 and the result would've been
a draw.
</P>
<P>
   However, (begin ital)no one(end ital) would've scored the final
three minutes in De La Hoya's favor, not even Marty Sammon, who had
the former champ winning 115-113 but gave Mosley the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, fresher and stronger in the end, landed twice as many
punches as De La Hoya in one of the more memorable - but clearly
one-sided - rounds in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is that the officials associated with the fighters and
the bout had no compelling reason to cheat De La Hoya. Had he won,
he would have continued to generate a tremendous amount of money
for all involved no matter who his next opponent might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Money follows the guy wherever he goes.
</P>
<P>
   And, from a long-term perspective, boxing seems to thrive only
when it has a superstar leading the way, a superstar like De La
Hoya. To tear him down is to tear down the sport.
</P>
<P>
   None of it makes sense, even in a sport capable of anything.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson to be learned here for De La Hoya isn't that people
are out to get him. It's that sometimes life isn't fair (the
Trinidad fight) and that no one wins every time out (the Mosley
fight) - not even the Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, (begin ital)he(end ital) was the benefactor of
controversial decisions earlier in his career. Many believe to this
day that he was beaten by both Pernell Whitaker and Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   Now - against both Trinidad and Mosley - is simply his turn to
be on the unfortunate side of tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A true champion doesn't whine about how the world is out to get
him. He accepts life's setbacks, learns from them and hopefully
emerges a better person - and better fighter - as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensible thing De La Hoya said all night is that maybe
he'll feel differently tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   He probably will. He won't retire. Too young (27), too much
money to be made, too much pride.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get his rematch with Mosley perhaps early next year and a
chance to regain his championship and some of the respect he's lost
as a result of the two losses.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, let's hope he's more gracious afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet as Sugar: The fight wasn't over for more than a few hours
and already knowledgeable boxing observers began to assess Mosley's
place among the best fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put him right there with Roy Jones Jr.,'' one said.
``(begin ital)Higher(end ital),'' another said. ``It's Jones,
Mosley, Trinidad,'' injected a third.
</P>
<P>
   That's how high they are on Mosley at the moment. And for good
reason: He was nothing short of brilliant Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He had never been in such a big fight in his life - with 20,744
mostly De La Hoya fans yelling and screaming at Staples Center -
yet he looked as relaxed and comfortable as he is sparring in the
gym.
</P>
<P>
   His poise, apparently the product of his easy-going nature and
supreme confidence in his ability, was striking.
</P>
<P>
   He stood face-to-face with the boxer many believed was the best
in the world and never doubted for a second that he was better.
</P>
<P>
   He had never faced a fighter of De La Hoya's physical strength.
This was only his third fight at 147 pounds after moving up from
135 and (begin ital)he(end ital) appeared to be the stronger of the
two.
</P>
<P>
   It was (begin ital)his(end ital) punches, not De La Hoya's, that
did the most damage.
</P>
<P>
   And those skills were something to behold. Everyone knew he was
one of the most complete fighters in the world. He just never had
the chance to prove it against an opponent of this caliber.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, did he prove it. He is simply better - considerably
better, in some eyes - than De La Hoya. That's the only logical
conclusion after watching Saturday's fight: He had to win the final
six rounds to win the fight and did just that.
</P>
<P>
   He won rounds six through 12 on Pat Russell's card, five of six
according to Lou Filippo and somehow split the rounds on the card
of Marty Sammon.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Mosley will live up to the name
Sugar, the moniker of two of the greatest fighters ever: Sugar Ray
Robinson and Sugar Ray Leonard. At 28, he's only now hitting his
peak.
</P>
<P>
   However, we saw something special Saturday, and he should only
get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you what I was going to do,'' Mosley said, ``and I did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He sure did.
</P>
<P>
   CompuBox: Computer statistics were very tight.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley landed 284 of 678 punches, De La Hoya 257 of 718. Mosley
connected on 174 of 304 power punches, De La Hoya 165 of 448. And
Mosley landed 110 of 374 jabs, De La Hoya 92 of 270.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking number is Mosley's connection rate on power
punches: 57 percent (to De La Hoya's 37 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the statistics don't tell us much.
</P>
<P>
   Second chance: HBO will replay the fight at 10:45 p.m. next
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rosenthal's column appears Mondays in the Daily News. He
can be reached at (818) 713-3618 or on the Internet at
boxwriteraol.com
</P>
</TEXT>
