<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MEASURE0619-COX     06-18 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEASURE0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Measuring the shape we're in
 &HT;    By John McCosh
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Earl Babbitt is tired of bumping his knees on the
backs of airplane seats and squeezing his 6-foot-3-inch frame into
cars made for smaller people.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he did something about it. Babbitt joined hundreds of
people participating in a body measurement study at Georgia Tech
this month. Tech is the final stop on a 12-city U.S. tour that has
drawn thousands of people providing personal statistics that
companies can use to make clothes fit better and cars more
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a tall guy, and I want to put in a vote in for my folks,''
Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   To cast his ballot, the Georgia Tech graduate student adviser
changed into a pair of bike shorts and subjected himself to 40 of
what people in the body sizing business call ``traditional
measurements,'' which are done with calipers and measuring sticks.
Next came the high-tech sizing, a three-dimensional laser scan that
adds Babbitt's image and vital statistics to a database that is
nearing 4,000 people. After 17-second laser scan, Babbitt walked
over to a computer screen to see his image painted in a variety of
angles.
</P>
<P>
   The study is sponsored by the U.S. Air Force and dozens of
private companies concerned that, for most of us, things just don't
fit right. The military last did a body measurement study in the
1950s and then the subjects were mostly physically fit young men.
This $6 million study is by far the most diverse that's been
conducted. Atlanta was chosen as a measuring site specifically to
increase the number of African-Americans in the database.
</P>
<P>
   One early conclusion from the study: Most of us have a
body-image problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've had one woman look at the computer screen
without saying, 'Ugh! I look fat,''' said Beth McCrary, the study's
project director at Georgia Tech. ``We're not happy with
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have athletically trained for weeks before their
measuring appointment. Many suck in their guts as the machine that
lowers the laser scanner begins to hum.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both the fit and flabby come to be measured. Since the
project began two years ago, measurement volunteers have weighed in
at 80 pounds on the low end and 400 pounds at the upper end of the
scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wonder why would a 340-pound person want to
come in here and put on shorts and a sports bra,'' said Scott
Fleming, a consultant with Sytronics, the contractor conducting the
study for the Air Force. ``It's because nothing has fit their whole
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said he's among those who have trouble fitting into the
off-the-rack world created by clothes designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think most people my weight are much shorter than me,''
Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt's dissatisfaction with what the garment industry
provides places him with the majority of American consumers. A 1999
survey by retail consultant Kurt Salmon Associates found that 62
percent of clothes shoppers complain that they can't find anything
that fits well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the American body has changed,'' and
clothes designer haven't kept up,'' said Adelle Kirk, a principal
with Kurt Salmon. ``And, frankly, the consumer has gotten more
demanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Body scanning is one way to answer the growing demands for a
custom fit. The same Kurt Salmon study found 59 percent of people
surveyed would disrobe for the scanners if it meant better-fitting
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. is already offering body scanning for custom
fit clothes at some of its stores. The San Francisco-based blue
jeans maker calls its body scanning program ``Original Spin''. Levi
Strauss is also participating in the Air Force study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to help us in the earliest stages of designing to
better fit the range in body sizes,'' said Jeff Beckman, a
spokesman for Levi Strauss. ``This is the first research of its
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies contributing $40,000 to help fund the study, and
get first crack the data, include airplane manufacturers, car
makers and swimwear makers. The Society of Automotive Engineers is
a lead sponsor of the project and will later sell the data for
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the study began with a military focus. The Air
Force planned to study people in the U.S. and in NATO countries to
figure out how to make equipment such as oxygen masks and flight
suits fit an increasingly diverse group of recruits. In 1992 the
Air Force noticed that clothing and car makers were about to
conduct their own similar studies and pitched a collaborative
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed CAESAR (Civilian American and European Surface
Anthropometry Resource), the researchers took their laser machine
on the road in April 1998. After visiting 10 major cities across
the U.S., the project made stops in San Francisco and Atlanta in an
effort to add more diversity to the sample.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at an African-American woman and Asian woman of
the same height and weight and looked at the shape differences,''
said Kathleen Robinette, director of the CAESAR project. ``It
really impresses how important it is to get people of all racial
groups. The big difference with this study is you get the shape in
3-D, and you can immediately see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the differences, she said, is Asians tend to have shorter
legs for their height than the rest of the population, and
African-Americans tend to have longer legs.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the car companies are likely to customize
interiors for different races.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be able to fit a whole spectrum of people,''
Robinette said. ``What I've heard is they want to have a
one-size-fits-all car. They use it for laying out the interior,
crash testing and packaging.''
</P>
<P>
   The clothing companies are interested in using the data to offer
custom-fit garments. Kirk, of Kurt Salmon, said the customized
market is now probably less than 1 percent of total apparel sales.
But she expects that to grow to as much as 20 percent in the next
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Robinette said consumers won't have to wait that long before
they see results from the survey. Data collected at the first three
cities has been tabulated and forwarded to the companies that paid
the sponsor fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see the benefits as early as next year,'' Robinette
said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers at Georgia Tech will continue measuring people
through the end of June and are still making appointments. They've
measured about 120 people and hope another 130 come in before they
leave town.
</P>
<P>
   The process takes about an hour, starting with filling out forms
and changing into shorts, because the laser doesn't scan through
clothes. Fleming said he learned through trial and error to tell
people they would have to wear the skin-tight clothes. Some people
walked out the door when they saw the bike shorts they were asked
to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes the measuring sticks and calipers. Researchers put
the volunteers on a scale and measure the body 40 different ways,
sitting and standing.
</P>
<P>
   Then the researchers prepare the volunteer for the scanner. They
place 72 adhesive white dots from head to toe, reference points
that show exactly how far one point on the scanned image is from
another. A nylon skull cap is added to cover up the hair.
</P>
<P>
   Then the volunteer stands on a platform centered among four
posts mounted with laser cameras that move up and down for
scanning. The laser is about as powerful as the one at grocery
store checkouts.
</P>
<P>
   And then comes the only painful part of the process. Those
little adhesive dots tend to cling to hair.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT     06-18 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MERCHANTS ENTICE SHOPPERS WITH SWEEPSTAKES 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advertisements touting cash giveaways and other sweepstakes have
cluttered the Internet for years, mostly appearing on search
services and other high-traffic informational Web sites. For
marketers, the object of the game was, and is, to compel
million-dollar dreamers to fork over their e-mail addresses and
other valuable personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, sweepstakes are migrating with increasing frequency
from informational sites to the front pages of Internet merchants.
Last week, for instance, buyers could register to win a trip to
Universal Studios from CDNow, a BMW from Buy.com, and a trip to see
a Dave Matthews Band concert from Borders.com, among many other
come-ons.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the goals are similar to those of advertisers _ namely,
get the consumers' e-mail addresses, and their consent to send
follow-up missives about new products and sales. But for e-commerce
executives, sweepstakes offer other, more immediate benefits,
including the chance to attract new customers and keep existing
customers coming back to the site. And because investors have
diminishing patience for Internet merchants that use generous, if
not ludicrously expensive, product giveaways and free shipping
promotions to snare new customers, e-tailers see sweepstakes as a
much more affordable way to achieve marketing goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``As e-commerce companies look more closely at their marketing
budget, they're shifting more and more of that money into
promotions, and sweepstakes in particular,'' said Steven Krein,
chief executive of Promotions.com, which conducts promotions on
behalf of Internet companies. ``It's much more attractive than
giving price-offs, or giving stuff away with every purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no shortage of original ideas on the Web, one
of the more imaginative sweepstakes offers from e-commerce sites
lately is the ``Win-a-Guy'' sweepstakes from OurHouse.com, which
sells home improvement supplies. In the contest, those who buy
something on the site earn chances to win a week's worth of
services from Lou Manfredini, who goes by the name Mr. Fix-It on a
Chicago radio program and on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea had to do with the tone of sweepstakes in general,
which is that they're fun,'' said Gary Briggs, OurHouse.com's chief
marketing officer. ``We wanted to do more than just say, `Come to
the site, get a free coffee maker.'''
</P>
<P>
   The current Win-a-Guy sweepstakes is OurHouse.com's second such
effort. The first, which ran from February through April, generated
more than 100,000 registrants _ of which 85,000 agreed to accept
marketing messages by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   As with other e-commerce executives who use sweepstakes, Briggs
has changed the campaign to fit his marketing goals of the moment.
When the site rolled out in November, he said, the first contest
was intended to acquire new customers, with a $10 discount for
first-time buyers who registered for the sweepstakes. By contrast,
Briggs said the current contest ``is more about driving people for
repeat visits and purchases.'' And so it rewards repeat buyers with
more chances to win.
</P>
<P>
   The best testament to the success of this promotion, of course,
is the revenue ultimately generated from contest registrants. Those
who entered the first Win-a-Guy sweepstakes bought $30 more in
goods per order than those who did not, Briggs said. And under the
current campaign, repeat customers in the sweepstakes have bought
$20 more in goods per order than other repeat customers.
</P>
<P>
   Such fine-tuning and statistical tracking is not found in most
sweepstakes, said Jim Nail, an analyst with Forrester Research, an
Internet consulting firm. ``We've been shocked at how little
tracking people do for any of their promotions,'' Nail said. ``When
we recently asked about the cost of promotions or what kind of
customers they generated from them, about 60 percent didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hamlin, vice president for operations at iQVC, the
Internet division of the shop-by-television company QVC, said that
when the site ran its only sweepstakes two years ago, iQVC did not
track the success of the program, aside from logging the names and
e-mail addresses of the 19,000 registrants.
</P>
<P>
   That will change, he said, with a new sweepstakes later this
year. That sweepstakes will dovetail with an ongoing contest on the
QVC network, in which announcers disclose a ``lucky number'' eight
times a day. QVC customers whose membership numbers match the lucky
number receive a $10 account credit, and are eligible to win cash
and prizes. Hamlin said the Web site would join the contest,
disclosing lucky numbers periodically and announcing winners.
</P>
<P>
   Integrating the two programs, he said, will enable the company
to lure more television customers to the Internet. ``When we bring
customers to the Web, their yearly purchases increase 25 percent,''
Hamlin said. ``So obviously, the more we can bring over, the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   A frequent refrain of sweepstakes naysayers is that the types of
people who seek quick riches or product giveaways are the least
desirable customers a company could engage. But Jonas Steinman,
co-founder of iWon.com, which is backed by CBS, said such opinions
were baseless. IWon, a so-called portal site, has given away more
than $21 million in sweepstakes cash to registered users since it
started in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-three million out of 190 million adults participated in
a sweepstakes or another game of chance in the U.S. last year,''
Steinman said. ``Contrary to the myth that participants are somehow
lower-end, they're increasingly reflective of the demographics of
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the buying behavior of sweepstakes participants on the
site's shopping channel, Bill Daugherty, iWon's other co-founder,
would not disclose specifics, but said the site's merchant partners
were ``incredibly pleased with the conversion rates of our users.''
</P>
<P>
   CDNow, which sells music CDs online, has also found that
sweepstakes provide fertile ground for customers. According to
Samantha Liss, the company's senior director for brand marketing,
between 8 percent and 12 percent of those who sign up for
sweepstakes and agree to be sent follow-up e-mail messages
eventually become paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow started using sweepstakes on the site at the end of 1997,
Liss said, and now runs one a quarter. The company initially paid
outside experts to manage the campaigns, she said, but now conducts
all such efforts with its own staff members. ``We've got it down to
a turnkey operation now,'' she said. ``We've got almost a template
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   CDNow's promotions manager handles the sweepstakes, she said,
and four other employees devote ``a couple days, tops, per
quarter'' to the events.
</P>
<P>
   Liss said CDNow had been able to extract sponsorship fees from
companies interested in using the sweepstakes as marketing
opportunities. At the end of last year, for example, CDNow ran a
millennium promotion, in which it gave away an Oldsmobile Alero.
Oldsmobile provided CDNow a car to give away, bought advertising
for the event and paid an undisclosed amount to CDNow for
sponsorship rights.
</P>
<P>
   Given such an arrangement, Liss said, the company's sweepstakes
have become a revenue source in their own right _ an invaluable
asset for a business that, like many other e-tailers, is
struggling. Liss declined to say how much revenue the site had
generated from its sweepstakes operations. ``I'll just say it's
been a very nice vehicle for us,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
