<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7680 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-18 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
ON GREENS, HERE'S SOMETHING TO CHEW ON 
</HEADLINE>
 FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So there we were, floating down the Rhine, eating four or five
meals a day prepared by eight French chefs.
</P>
<P>
   We were served goose-liver terrines, rabbit pates, breast of
duckling, sea scallop souffles, filets of beef, wild mushroom
sautes plus crepes, tarts, tortes and Black Forest cake.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? My wife was ecstatic about the lettuce. The leaves
were tiny, delicate and, well, you couldn't get a good grip with
your teeth. It wouldn't have helped if you did, because the lettuce
leaves had as much taste as a cocktail napkin.
</P>
<P>
   It took her three days of research to learn that this green was
called ``mache'' and that you probably couldn't find it in American
markets. That news provided some relief to me.
</P>
<P>
   Romaine lettuce is OK, if it is accompanied in a salad by
shrimp, crab and a Gorgonzola dressing. But when I see somebody
gnawing through a blob of bibb or an undressed slab of iceberg, my
stomach begins to rumble in protest.
</P>
<P>
   If a person has to eat fodder, it should at least taste like
something and provide the consumer with more than a green patch on
a front tooth.
</P>
<P>
   My favorites are beet greens, turnip greens, collards and chard.
They contain far more vitamin C, calcium, iron and beta carotene
than salad greens. They should arrive at the table cooked,
benefiting greatly from their association with bacon grease, onions
and either hot pepper flakes or Tabasco.
</P>
<P>
   My wife allows me two tablespoons of bacon grease each
millennium. So I usually substitute low-fat turkey ham for the
bacon, as in the following recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Great Greens
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds greens
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup diced ham (or six slices bacon)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   You can use collards, turnip greens or a combination of the two.
Rinse them, remove tough stems and chop the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   If you use ham, saute it in the 2 tablespoons of vegetable oil,
then remove. If you want to include bacon, omit the vegetable oil
and fry until crisp, then remove. Leave 2 tablespoons of grease in
the pot.
</P>
<P>
   In the remaining oil or grease, saute the onion until soft but
not browned. Add the chicken broth and half the ham or crumbled
bacon. Bring to a boil, then add the greens in bunches, adding more
as they cook down. Cover the pot and simmer the greens about 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This will serve eight or more with the rest of the bacon and ham
sprinkled across the top. Add red pepper flakes or Tabasco to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   An appropriate main course, to serve with the greens, might be:
</P>
<P>
   Two-Clucker Stew
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 and one-half teaspoons salt (divided)
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 chickens, cut into serving pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 large onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried sage
</P>
<P>
   6 stalks celery
</P>
<P>
   10 medium carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 pound large, fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   On a piece of waxed paper, mix together the flour, paprika, 1
and one-half teaspoons salt and the pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Wash and dry the chicken then roll to cover in the flour
mixture. Save the remainder of the flour mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large skillet and brown the chicken
pieces on both sides, in two batches. Remove to a large pot or
Dutch oven.
</P>
<P>
   Add more olive oil to the pan if needed, and lightly brown the
onions, in two batches. Dump the cooked onions into the pot with
the chicken. Moosh around with a wooden spoon, then add the broth,
basil, sage and the final teaspoon of salt. Bring everything to a
boil, cover, reduce heat and simmer 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each carrot into three or four hunks and add to the stew.
Simmer another 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Clean and quarter the mushrooms. Slice the celery into \-inch
pieces. Add both to the stew along with the lemon juice. Cover and
simmer a final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken pieces and vegetables to a platter in a warm
oven.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat together the egg yolks and half-and-half.
Stir in the leftover flour mixture and keep stirring until you have
a smooth paste.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the liquids left in the pot to a boil. Add a cup of these
pot liquids to the egg mixture, stir until smooth then pour the
whole mess into the pot, stirring until the sauce begins to
thicken.
</P>
<P>
   Pour some of the sauce over the chicken and veggies and pass the
remainder around in a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Serves eight, over split baking-powder biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   What's that green splotch on your front tooth? If it's mache,
you're outa here!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
