<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS' 20TH HOMER SPARKS ANGELS TO 8-6 WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE -- Troy Glaus smacked his 20th home run of the season
to give the Angels a 5-0 lead on their way to an 8-6 win over the
Baltimore Orioles on a hot and humid Sunday afternoon at Camden
Yards, but the 23-year-old third baseman won't let himself get too
excited about the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He's halfway to 40 homers, something no Angel player has ever
done. So what does it mean to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means I know I'll end the season with at least 20,'' he
said. ``I don't put too much weight in it. They're nice to hit but
you never know if you'll hit another one.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Glaus' only hit of the day, but the Angels had
everything else working for them as they finished their nine-game
trip with two consecutive wins after losing five of the first
seven.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn had three hits, Darin Erstad hit a two-run homer, and
Orlando Palmeiro, Tim Salmon, Adam Kennedy and Benji Gil all
chipped in with two hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting guys we need to swing the bat to swing the
bat,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``Troy hits the homer to
break the game open, Mo gets three hits, Timmy had a big hit.
That's the type of offense we have to have. But we also executed
two hit-and-runs so that helped. Just as important as the big guys
swinging is little ball and that was evident today.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Etherton (2-1) matched his season-high with 6 1/3 innings,
getting the victory while allowing only four hits. He did give up
four runs, but got relief help from Shigetoshi Hasegawa and Troy
Percival (17th save).
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy, though, as the Angels saw an 8-2 lead shrink to
8-4 going into the ninth. And in the ninth, the Orioles cut their
deficit to 8-6 and brought the winning run to the plate in Delino
DeShields, with Albert Belle looming on deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team's been very hot,'' Scioscia said of the Orioles, who
had won six in a row before the Angels took the last two games in
the series. ``They have a lot of veteran hitters, good hitters who
know how to work their way back into a ballgame. You don't expect
it to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels jumped on Orioles starter Scott Erickson (3-4) in the
third inning, which was no small feat. Erickson entered the game
with a 16-4 record vs. the Angels in his career. But in the third,
the Angels got five hits, including an RBI single by Vaughn, a
sacrifice fly by Garret Anderson and Glaus' three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Etherton enough room to work. Making his fifth start
since being called up May 26, Etherton gave up only two hits -- a
two-run homer by Charles Johnson and a double by Will Clark --
through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton has been steady in all five starts. He's pitched at
least five innings in each one, and hasn't allowed more than four
runs in any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any change in his poise, it's the same poise he
had when he first came up,'' Scioscia said. ``It's why he got an
opportunity without a lot of minor league experience. He doesn't
scare off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even with Belle at the plate. Belle who went into the game
with six homers and 16 RBIs in his previous four games. He homered
in all four, but Sunday Etherton got Belle all three times he faced
him. Hasegawa struck out Belle in his fourth at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made good pitches on him,'' Etherton said. ``I know how
dangerous he is. I just moved the ball in and out and fortunately
he it at people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seth did a good job of changing speeds on him,'' Scioscia
said. ``He moved the ball around and changed speeds well. He was
pitch-efficient early in the game but the humidity took a lot out
of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Etherton was lifted after Harold Baines' RBI single with one out
in the seventh. The Orioles scored another in the inning on Brady
Anderson's RBI single, the run charged to Etherton.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa got the Angels to the ninth, but after giving up a
leadoff homer to Jeff Conine and walking Will Clark, Scioscia went
to Percival, who gave up a single and a walk but ended it by
getting DeShields on a grounder to second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
