r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     06-18 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BONUS FOR ANGELS' FIRST-ROUND PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE -- The Angels announced Sunday they signed first-round
draft pick Joe Torres, a left-handed pitcher from Gateway High
School in Kissimmee, Fla. Torres received a signing bonus believed
to be worth about $2.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who was the 10th pick overall in the draft June 5, has
been assigned to Single-A Boise.
</P>
<P>
   Torres won't turn 18 until Sept. 3, but Angels scouting director
Donny Rowland isn't concerned about Torres' youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a highly-confident, highly-experience 17-year-old,''
Rowland said. ``He's played at a high level for a long time. Any
time you take a high school pitcher in the first round, you assume
risks. But if you assume the risks, you believe the return will be
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his youth, Torres has international experience. He
played on the USA youth national team, which won a gold medal in
1998, and on the USA junior national team in 1999. He was the
winning pitcher in the USA's victory over Chinese Taipei in the
1999 gold-medal game.
</P>
<P>
   Torres signed a letter-of-intent to attend the University of
Miami, but made it clear after he was drafted he was more
interested in pitching professionally right away.
</P>
<P>
   As for what he'll do with his signing bonus, Torres said he's
``saving it for a rainy day. The big money's in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres will be in Anaheim Tuesday to meet the media, the team
and watch the Angels play the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Torres went 4-4 with a 0.38 ERA in 11 games his senior season at
Gateway High, striking out 128 in only 55 innings. In his four
losses, he threw a no-hitter, two one-hitters and a two-hitter. In
his high school career, he was 14-15 with a 1.58 ERA. Baseball
America magazine ranked Torres the No. 3 high school prospect in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Troy Percival has gone back to using a high leg kick
during his delivery, something he abandoned in recent years because
of his arm and shoulder problems. But because he is feeling
stronger now after off-season shoulder surgery, Percival has
returned to the delivery he used so successfully in 1995 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of violent but I'm getting strong enough to go back
to it,'' Percival said. ``It's more deceptive to hitters, they see
my body flying all over. The last 2 years guys were taking pretty
good hacks off me as opposed to recently. (Sunday) nobody was able
to take a good hack off me.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival pitched the ninth inning for his 17th save.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia's approach to using the designated hitter
spot is different than most managers. Instead of using an aging
player who might have some power, Scioscia is using it as a
semi-day off for a regular player, while putting either Scott
Spiezio, Orlando Palmeiro or Edgard Clemente in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio, Palmeiro or Clemente might also get a start as the DH,
but Scioscia likes to mix and match depending on that particular
day's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a full-time DH,'' Scioscia said. ``Each guy
brings something different to the lineup. Orlando's a great
situational player this club needs. Spiezio has some power.
Clemente can hit left-handers. All three play good defense are are
versatile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beautiful thing about the American League -- a guy
can get rest and still get his at-bats. It's important for guys to
be in there, whether it's the DH or playing the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
