<HEADLINE>
U.N. SECURITY COUNCIL CERTIFIES ISRAEL'S WITHDRAWAL FROM SOUTH
LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ After 16 hours of deadlock, the U.N. Security
Council Sunday gave a qualified endorsement of Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's certification on Friday that Israel has withdrawn from
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time it expressed concern over Beirut's charges that
the Israelis continue to encroach on Lebanese soil.
</P>
<P>
   The council's endorsement is important because it opens the way
to stationing U.N. peacekeepers across southern Lebanon and
authorizes them to help the Lebanese government restore its
authority in the often chaotic border region.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who is visiting the Middle East, threatened to scrap his
visit to Lebanon, scheduled Monday, if the council declined to
support his confirmation of the withdrawal, which was based on
field inspections by U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats said Lebanon complained that Israel violated its
border as recently as Sunday, driving equipment across to build a
fence. Lebanon has also accused the Israelis of holding on to
patches of its territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of any Israeli soldier inside the Lebanese
borders would mean the violation of the borders drawn by the
U.N.,'' Annan said Sunday in Cairo, Egypt. He promised to refer any
such violation to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the council convened to consider a statement
approving Annan's certification of the Israeli withdrawal, but
failed to reach consensus after 10 hours of discussions. U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright intervened, organizing a
conference call that linked President Emile Lahoud of Lebanon with
Annan's special envoy for the Middle East, Terje Roed-Larsen, at
the United Nations, and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen told the Secuity Council that without its
endorsement, Annan would cancel his visit to Lebanon. Annan
conveyed the same message to Lahoud, officials and other diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a further six hours of consulations Sunday, the council
finally produced a statement that ``welcomed'' the
secretary-general's report, but also endorsed the work done by the
U.N. verification teams.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for the endorsement looked bleak Sunday morning, after
Russia asked that the council members return to consultations and
seek further clarification of Lebanon's complaints. Some diplomats
said that Russia instructed its delegation not to override
Lebanon's objections. Russia wields veto power in the council,
precluding adoption of a meaningful statement without its support.
</P>
<P>
   To end the stalemate, the French and British delegations crafted
a new sentence addressing Lebanon's complaints. It said that ``the
council notes with serious concern reports of violations that have
occurred'' since Friday, and it called upon all parties ``to
respect the line as identified by the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of the council's endorsement would not only have
embarrassed the secretary-general, but would also have undermined
the credibility of his current Middle East visit. Annan has said he
hoped to use the momentum of the Israeli withdrawal to galvanize
other stalled peace talks in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who arrived in Cairo this evening from Tehran, Iran, is
scheduled to meet Lahoud and Lebanon Prime Minister Salim Hoss in
Beirut on Monday, and also to visit the U.N. peacekeeping mission
at its headquarters at Naqura, in southwestern Lebanon. Annan is
later expected to go to Jordan, Israel, the Palestinian territories
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen, who supervised the complex process of verifying
Israel's withdrawal , said Friday that the U.N. mission in southern
Lebanon will be expanded to 5,600 peacekeepers from the current
4,400. They are to set up fixed positions along the border and
conduct regular patrols, The numbers of U.N. peacekeepers could
eventually swell to 8,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen postponed his own visit to Beirut this weekend to
remain available here for the Security Council. In the course of
the verification, he met regularly with senior officials of
Lebanon, Israel and Syria, among other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. inspection teams checked the length of the 72-mile
border before reporting to Annan on Friday that the Israelis had
withdrawn. But within hours, Hoss asserted that Lebanese
specialists accompanying the inspectors had witnessed Israeli
encroachments. Lahoud separately called Annan's confirmation of the
withdrawal inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council, in its statement Sunday, called upon the
Lebanese government and armed forces to move faster to take control
of southern Lebanon. The statement said that the council would
review whether to extend the peacekeeping mission's mandate at the
end of July. It pointedly noted that, ``The United Nations cannot
assume law and order functions which are properly the
responsibility of the Government of Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that France, which contributes troops to the
peacekeeping mission, wants Lebanon to assume responsibility for
what has become a lawless region rather than leave it to the United
Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
