<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGRAM AND VIVENDI EXPECTED TO ANNOUNCE $33 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vivendi and the Seagram Co. are preparing to vote Monday on
Vivendi's purchase of Seagram for roughly $33 billion in stock. The
companies' boards met over the weekend to discuss the deal, and an
agreement could be announced by the end of the day or Tuesday
morning, according to a person close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi owns 49 percent of Canal Plus, the French pay television
company, and that company's board is also expected to meet Monday
to approve the Seagram acquisition. Canal Plus is a public company
and French law requires that it approve any merger undertaken by
Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to equity of roughly $33 billion, Vivendi is
expected to assume $6.6 billion in Seagram debt.
</P>
<P>
   Two people close to Seagram board members said Edgar Bronfman
Jr., Seagram's chief executive, had pushed for a final vote as
early as Monday, but that some directors were reluctant to move
that rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bronfman, Edgar Bronfman Jr.'s uncle and a director, has
been reducing his stake in Seagram, and there have been reports
that he is not happy with the company's performance. One of the
people with knowledge of the board said Charles Bronfman did not
want to vote on a sale as quickly as his nephew hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Edgar Bronfman Jr. had misgivings about
selling the company founded by his father and about the real value
of Vivendi's stock, according to a third executive with knowledge
of the board. Nevertheless, this person said, it still seemed quite
likely the deal would go through. Bronfman could not be reached,
and a Seagram spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's board meeting began at 11 a.m. in New York and
continued for six hours, according to a person with knowledge of
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The final price of the deal is still being negotiated, a person
close to the talks said, in part because Vivendi's stock has fallen
14 percent, to $94.40, since word of the deal leaked out last
Tuesday. But the price is expected to be around $75 a share.
Seagram shareholders are likely to get a collar _ a feature
limiting how much the deal price can vary _ if Vivendi's stock
falls further. Seagram stock closed at $61.4375 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Bronfman Jr. is set to become vice chairman of the new
company under Vivendi's chairman, Jean-Marie Messier. Bronfman
plans to commute from New York to Vivendi headquarters in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi has indicated that it will sell all or part of Seagram's
liquor business to reduce or eliminate Seagram's debt. Vivendi also
plans to sell roughly 30 percent of its water business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its stake in Canal Plus, Vivendi is the
second-largest cellular telephone and telephone operator in France,
and it has a joint venture with Vodafone AirTouch to create a
mobile Internet portal in Europe. Seagram owns Universal Studios,
several theme parks, a record company and a leading liquor
operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
