<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES NEEDS THIS TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER   
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Today's sermonette is written on behalf of the Los
Angeles Lakers, who will go into Game 6 of the NBA Finals tonight
with the weight of the city on their athletic shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Let us quote the great writer Joseph Conrad, who journeyed the
globe in search of whatever answers lingers in the soul of man.
</P>
<P>
   From his extraordinary ``Heart of Darkness,'' which was also
translated into the film ``Apocalypse Now'' by Martin Scorcese.
</P>
<P>
   (set ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``No fear can stand up to hunger, no patience can wear it out,
disgust simply does not exist where hunger is. And as to
superstition, beliefs, and what you may call principles, they are
less than chaff in a breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   I believe Phil Jackson would agree, and perhaps approve.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is hungry and parched for victory. It has been 12
years since a professional team sent a banner up a flagpole, a
dozen years since the Lakers and Dodgers both won 1998 titles and
reinforced the belief that the good times in L.A. would roll on
forever. But since, we have seen far too many teams fall short of
success, including this Laker team we tentatively embrace.
</P>
<P>
   In those dirty dozen years, a hero named Magic Johnson was
forced to retire prematurely. The Kings went to the Stanley Cup
finals, then their owner went to prison. The Dodgers stuttered in
several pennant races before being sold and sullied. The Rams and
Raiders went to the supermarket and never came back.
</P>
<P>
   And while UCLA did win a college basketball title in 1995, the
subsequent demise of Jim Harrick robbed that flag of its sparkle.
</P>
<P>
   So yes, it can be said without lapsing into hyperbole: Los
Angeles needs a victory.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter a bit that the Lakers have needed 23 games,
including tonight, to win a title, more games than San Antonio
needed last year (17), more games than the Chicago Bulls needed in
their six titles years (21, 19, 18, 19, 22 and 17, respectively,
counting backwards). Only one other champ has needed 23 games since
the end of the Magic-Larry Bird era, the 1994 Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that the Lakers have been unable to put teams
away, that they are 3-6 in closeout games. They lost twice to
Sacramento after opening 2-0, once to Phoenix after a 3-0 start,
blew serve twice to Portland after a 3-1 advantage, and once to
Indiana on Friday, two days after playing perhaps their best game
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that Shaquille O'Neal brings a 40 percent
free-throw shooting average into Game 6, or that renown free throw
misser Wilt Chamberlain shot better than that in 10 of his 13
playoff seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that the Lakers lost Game 5 by 33 points, the
franchise's biggest playoff loss since 1985, and 14 points more
than any loss suffered by Jackson since he started coaching
champions in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that Kobe Bryant went from Air-worthy in Game
4 of the finals to air-ball in Game 5, because we all know how
talented and important he is, and all of those comparisons are
tired, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that the Hack-a-Shaq has taken the NBA's
Miami-versus-New York-induced thuggery to new lows, and introduced
the three-hour game to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Or that Jackson himself has said this team often lacks ``a
championship quality,'' or that Ron Harper said any of the Bulls
teams he played on ``would have beaten the crap out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter what Mrs. Glen Rice has to say about her
husband's playing time, because your options in any offense (ital)
should (end) favor a 315-pound center who can dunk and a slashing
21-year-old who can create, over a 20-foot jumper by a mercurial
shooter who views defense as personal down time.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't even matter that Jackson will likely tear this team
up after the finals, wins or lose, that the Lakers could role out
two or three new starters next season.
</P>
<P>
   It only matters that the Lakers win. That's what an Oscar-worthy
crowd will want when Game 6 tips at Staples Center. Aesthetics do
not mater.
</P>
<P>
   From the ever-present Jack Nicholson and rapt Denzel Washington
to photo opportunists like Selma Hayek and Arnold Schwarzeneggar,
from every longtime Laker fan who has endured high blood pressure
following the team the last four season, it only matters that they
win. By one point or 21. By silencing Reggie Miller with blanket
coverage or watching him suffer another 1-for-16 night.
</P>
<P>
   Never have the words so often used by another opportunist and
former L.A. sports carpetbagger, Al Davis, been more true and
important.
</P>
<P>
   Just win, baby. How isn't important. Win, and we will bury any
and all facets of the past that have been waved in your face.
</P>
<P>
   No more references to Shaq's previous bowouts. No more lectures
on his free throws. No more seminars contrasting and comparing Kobe
Bryant to Michael Jordan. A full pardon regarding Ron Harper's
Clippers career. No more questions about Robert Horry's state of
mind. No more virgin jokes for A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am dying of thirst by the side of the fountain,'' wrote
Charles d'Orleans, way back in the 15th Century. It only seems like
six centuries ago since L.A. last quenched its thirst. The Lakers
have their hand on the faucet. For the good of L.A., let's hope
they turn it on tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
