<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS HELP REED STEER CLEAR OF TROUBLE THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The first injury came in Japan, when the automatic
door on a taxicab conked him on the knee. Then came a stiff neck
against Los Angeles, a numb foot in Philadelphia, a bruised hand
against Milwaukee and a pulled muscle in his side in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kept fighting, fighting and fighting,'' said the Mets
right-hander Rick Reed, who escaped Sunday's start without injury
and with a 7-3 victory over the Brewers. ``Finally, my past two
outings have been fine with me, right where I want to be. Each time
out's getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed worked seven innings, allowing three runs on seven hits and
a walk. He had no decision in each of his previous six starts _
``That's unreal; I don't want to go through that again,'' he said _
but earned a victory Sunday, his first since April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Belliard smacked a leadoff home run off Reed. But the first
hitter in Reed's last start against the Brewers inflicted more
damage. In that game, at Shea Stadium on April 19, Marquis Grissom
led off by smashing a liner off Reed's glove hand. Reed went on to
pitch seven strong innings for a victory, but his wrist and palm
were crushed.
</P>
<P>
   He could not make a fist or slide his hand into his glove for
several days, and the pain disrupted his sleep. Reed missed a start
and, as he struggled over the next month, he changed his mechanics
to protect his hand when he got into fielding position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into some bad habits with my front shoulder, and that
started elevating the ball in the strike zone,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   That was not a problem Sunday for Reed, who trailed by 1-0 after
Belliard's homer but pitched with a lead for most of the game,
courtesy of the Mets' five-run fourth inning against Jason Bere.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco led off with a single and scored on Mike Piazza's
double, and Jay Payton drove in another run with a sacrifice fly.
After Benny Agbayani beat the throw to first base on what would
have been an inning-ending double play, Kurt Abbott bashed an
off-speed pitch for a three-run home run that traveled an estimated
405 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was starting for the first time since Tuesday, when he
made a throwing error that brought in the Chicago Cubs' winning
run. Abbott admitted wondering why he was not in Manager Bobby
Valentine's lineup the next three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's normal,'' he said. ``Of course. When you want
to play and you're not in there, you have reason to ask, `How come
I'm not in there?' But he's the manager and he makes out the lineup
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine told Abbott and Melvin Mora they would share the
playing time while shortstop Rey Ordonez was out with a broken
forearm, but he never mentioned who would play when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the hot hand,'' Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, whose second single helped the Mets score their sixth
run, has a better idea when he will start: every 10 or 11 days. He
had not started since June 3, so he had a feeling he would today.
</P>
<P>
   He has seven hits in 20 at-bats in his six starts, for a .350
average. When he does not start, he is six for 40, .150. But Franco
has felt comfortable with his swing all season and was a little
embarrassed that a two-hit day would be notable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how I feel and I know what I'm seeing, and I know I can
hit what I'm seeing,'' Franco said. ``I've hit .280 many times and
felt worse than I do now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
