<HEADER>
A7709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-N     06-18 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH HAS OTHER THINGS ON HIS MIND BESIDES THROWING PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The emotions were swirling again for Chuck Knoblauch
Sunday before the New York Yankees' 17-4 loss to the Chicago White
Sox, confusing emotions that he has conceded will not soon vanish.
Knoblauch is the second baseman who does not understand why his
throws to first base sometimes act like paper airplanes, sailing
without any direction.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged his shoulders and scrunched his face when he
casually fielded questions. He spoke about the difficulty of having
an ailing father on Father's Day, about being unable to persuade
his mother to visit him from Texas and about how any progress he
makes in combating his problem will probably be incremental.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys see the baseball stuff,'' Knoblauch said. ``It might
not be a baseball thing. It probably isn't. It's probably something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch suggested that he received some sort of treatment to
deal with his chronic throwing problems following the 1999 season,
but he has refused to discuss what he might have done. He has
ignored the reams of unsolicited advice he has received and snapped
his fingers to indicate that, if this were a trivial problem, it
would have been solved by now.
</P>
<P>
   While Knoblauch has acknowledged that he will undergo some
treatment, he has refused to disclose whether it will be with a
sports psychologist. When he was asked why he was reluctant to talk
about what he might have done to address the problem previously,
the second baseman bristled slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you do this winter?'' he said, repeating a reporter's
question. ``The winter is personal. I know people want to know, but
I don't think I should talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch fielded two grounders Sunday in the five innings he
played and tossed soft, accurate throws to first both times, which
caused the fans to explode in applause. As gracious as it was for
fans to cheer for Knoblauch, he would obviously prefer it if a
routine throw did not attract intense attention.
</P>
<P>
   When Knoblauch whipped a ball into the stands on Saturday, it
struck Marie Olbermann, the mother of Keith, a broadcaster for Fox
Sports. Although some players discussed the bizarre nature of whom
the ball hit, Knoblauch said he was unaware the ball hit Keith
Olbermann's mother until reporters told him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was Father's Day, a difficult day for anyone who has lost
a father or who feels as if a father has been lost. Ray Knoblauch
coached Chuck during his amateur career, and Chuck credits his
father with helping him reach the majors. But Knoblauch has not
really been able to speak with his father during his two-year
throwing ordeal because Ray has Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy,'' Knoblauch said. ``It's not just because
it's Father's Day. It doesn't change. That's never easy.''
</P>
<P>
   After Knoblauch made three errors in Thursday's game and he and
manager Joe Torre agreed that he should leave Yankee Stadium, the
first thing Knoblauch did was call his mother, Linda. Knoblauch,
who talks to his mother almost every day, said she told him she
wanted to travel to New York and hug him. Still, Knoblauch has been
unable to pry his mother from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked her to come, but she can't,'' Knoblauch said. ``She
doesn't want to leave him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
