<HEADER>
A7710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUKE-SECRETS-DISAPPEA     06-18 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-SECRETS-DISAPPEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY REJECTS CALLS TO RESIGN OVER LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The strange case of lost and found nuclear secrets
at Los Alamos National Laboratory took on a political edge Sunday,
as some Republican leaders in Congress called on Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson to resign after yet another security lapse at the
New Mexico laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard C. Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Select Committee
on Intelligence, said Sunday that it was time for Richardson to
take responsibility for the security breaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should step down, he should be responsible,'' Shelby said
in an interview on the CBS News program ``Face the Nation.'' ``I
don't believe he's served his president well, and I don't believe
he's served his nation well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., a member of the intelligence panel, also
called for Richardson's resignation, while the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., complained that Richardson had ``not
been paying attention to this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson rejected the calls for his resignation, saying on the
ABC News program ``This Week'' Sunday that stepping down would be
``walking away'' from a problem that he had vowed to fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will take responsibility to clean up this mess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks came at the end of a long week for Richardson, the
Energy Department and the Los Alamos laboratory. Officials at Los
Alamos announced on Monday that two computer hard drives containing
nuclear weapons data were missing, and that employees had waited
more than three weeks to report their disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, Richardson announced that the hard drives
had reappeared under equally mysterious circumstances. They were
discovered behind a copying machine in an area of the laboratory
that had been repeatedly searched by the FBI and the Energy
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The hard drives were used to store nuclear weapons data needed
by the Nuclear Emergency Search Team, which responds to nuclear
accidents and nuclear-related threats. The drives contained design
information about nuclear weapons from China, France, Russia and
the United States, which could be used by the team to disarm
weapons
</P>
<P>
   The two drives were flown to Washington from Los Alamos after
they were found. They were being examined electronically to
determine if they had been tampered with or the data compromised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there's been no espionage,'' Richardson said on the
NBC program ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery surrounding the hard drives came a year after
questions first came up over lax security at Los Alamos in the wake
of the Wen Ho Lee case.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was a scientist at Los Alamos who was investigated in
connection with allegations that China had stolen nuclear data. He
was fired in March 1999 for security violations and was arrested in
December on charges of mishandling classified material after it was
discovered that he had downloaded and copied vast amounts of
nuclear weapons data from the classified computer network at Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee was never charged with espionage, and the accusations
that China had stolen design information about America's most
advanced nuclear warhead have not been proven.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby and other Republican lawmakers said Sunday that
Richardson had repeatedly assured Congress that security at Los
Alamos had been improved in the wake of the Lee case. They also
noted that Richardson had opposed congressional plans to reorganize
the nuclear weapons laboratories and programs after last year's
espionage controversy. After Congress created an independent agency
to manage the laboratories, Richardson resisted the plan, arguing
that he should remain in charge, and that he could guarantee the
safety of the nation's nuclear secrets. Last week, in the wake of
the latest security breach, a new director of the new nuclear
weapons agency was confirmed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Richardson's words promising to protect the nation's
secrets were thrown back at him by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose to assume the full responsibility, to reject putting
someone else in charge, to fight the creation of this new
semiautonomous agency,'' Kyl said on ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the one, by his own choice, who chose to accept
(responsibility), and therefore he has to bear the consequences,
and I believe he ought to step down.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, assailed the Clinton administration's for its
handling of security, telling an audience in Florida that
``America's national security should not be a matter of lost and
found.'' Bush added that the administration is to blame for
``confusion and chaos'' at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson stressed Sunday that he has been working over the
past year to tighten security, but suggested that his efforts have
been impeded by a nonchalant attitude about security among
scientists at the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the human element,'' Richardson said. ``I'm
trying to change the security culture. I'm trying to deal with that
human element, and I'm doing my best. But to say that security has
not been upgraded at Los Alamos and at all our labs is wrong. We
have done a good job in upgrading security cybersecurity, physical
security, polygraphs, and I stand against anybody that rejects that
view.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, on the ABC program ``This Week,'' that ``I have to
keep a balance between science and security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Security is a priority, but at the same time a lot of
important scientific research has to take place, and you know,
right now I don't seem to win,'' he said. ``I'm attacked by
scientists that say `too much security,' members of Congress that
don't like polygraphs, civil libertarians that say I've gone too
far. And now you get _ now, I can take the heat. I just want to fix
this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said investigators were focusing on members of the
Nuclear Emergency Search Team and scientists who had access to the
vault in the nuclear weapons design division of Los Alamos where
the hard drives were stored.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was possible that a scientist took the hard drives
and ``panicked'' when their disappearance led to an investigation.
The person may have then dropped them behind the copying machine in
order to return them without being caught.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which is now conducting a criminal inquiry, has given
polygraph tests to 26 people so far, focusing on scientists in the
laboratory's X Division and NEST members. At least three people
have flunked the tests, offering contradictory answers, officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richardson said on ``This Week'' that ``the FBI is focusing on a
few individuals within that X Division. We do believe there is no
evidence, according to the FBI and our experts, of espionage or
that they left the X Division. But at the same time, this is not a
victory speech. We have to get to the bottom of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The deputy energy secretary, T.J. Glauthier, appearing on Fox
News Sunday, said investigators ``can't tell for sure'' at this
time whether the hard drives had been copied or tampered with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
