r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-18 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS REFLECTION OF L.A.'S DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - The way Sam Perkins was talking Sunday, the Lakers
resonate the Los Angeles lifestyle better than any group since the
Beach Boys. ``The way the lifestyle is in L.A., they play the same
way,'' Perkins said. ``Their finesse, their showmanship, their
stars; they fit the mold.''
</P>
<P>
   What the former Laker surely knows but didn't dare say, for fear
of seeing it close-up today, is that there's another side to Los
Angeles. It is a side best reflected by Lakers reserve forward Rick
Fox, who, when he isn't shooting movies or squiring his actress
wife Vanessa Williams around, is providing sparks and scowls and
the occasional flagrant foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look within and find all the evil inside of
you,'' Fox said. He was talking about the drive to win an NBA
title, but, honestly, he could have been talking about the drive to
the Staples Center, site of tonight's NBA Finals Game 6 between the
Lakers and the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Any tourist who has taken the wheel of a rental car in L.A. and
survived to tell about it will say this: When Angelenos aren't
languidly speaking on their cell phones, sipping soy lattes,
sunbathing or stargazing, they're striking fear and loathing into
the hearts of the paltry few defensive drivers in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Stick an Angeleno in the fast lane of the southbound 101, give
him a hundred or so feet to make the 405 interchange (after all, no
sense creeping along in the slow lane any longer than is
necessary), and we guarantee you'll see such aggression it'll make
your testosterone boil.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal spinning off Rik Smits in the paint and then
elbowing him in the face to get off one of his baby hook shots is a
passive act next to the behavioral patterns of the typical Angeleno
during his or her daily commute.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Pacers' Reggie Miller perpetuate the Evian-drinking,
caffe latte-sipping Angeleno. We know that to live in L.A. is to
acquire over time, in addition to a tan and an agent, a mean streak
that is manifested in last milli-second lane changes, chronic
tailgating and failure to yield to anything that isn't flashing red
lights (and even then it's iffy).
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis might have the Speedway, but in L.A. every driver
is Mario Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   We have a well-tread saying in L.A.: You are how you drive. If
the Lakers make that their mantra tonight, we guarantee the Pacers
will be on the next plane home to their beloved Conseco Fieldhouse,
which, for the record, houses a Starbucks along with all those
nifty historical exhibits and is just a Miller 3-pointer away from
the Have a Nice Day cafe (we kid you not).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there would appear to be a lot of Hollywood, at least as
Miller perceives it, creeping into Hoosierville. As the owners of a
3-2 lead in the best-of-seven championship series, the Lakers'
mission tonight is to prove beyond a sliver of a doubt that the
fierce pride and provincialism of Hoosierville that Miller, a
former Bruin, perfectly personifies is alive and well in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did a laudable job of defending their turf in the
first two games. They raced to a 15-point lead after one quarter on
the way to a 17-point victory in Game 1 and rode O'Neal's back to a
seven-point win in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   If it appeared the Lakers played with a lot more aggression at
the Staples Center than at Conseco Fieldhouse, there's a reason.
The referees let them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's more liberties given to a home-court team in
terms of being able to play physical,'' Fox said, and the numbers
bear him out. In Games 1 and 2, the Pacers accrued 61 fouls to the
Lakers' 45.
</P>
<P>
   That was partly Indiana's own conscious doing; in Game 2, the
Pacers' Hack-a-Shaq strategy put O'Neal on the line as many times
(39) as the whole Indiana team. For whatever reason, in the three
games in Indiana the referees' whistles went the other way, with
the Lakers collecting 91 fouls to the Pacers' 71.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Lakers must come out as mean as the L.A. driver who
refuses to make room for a merging car. They can't concede so much
as a foot, lest the Pacers take the series the distance.
</P>
<P>
   If it takes a flagrant foul on Jalen Rose by A.C. Green, a.k.a.
Mr. Serene, in the first minutes of play to set the tone, so be it.
Whatever they do (boxing out and rebounding would be nice), the
Lakers can't afford to stand around and look pretty like all the
other Angelenos inside the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' resident pretty boy needs no such reminders. From
Game 1 of the postseason, Fox alone seems to have grasped the
importance of every night bringing the same aggression he unleashes
on the lanes of L.A. roads to the basketball court's passing and
driving lanes.
</P>
<P>
   He might as well be wearing red for how often he has been, uh,
ticketed. Fox has collected five technical fouls in the postseason,
two more than he can recall receiving in his first six years in the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear Fox has been a marked man since being ejected
late in the fourth quarter of Game 4 of the Western Conference
semifinals at Phoenix after drawing two technicals in 31 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I get when I check into games now?'' Fox said,
shaking his head. ``(The referees say) None of that s--- tonight.
Behave yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets fouls and flagrant (fouls) for trying to block
shots,'' said reserve center John Salley, who had his own unique
take (doesn't he always?) on why that is so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me,'' Salley said, smiling, ``like the referees
are mad he married Vanessa Williams and are jealous as all
outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course. It's all in a day's title drive for L.A.'s team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
