<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7728 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-NYT     06-18 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS FALL AS TIGER CRUISES TO U.S. OPEN VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Tiger Woods looked natural making
unforgettable shots, he looked natural making history, and it
seemed natural that Woods, the world's best player, won the 100th
U.S. Open on Sunday in record-setting fashion. Woods made a
dramatic statement that his phenomenal skills have never been in
more perfect harmony, the clearest signal yet that he intends to
dominate his sport during this generation.
</P>
<P>
   On a picture-perfect day at one of golf's most sacred locations,
Woods (12 under par, 272, 65-69-71-67) won the Open by a
record-setting 15 strokes over South Africa's Ernie Els and Miguel
Angel Jimenez of Spain, who tied for second place at three over
par. It was the largest victory margin ever in a major
championship, surpassing the 13-stroke victory margin by Old Tom
Morris at the 1862 British Open. The winning margin also broke a
record that had stood 101 years, surpassing the 11-stoke victory by
Willie Anderson in 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also set the record for lowest score in relation to par
(12 strokes), breaking the previous record of eight under par set
by Ben Hogan in 1948, and equaled by Jack Nicklaus in 1980 and Lee
Janzen in 1993. And Woods' winning total of 272 tied the all-time
winning totals held by Nicklaus and Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has now won two majors by record-setting margins, his
12-stroke victory at the Masters in 1997, and Sunday's victory that
left a mind-boggling gap between him and a world-class field. When
Woods reached 12 under par by making a 10-foot birdie putt at the
par 5, 14th hole, he became only the second player to reach 12
under in Open history, tying Gil Morgan, who did it in 1992. But
unlike Morgan, who faded and lost the 1992 Open to Tom Watson,
Woods turned this event into an affirmation of his skills, leaving
people shaking their heads in awe.
</P>
<P>
   At 24, Woods has already won three major championships _ the
Masters in 1997, the PGA Championship last year and Sunday's
victory at the Open. His ambition is to be remembered as the
greatest player of all-time. And Sunday, he completed one of golf's
all-time great performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Masters and the PGA Championship were special wins, but to
win our national championship, being an American, is a great
feeling,'' said Woods, who won three consecutive U.S. Amateur
championships (1994-96), and who has 23 victories worldwide since
turning professional in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe the thoughts that are going through your
mind. You grow up dreaming of beating all the best players, and
then you're walking down that fairway about to win,'' Woods said.
``It was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   When Woods won the Masters, it was a phenomenal performance by a
22-year-old who overpowered Augusta National Golf Club with his
length, while making putts from all over the greens. But this
victory was perhaps more impressive. The golf course was more
difficult. It required more accuracy off the tee, more course
management, and more patience.
</P>
<P>
   The Open has often been called golf's most demanding test, and
Woods passed it easily, like a class valedictorian. The outcome was
all but decided Saturday morning, when Woods took a record-breaking
six-stroke lead after two rounds. At that point, the rest of the
field needed strokes, and Woods was not giving any.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Woods first turned professional when
people wondered if he had the game to win an Open, whether he had
enough accuracy off the tee, or enough control with his short
irons, or enough patience. Those questions have been silenced.
Woods can win on any golf course that has tee boxes, fairways, and
greens.
</P>
<P>
   Only Nicklaus, who won three different majors by age 23, has won
three different majors quicker than Woods. And at next month's
British Open at St. Andrews, Scotland, the birthplace of golf,
Woods will attempt to complete the career Grand Slam, winning all
four majors faster than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday's final hole, a picturesque 543-yard par 5, the drama
centered on whether Woods would break the scoring record of 272.
After his tee shot and a lay-up approach, Woods hit his third on
the green, about 15 feet left of the hole, giving him a chance to
putt for birdie and a record 271.
</P>
<P>
   As Woods walked to the green, he removed his hat to acknowledge
the roaring gallery, and some fans dropped to their knees and bowed
repeatedly. Woods missed the putt for birdie at No. 18, but he made
the next putt for par, settling for a 272 total, one of the few
things Woods settled for during an amazing four-day performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those great weeks,'' said Woods, who won
for the fifth time this year, including his last two starts. ``I
made a lot of putts, big putts that I really needed that kept my
momentum going.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day at eight under par, Woods parred his way
through the front nine, then provided more memories on his
triumphant march to the Open trophy. At No. 10, Woods made a
12-foot putt for his first birdie of the day. That one putt seemed
to send a charge through Woods' body, just like it sent a charge
through the gallery. Two holes later, Woods made an 18-foot putt
for birdie, to reach 10 under par.
</P>
<P>
   Then at the par-4 No. 13, Woods hit another incredible shot, an
iron approach that nearly went in the hole, passing by the left
side of the cup and stopping less than 2 feet from the hole. Woods
tapped-in for another birdie that moved him to 11 under par.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, one could sense the momentum building. Woods made
another birdie at the par 5 No. 14, chipping to 8 feet on his third
shot, then making still another putt. At No. 16, Woods just missed
a 15-foot putt by less than a foot that would have moved him to 13
under par. Then at No. 17, Woods saved par with a superb bunker
shot that settled just a foot from the cup, another display of his
almost magical touch around the green. Then came the finish, with
Woods taking his well-deserved walk down the last fairway, soaking
in the adulation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a week filled with emotion. The absence of Payne Stewart,
the defending champion who was killed in a plane crash last
October, was felt by the entire field, and Nicklaus, who missed the
cut, bid a tearful farewell to the gallery at No. 18 on Friday,
playing perhaps his final major.
</P>
<P>
   But the torch held by golf's most-dominant player has been
clearly passed from Nicklaus to Woods. And at the 100th Open,
everyone else was truly playing for second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest point?'' asked a puzzled Woods, when asked for his
highest and lowest points of the week. ``I never really had a low
point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
