<HEADLINE>
THE BOOK STORE IS CLOSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A site that had been selling college and pro football playbooks
has temporarily suspended operation after a backlash of criticism
it received in the media, including a story in Sports Illustrated
that questioned its motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have desired to be a resource for youth, junior high and
high school coaches,'' says the message on the home page for
SportsPlayBooks.com, based in Texas. ``Unfortunately, some concerns
have been raised concerning the material on our website. We have
never intended to undermine anyone or hurt anyone. We believed our
material could help coaches with their own teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Orders from an inventory of more than 100 playbooks going for
$23.95 were stopped after May 19 and the site will be up and
running again ``sometime this summer,'' it adds.
</P>
<P>
   -Houston Astros manager, former Taft High star and
self-proclaimed techhead Larry Dierker has been providing weekly
columns to MaxBaseball.com, a site that prides itself on free
original audio and video programming content.
</P>
<P>
   -The San Francisco Giants have pulled off launching a season
ticket exchange element to their Web site (www.sfgiants.com).
Season ticket holders who want to sell their seats can do so at
face value or more, and buyers who reply can then buy them with
credit cards. The team takes a 10-percent processing fee and
reissues the ticket to the buyer either by mail or at will call.
</P>
<P>
   -Major League Soccer is the first pro sport to combine forces
with SeasonTicket.com, a new site that not only provides unique
video highlights but allows users to taylor them to their own
desires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
