<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGEROUS COAL MINES TAKE HUMAN TOLL IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DATONG, China _ ``Sometimes it happens with no warning,''
explained the man as he emerged from eight backbreaking hours
underground, rubbing his coal-smudged face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you hear a creaking sound,'' he said of the final
seconds before a tunnel collapses. ``Then you hear pop-pop-popping
and you run as fast as you can to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   In eight years of dreary toil, the last two of them here in
northern China's coal capital where he came in search of better
wages, 35-year-old Jin Qian has seen cave-ins and fires and
explosions. He has heard the tell-tale creaking and run for his
life, and he has seen co-workers get obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   But far more routine, he and other miners say, are the physical
injuries that can leave a worker maimed for life. They speak of
broken arms and crushed fingers, of hands split by picks, of
battered ribs and collapsed lungs.
</P>
<P>
   This is the harshest face of coal mining in China _ a country
that produces more coal than any other in the world, and that, its
own alarmed officials admit, has probably the world's worst mine
safety record.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's produces one-fourth of the world's coal, but accounts
for four-fifths of the world's coal-industry fatalities,'' Wang
Shengshen, a mining engineer at the Chinese University of Mining,
said at a recent conference.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Baoming, head of the State Coal Industry Bureau, said in a
journal article this March that accidental deaths in China's coal
mines ``have wavered at around 10,000 a year.'' These are the
official numbers, which mining experts here say are an undercount
and do not begin to account for nonfatal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, whose agency is trying to combat the problem with
intensified mine inspections nationwide, cited international data
indicating that for every million tons of coal produced, China had
11 times as many reported fatalities as Russia, 15 times as many
fatalities as India and 182 times as many as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In China, most dangerous of all are the small, private mines
that in many regions surround giant, state-run mining companies, as
they do in Datong.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the thousands of privately run mines, each burrowing
into the thick seam of embalmed energy beneath these rolling
prairies, men wearing head lamps climb down crude shafts where they
use picks and crowbars to pry loose chunks of coal.
</P>
<P>
   With shovels and by hand, they heap the coal onto metal carts
that are jerked through long corridors to the open air. Finally, it
is loaded onto trucks for eventual sale throughout China and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   China, as its thickly polluted skies attest, makes intense use
of its vast coal reserves, burning it to fuel most electric plants
and factories and often even for home heating and cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The large state mines, some of them virtual cities unto
themselves, usually give workers better job security, health care
and pensions, and their operations are more mechanized.
</P>
<P>
   In theory at least, these mines are watched over by the
state-run labor organization; while coal mining is dirty and
dangerous anywhere, they tend to take better precautions against
explosions, fires, cave-ins and other special hazards. However,
slumping prices in recent years have led to charges of scrimping on
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller mines are usually run by private entrepreneurs, who
sometimes have subcontracted facilities that were originally
developed by a local government. These operations, too, are
increasingly subjected to safety inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But because the labor is so arduous and risky and these mines
offer no long-term benefits, their front-line digging jobs are
shunned by all but the most desperate workers: underemployed
farmers from nearby counties or work-gangs contracted from distant
regions.
</P>
<P>
   One worker in a private mine, Wang Jing, said that more than
half the men in his nearby village are willing to risk the drudgery
and danger because they could not scratch a living out of the
semi-arid hills of Shanxi province, just below the Mongolian
desert.
</P>
<P>
   The miners work six or seven days a week in eight-hour shifts,
with no break for a meal. Each is paid according to how many carts
he fills, and the most dogged workers can make $120 in a good
month, miners said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to better inspections, the Chinese government has
begun to close down tens of thousands of the smallest and most
dangerous mines _ in part because of safety, but also because of
surplus production capacity and evidence that reckless tunneling on
the fringes may impair the long-term production of the state mines.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the closed-down mines, workers here said, have
secretly reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Resting on the large bed he shares with two fellow villagers,
weary after his 7:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. turn underground, a migrant
from Sichuan province reflected on his plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mine is pretty safe,'' said the man, who gave his surname
as Zhao. For the last four years he has worked in a private mine
where 200 workers in two shifts produce about 500 tons of coal a
day. ``The owner knows that the mine must be safe if it is to keep
operating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, small accidents happen constantly,'' he said. ``Doing
such hard physical work at piece rates, it's unavoidable.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhao, 36, has a wife who farms and a 12-year-old boy in school
back in Sichuan. Like most of his work crew, who are all from the
same county, he returns home once a year during the Chinese New
Year. Of his monthly wages of about $110, he said, he saves $60 to
send back home.
</P>
<P>
   The mining work, he said, is ``really tough.'' But back in his
home village, each family has only a fraction of an acre of
farmland, not enough to survive on. He hopes after several years to
return with savings ``to try something different, maybe animal
husbandry, growing pigs or chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   When injuries occur, Zhao said, most of the private mines in the
Datong area pay for medical care, but that workers who suffer
permanent disabilities have little choice but to move back home,
with no compensation for crushed opportunities. And the medical
care the owners pay for, he said with a laugh, is not always the
best around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're injured you get the cheaper medicines rather than
the better ones, and you have to get better sooner rather than
later,'' Zhou said. ``That's the way the market economy works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2133EDT &QL; 
