<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BASEBALL TEAM HAS `GREAT FUTURE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's baseball team had just been eliminated from
the College World Series, but amid the post-game disappointment,
there was also a realization: The Trojans were probably in Omaha a
year earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is upset to have to look at next year, but it's a
great future,'' pitcher Ronald Flores said. ``Our team is so
young.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering USC was ranked fourth in the nation at the end of
the year, it should be ranked at least that high going into next
season. The Trojans return their top four pitchers, six of eight
position players and their designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that this season's team, which didn't have anyone
drafted in the first five rounds, had a 16-game winning streak and
became only the third team in USC coach Mike Gillespie's 14 years
to reach the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would say we overachieved,'' Gillespie said.
``I certainly think this team achieved at the maximum level.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would confuse these scrappy Trojans with teams that won
conference titles in 1991 or 1996 but did not advance to the
College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly had teams that were outstanding teams and had a
legitimate chance to get here, and didn't for one reason or
another,'' Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2000 edition won with good defense and pitching, and
those areas should be just as strong next season.
</P>
<P>
   USC expects to lose just two starters: senior third baseman
Justin Gemoll and sophomore catcher Beau Craig, who probably will
sign a contract with the Oakland A's after being drafted in the
sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing a lot of offense in Gemoll and Craig,'' Gillespie
said. ``We don't have a lot coming in. Perhaps a freshman will step
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the incoming freshmen are infielders Michael Moon of
Rancho Cucamonga and Jonathon Brewster of Notre Dame High in
Sherman Oaks along with left-handed pitcher Fraser Dizard of
Edmonds, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Moon will replace Gemoll at third, and first baseman Alberto
Concepcion will switch to catcher, meaning USC needs to find
someone to play first. The Trojans could also use a power-hitting
outfielder, something they lacked in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   There's always a chance a transfer will fill one of those roles.
In recent years, some of USC's best players (Gemoll, pitcher Mark
Prior, pitcher Barry Zito) have transferred over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows, maybe something will happen out there,'' Gillespie
joked.
</P>
<P>
   The expected leaders will be shortstop Seth Davidson (.305),
second baseman Anthony Lunetta (.343, 12 homers, 50 RBI) and
Concepcion, who hit eight home runs in only 117 at-bats, which is
about half a season in college baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If USC's offense needs a boost, its pitching is deeper than
ever. The Trojans will have one of the best pitching staffs in the
nation, with all three starters returning (Rik Currier, Prior,
Anthony Reyes) along with their top reliever (Flores).
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff we have is pretty legit,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   Currier went 15-3 this season as USC's ace, while Prior (10-7)
will be the most physically gifted player on the team and a certain
first-round draft choice. Reyes (6-6) threw a 95-mph fastball in
Omaha and probably had the most impressive World Series performance
of the three starters despite being a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Flores was 6-2 as the team's mid-week starter and reliever. The
only thing lacking is a left-hander, and that's where Dizard should
find a role.
</P>
<P>
   Dizard was 7-2 with a 1.26 ERA while hitting .368 and was the
Gatorade state player of the year in Washington. He was selected in
the 21st round by the Baltimore Orioles but says he intends to come
to USC.
</P>
<P>
   Almost forgotten is 6-foot-6 sophomore Chad Clark, who was a
high school All-American but had control problems this season, and
sophomore Brian Bannister, the son of former major-leaguer Floyd
Bannister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
