<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7746 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-INVESTIGAT     06-18 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-INVESTIGATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HEAT OF CAMPAIGN, A NEW REPORT STIRS OLD QUESTIONS FOR MRS.
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is an added starter on The New York Times front page)  
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton campaigns around New York
in her Senate bid, voters almost never ask her about Whitewater,
the wide-ranging investigation into Arkansas land deals that an
independent counsel has been pursuing for more than six years.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do they raise questions about the firing of workers in the
White House travel office, her immense good fortune in the
commodities markets, or any other matter that has been
investigated. When a reporter makes a rare query along those lines,
Clinton successfully fends it off by saying that such things have
been ``investigated to death'' and that she believes people are
tired of them.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton's campaign has been concerned enough to
poll voters on their views about the investigations, which are
nearing completion with her campaign in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, Robert Ray, the independent counsel who has
been investigating the Clintons, is expected to file a report with
a special judicial panel that will deal in part with whether the
first lady played any role in the firing of seven longtime
employees in the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   The report will not be made public, but people close to the
investigation say it is highly unlikely that it will recommend that
anyone be criminally prosecuted. Ray, who replaced Kenneth Starr as
the independent prosecutor last October, may announce that
conclusion publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The report itself, which will remain under seal for at least
three months, is expected to include a narrative that will touch on
whether Clinton was a force behind the decision to fire the
employees and whether she or any White House aides tried to conceal
her role.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's political aides have said they believe that
scandal-weary voters no longer care about these issues. More to the
point, her supporters have argued that the scandals have been shown
to be without substance and that the Clintons have been targets of
a concerted effort by their political enemies to discredit them and
undo the results of two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no concern about these things,'' Clinton said in a
recent interview. ``I don't know how it will be used to be damaging
to me, if that's the idea behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a summary of those issues, what Clinton has said about
them, what is publicly known and what questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL OFFICE FIRINGS
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, 1993, only a few months into the Clinton
administration, seven longtime employees of the White House travel
office, which handles arrangements for journalists accompanying the
president on trips, were dismissed and ordered off the White House
grounds. They were quickly replaced by friends and relatives of the
Clintons, most of them from Arkansas. White House officials said
that evidence of gross financial mismanagement had led to the
dismissals, allegations that were later found to be
unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
   After several news reports suggested that the firings had been
improper, the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, looked into the matter and sent Clinton a series of
questions about her role in it.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, the House Committee on Government Reform and
Oversight began its own investigation and sent Clinton additional
questions. About the same time, Attorney General Janet Reno
authorized Starr, the Whitewater prosecutor, to look explicitly
into Clinton's actions in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The committee turned up what appeared to be a stark conflict
between Clinton's account of the shake-up and documents written by
David Watkins, the senior White House aide who carried out the
firings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton portrayed herself as a peripheral figure, someone who
had only casually asked to be kept informed. Watkins described a
climate of fear stoked by Clinton, who wanted the travel office
employees fired immediately. In a memo to Thomas F. McLarty III,
then the White House chief of staff, he wrote, ``We both knew there
would be hell to pay'' if ``we failed to take swift and decisive
action in conformity with the first lady's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a written chronology of events leading up to the firing,
Watkins quoted Clinton as saying, ``We need those people out and we
need our people in.'' He also wrote that he had spoken directly to
Clinton about his efforts to fire the employees. In addition, a
week before the dismissals, he said, he had been told by Harry
Thomason, an Arkansas friend of the Clintons and a Hollywood
producer, that Clinton told him she was ``ready to fire them that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   In her response to the General Accounting Office, Clinton said
she had played no role in the decision to fire the employees,
though she might have expressed concern about the travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer told the GAO that ``Mrs. Clinton does not know the
origin of the decision to remove the travel office employees'' and
that ``she did not direct that any action be taken by anyone with
regard to the travel office other than expressing an interest in
receiving information about the review.''
</P>
<P>
   In her answers to the House committee, Clinton said she did not
remember telling Thomason on May 12 that she was ready to fire the
office employees that day. Although Watkins' documents portray
Clinton as intensely interested in the firings, she told the
committee investigators that she had been greatly preoccupied with
other matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to remember the specifics of conversations that
occurred almost three years ago,'' she told investigators, adding
that ``the spring of 1993 was a busy and stressful time.'' She said
she was busy adjusting to ``a change in living circumstances,
putting my daughter into a new school and increased entertainment
and media demands of the White House,'' as well as attending to her
father, who had suffered an ultimately fatal stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS DEALINGS
</P>
<P>
   Much of the investigation of Clinton's role in the range of
issues known collectively as Whitewater has centered on what she
did as a lawyer for various Arkansas clients, and allegations that
she tried to conceal or minimize her role.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, the independent counsel, is expected to file his report on
these matters with the special panel, made up of three judges,
sometime in the fall. It is uncertain whether its contents will be
available before the November election.
</P>
<P>
   One issue is how Clinton came to represent Madison Guaranty
Savings and Loan, a thrift institution that was operated by James
McDougal. McDougal and his wife, Susan, were partners of the
Clintons in the Whitewater real estate investment in the Ozarks.
Another issue is whether she sought to use her influence as the
governor's wife to seek special treatment from a state agency for
Madison, which was owned by her Whitewater partner.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of the Whitewater controversy, Clinton said
that she became the billing partner at her law firm for Madison
Guaranty because Richard Massey, a young associate at the firm, had
asked for her help.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Massey brought in the account in 1985 because of
his association with a young man who worked for Madison. In April
1994, she told a nationally televised news conference:
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very bright young associate in our office who had
a relationship with one of the officers at Madison, a young man
whom he had known,'' she said. ``Those two young men thought it
would be legal under Arkansas law for a savings and loan to issue
preferred stock, but there was absolutely no law on that, but they
couldn't be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that ``the young attorney'' came to her because she
knew McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, she added another detail in an interview
with the Resolution Trust Corp., the organization created to
liquidate the assets of failed savings and loans. She said that
James McDougal still owed the law firm money from a previous case
and that she became involved because she was the most likely person
to get him to pay the debt before the law firm would agree to
represent Madison.
</P>
<P>
   When Massey testified before Congress in January 1996, he
remembered events differently. He said that he was not responsible
for signing up Madison as a client and he did not recall any
conversation with Clinton in which he asked her to help him sign up
Madison and deal with McDougal's past debts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses have said that McDougal had settled his debts
with the law firm well before the time in 1985 that Clinton agreed
to work on the Madison account.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue was a task Clinton undertook for Madison six days
after Madison became a client. She telephoned Beverly Bassett, the
state securities commissioner in her husband's administration, to
discuss a proposal for Madison to float preferred stock. Clinton
told investigators for the RTC that she did not remember whom she
spoke to at the agency. She said she had only been trying to find
out who was the appropriate official for Massey to contact.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with National Public Radio on Jan. 13, 1996, she
said: ``Well, my memory about that is that I called the office. I
do not believe that I ever talked to the commissioner. And the
reason that I called is that we didn't know _ namely Mr. Massey and
the law firm _ who in the securities office was to handle this kind
of work because it was something new for Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   But the regulator, by then Beverly Bassett Schaffer, recalled
the conversation in detail when she testified before the Whitewater
committee. She said that Clinton, in fact, had spoken with her and
discussed the substance of the proposal to issue the stock. Massey,
for his part, testified that he had already known which person in
the state securities office to deal with on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Another lingering issue the final report is likely to address is
the batch of missing billing records discovered inexplicably in a
family room of the White House years after they were sought by
investigators. The billing records bear on two issues: how much
work Clinton did on the Madison account and her role in helping
with a troubled real estate transaction known as Castle Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The billing records showed that she put in about 60 hours of
work on the Madison account over a little more than a year. Her
lawyers have said that confirms her assertion that her contribution
was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   But the billing records show that most of her work came in a
short period, and that it was devoted to helping McDougal and Seth
Ward, a Little Rock businessman, develop a plot near Little Rock
known as Castle Grande. Clinton first said that she had never done
any work on Castle Grande, which was termed a sham transaction by
bank examiners.
</P>
<P>
   When the billing records showed that Clinton billed for more
than 30 hours of work on Castle Grande, she said that she had never
known the project by that name. She said that the development had
been known in her office only as the International Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, lawyers in the independent counsel's office
fiercely debated whether to charge Clinton with perjury. One senior
prosecutor even drafted a sample indictment, but that course was
ultimately rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel did end up successfully prosecuting
several other Arkansas figures, however, including Gov. Jim Guy
Tucker, who resigned from office.
</P>
<P>
   FBI FILES
</P>
<P>
   Allegations about Clinton's role in the improper acquisition by
the White House of some 900 confidential FBI files had two
components.
</P>
<P>
   First, an FBI agent said he had been told that Clinton was
behind the hiring of Craig Livingstone, the White House official
who was at the center of obtaining the files. Second, some
Republicans charged that the files had been acquired at Clinton's
behest to be used as a political intelligence-gathering tool. Many
of the files were of prominent Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In March, however, Ray said that he had completed his
investigation and that the files had been acquired through a series
of errors committed by midlevel officials at the White House. And
he dismissed the notion that Clinton had been behind Livingstone's
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the FBI files matter, the independent counsel determined
that there was no substantial credible evidence that any senior
White House official, or first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, was
involved in seeking confidential Federal Bureau of Investigation
background reports of former White House staff from the
administrations of President Bush and President Reagan,'' Ray
reported.
</P>
<P>
   COMMODITIES TRADES
</P>
<P>
   One issue that was never investigated was Clinton's
extraordinary profits in trading in the commodities markets over
nine months in 1978 and 1979. Records show she turned an initial
investment of $1,000 into profits of nearly $100,000. She initially
said that she had placed all the trades herself and had made her
decisions by consulting a friend, James Blair, a poultry company
executive whose business was regulated by the state, and studying
the market in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   She later acknowledged that Blair had placed many of her trades
on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's good fortune in the commodities futures market has
been in the news in recent days, but the reason was that her
Republican opponent for the Senate, Rick Lazio, was the subject
newspaper reports about his own investments. The news accounts
reported Lazio, a Long Island congressman, had turned a $2,300
stock market investment in a company owned by his political
supporters into nearly $16,000 in a matter of weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
