<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN LEADER TAKES PRAGMATIC APPROACH
</HEADLINE>
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe, June 18 _ As waves of political violence and
lawlessness wash across this country, the people here look south
for hope. There, at the foot of the continent, sits South Africa,
the beacon of democracy and the uncontested superpower of
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The former South African president, Nelson Mandela, cast his
moral mantle over the continent. His successor, Thabo Mbeki, seemed
to continue that policy, proclaiming the dawning of an ``African
renaissance'' in which leaders would no longer tolerate despots or
ignore the cries of the weak and oppressed.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Zimbabwe lurches toward next weekend's parliamentary
elections and growing numbers of opposition party supporters have
been beaten, killed and intimidated, South Africa remains
remarkably silent.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no condemnations of President Robert Mugabe, 76,
who is widely blamed for condoning or instigating the worst
political clashes here in more than a decade. Instead, Mbeki
praises Mugabe in public and prods him in private, treading
carefully with a significant trading partner and ally and ignoring
the howls of protest from human rights activists here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   One year after he inherited the reins of power from Mandela,
Mbeki is increasingly embracing a pragmatic foreign policy
seemingly driven more by national interest than humanitarian
principle.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, he has pledged soldiers to keep the peace in
Congo, sent helicopters to rescue Mozambicans from floods and
traveled to the West as a champion of debt relief, foreign
investment and poverty reduction for his struggling continent.
</P>
<P>
   But in December, Mbeki declined to meet one-on-one with the
Dalai Lama, in part because some officials feared a meeting might
endanger South Africa's budding economic relations with China. And
this month, the Mbeki government drew sharp criticism from Amnesty
International, the human rights group, for considering arms sales
to the Chinese despite that country's spotty human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   And as South Africa's post-apartheid democracy flexes its
diplomatic muscles in a world that looks more and more toward
Africa for solutions to African problems, political analysts say
they expect to see more behind-the-scenes negotiating and less
tongue-lashing from the continent's biggest economic and military
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mandela really used his presidency as a bully pulpit,'' said
Chris Landsberg, a lecturer in international relations at the
University of the Witswatersrand in Johannesburg. ``Thabo will
articulate the importance of those same norms, democracy, good
governance, the rule of law. What he will not do is mention names.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't go to Washington and single out Mugabe publicly. And
in the future, I think we're going to see more instead of less of
this quiet diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a strategy pursued by many powerful nations as they strive
to influence, rather than alienate, ideologically wayward, but
strategically important leaders and countries.
</P>
<P>
   And while opposition party leaders here have condemned Mbeki for
negotiating quietly with Mugabe as well as American, British, and
other European officials to resolve the crisis, Strobe Talbott,
deputy secretary of state in the Clinton administration, praised
Mbeki's handling of the situation during a visit to South Africa
last month.
</P>
<P>
   South African officials say they have little choice. Mugabe is
widely viewed as a proud and mercurial leader who responds poorly
to public criticism. They say they cannot afford to lose their
leverage with such an important neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is South Africa's largest regional trading partner,
although exports to Zimbabwe account for only about 3.5 percent of
its total trade. And Mugabe, a staunch supporter of the South
African anti-apartheid struggle, remains a key player in southern
Africa. Alienating him, officials say, could threaten regional
trade agreements and peace efforts in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   So in April, Mbeki told Mugabe privately to tone down the heated
rhetoric, end the violence, hold free and fair elections and obey
the rule of law, South African officials say. In return, Mbeki
promised to negotiate with the West to free up funds for land
redistribution and to argue Zimbabwe's case with officials from the
International Monetary Fund, which is withholding financial
support.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has had some success. Mugabe did agree to allow
international observers to monitor the parliamentary elections,
scheduled for Saturday and Sunday. And donors have agreed in
principle to finance land reform. But the violence has only become
worse, leaving opposition party members here feeling betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, at least 26 people have been killed and 150
injured, most of them black supporters of the new opposition party,
the Movement for Democratic Change. But during a visit to Zimbabwe
last month, Mbeki made no mention of the attacks. Instead, he
praised Mugabe for his support in the era of South Africa's
struggle against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to take this opportunity publicly to salute
President Mugabe, the rest of the leadership and the people of
Zimbabwe for what they did to ensure our liberation from apartheid
tyranny,'' Mbeki said in a speech at the opening of the Zimbabwe
Trade Show in Bulawayo, while members of the opposition shook their
heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2150EDT &QL; 
