<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-VIOLENCE-2ND     06-18 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-VIOLENCE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HARARE, ZIMBABWE: in disbelief.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``South Africa provided moral leadership to the region under
President Nelson Mandela,'' said Welshman Ncube, the
secretary-general of the Movement for Democratic Change. ``We
looked to South Africa in admiration and hope. It is a grave
disservice to the people of Zimbabwe and the region that they align
themselves with despots.''
</P>
<P>
   South African officials acknowledge that Mugabe has not
responded as the Zimbabwean opposition had hoped. But they contend
there would have been no progress at all if he had publicly rebuked
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, on the other hand, has spoken out about Zimbabwe. But
even Mandela, who is celebrated as one of the world's pre-eminent
moral voices, had to juggle humanitarian principle and national
interest at times when he was president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for instance, Mandela decided to close South Africa's
embassy in Taiwan, a country that was considered supportive of the
liberation struggle, as a prelude to establishing full diplomatic
ties with China. And another longtime supporter with a poor human
rights record, President Fidel Castro of Cuba, kept Mandela's
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   For similar reasons, Mbeki's government quietly allowed the
former Ethiopian dictator, Mengistu Haile Mariam, to receive
medical treatment in South Africa last year while human rights
activists angrily clamored for his extradition. Mengistu, another
champion of South Africa's liberation struggle, is wanted in
Ethiopia on charges that he committed genocide during his rule.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the South African government acknowledge that there
is still much work to be done in Zimbabwe. But South Africa is
still feeling its way in foreign policy as it reaches beyond its
borders after decades of apartheid-era isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be wrong,'' said Mbeki, reflecting on his government's
Zimbabwe strategy, during an interview with foreign journalists
last month. ``I mean, somebody may say that perhaps we'd produce
results by shouting, denouncing. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm saying we've proceeded from the position that there
are problems there,'' he said ``But this is our neighbor. We have
to live with the Zimbabweans forever here. So let's end this
violence. But let's look for a cooperative approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
