<HEADER>
A7751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-TAKESHITA-NYT &LR;      06-18 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TAKESHITA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBORU TAKESHITA, 76, FORMER JAPANESE PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Noboru Takeshita, a former prime minister, and one of
the legendary kingmakers of postwar politics in Japan, died Monday
in a Tokyo hospital after a long illness. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Takeshita (pronounced tah-kesh-tah), who was prime minister from
1987 to 1989, during the height of Japan's financial power, was
forced to resign from office by a stocks-for-favors scandal that
involved much of his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   But his influence over Japanese politics flourished, even in
resignation, as he used his control over the largest faction in the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party to pick a succession of prime
ministers and, it was widely believed, direct their policies.
</P>
<P>
   Takeshita's last hand-picked government was that of his longtime
protege, Keizo Obuchi, who became prime minister in July 1998. When
Obuchi suffered a debilitating stroke in April, his chief Cabinet
secretary, Mikio Aoiki, was widely reported to have spent four
hours at Takeshita's sickbed, plotting the prime minister's
succession.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi died in May and was replaced by Yoshiro Mori, a leader of
another Liberal Democratic Party faction. Mori's accession to
power, however, was made possible only through the approval of
Takeshita's former faction.
</P>
<P>
   Takeshita was said to have been deeply affected by Obuchi's
stroke, and he resigned the seat he had held in Japan's Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Kakuei Tanaka, who had served as prime minister in
the 1970s, Takeshita was widely considered a principal architect of
the patronage-driven, machine-driven system of government that has
characterized Japanese politics since the country's rise to
economic power starting in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It was a system that de-emphasized policy matters and
concentrated instead on building the kind of consensus needed to
cobble together the complex coalitions needed to wield power within
the Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's overwhelming policy priority in much of this period was
rapid economic growth, a concentration on gross national product,
leading the ruling party's ideology to be dubbed GNP-ism by some.
</P>
<P>
   Tanaka, and later Takeshita, wielded their influence by
receiving a steady flow of visits from lawmakers eager to
redistribute some of Japan's new wealth to their districts, and
contractors eager to collect some of the budgetary windfall that
came from the country's ambitious development plans.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tokyo and other large cities grew immensely during this
period, both men favored rural, underdeveloped areas of Japan. And
together with the government's huge subsidies for Japan's rice
farmers, their heavy spending in so-called rear-Japan _ the
country's western hinterlands _ ensured the loyalty of rural voters
as the bedrock of the Liberal Democratic Party's electoral base.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, however, would be brought down by scandals caused by
the close and scarcely regulated collusion between government and
business.
</P>
<P>
   Takeshita was forced from office after admitting that he
accepted illegal stock and cash donations from Recruit Co., a
publishing and telecommunications firm. The scandal involved large
payments from Recruit to leaders of the Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Takeshita resisted the calls for his resignation,
even as three of his ministers were forced to leave office.
Finally, though, with some opinion polls showing as little as 3
percent support for his government, Takeshita agreed to step down.
He was never charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Takeshita had another brush with scandal in 1992, when it was
revealed that his allies had paid Japanese organized-crime groups
to put down a smear campaign that far-right groups were waging
against him. The payments were later confirmed by Shin Kanemaru,
another powerful Liberal Democratic Party politician and associate
of Takeshita, who acknowledged his role in a 1996 interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although cited less often, Takeshita's influence over Japan's
economic direction was comparable in scope to his influence on
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Where his predecessor as prime minister, Yasuhiro Nakasone, had
failed to pass a highly unpopular consumption tax, Takeshita, in
his quiet, back-room way, quickly cobbled together the necessary
coalition and passed it.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest legacy, however, predated his term as prime
minister. As the powerful finance minister, in 1985, Takeshita
signed the Plaza Accord, in which the world's wealthy nations
agreed to push down the value of the dollar. After the agreement,
Japan's currency, the yen, soared. In response, the government
imposed a series of interest-rate cuts that quickly sent asset
prices soaring.
</P>
<P>
   During the ensuing decade, known as the bubble years, stock and
real estate prices reached astronomical levels. At one point, the
land on which Japan's Imperial Palace is located was said to be
worth more than the entire state of California.
</P>
<P>
   Noboru Takeshita was born on February 26, 1924, in the farm
village of Kakeya in western Japan, the son of a sake brewer. He
served in the Japanese army during World War II as an instructor.
He was a graduate of the prestigious Waseda University in Tokyo,
and before turning to politics, he managed a high school judo team
and was an English teacher, though he would later acknowledge that
he did not speak the language very well.
</P>
<P>
   He was first elected to office in 1951, winning a local assembly
seat in his native Shimane Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
   Takeshita was first elected to Parliament in 1958 at age 34 and
rose in the ruling-party ranks under the tutelage of Tanaka, who
was prime minister from 1972 to 1974. He was chief Cabinet
secretary _ typically a launching pad for higher office _ for
another of Japan's most powerful postwar prime ministers, Eisaku
Sato, and again under Tanaka.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife Naoko, whom he had known since
childhood, and by three daughters and several grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
