<HEADLINE>
BEFORE SHAWN GREEN, THERE WAS HANK GREENBERG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Film: ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg''
</P>
<P>
   Credits: Produced, written and directed by Aviva Kempner
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Now showing: Laemmle Town Center in Encino, Village Twin in
Westlake Village and Landmark at Westside Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Why it's worth seeing: From the opening strains of a Yiddish
translation of ``Take Me Out to the Ballgame,'' Kempner's glowing
documentary examines how the Hall of Fame first baseman/outfielder
with the Detroit Tigers in the '30s and '40s was considered
baseball's version of Moses to Jewish Americans.
</P>
<P>
   While not deeply religious, Greenberg felt an obligation to his
heritage in a city with strong anti-Semetic leadership, riled by
the emergence of Hitler overseas. Only after Greenberg gave up four
years of his playing career to fight for the U.S. during World War
II did that societal bigotry somewhat change - ironically, as his
attitude about religion even soured more.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the narration is by Greenberg himself, taken from tapes
he recorded during the last months of his life (he died of cancer
at age 75 in 1986) in preparation of an autobiography released in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know: Jackie Robinson credits Greenberg with helping him
make the transition to the big leagues. In 1947, when Robinson
broke the color barrier, Greenberg was in his final season for the
Pittsburgh Pirates. While he would not allow his teammates to taunt
Robinson as other teams did, Greenberg confided with Robinson about
the similar razzing he had to endure, which Robinson later admitted
made Greenberg one of his heroes.
</P>
<P>
   End quote: ``(Growing up) I wanted to be Hank Greenberg ... I
joined the Beverly Hills Tennis Club because he was a member.'' -
actor Walter Matthau.
</P>
<P>
   More info: The film's Web site: www.hankgreenbergfilm.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
