<SLUG> BC-NY-EGAN-INSTALL-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ARCHBISHOP TAKES HELM IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With chants, scriptures and a moving tale of his own
to mark continuity and a new beginning, Edward Michael Egan took
the throne of St. Patrick's Cathedral on Sunday and, in ancient
rites of magisterial splendor, was invested as the ninth archbishop
of New York, the nation's most visible Roman Catholic leader.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks after his appointment by Pope John Paul II, the tall,
commanding 68-year-old churchman, a theological conservative and
canon lawyer who has been the bishop of Bridgeport, Conn., for 12
years, entered the packed cathedral in a choral procession of
ecclesiastical banners, honor guards and church officials.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been a scene from Raphael or Titian: The cathedral
bathed in Florentine light, arches within arches, vaulted stone
pillars, soaring stained glass, the rapt faces of priests, nuns and
laity arrayed over the vast, gray drafty interior, and at the focus
a bishop radiant in white vestments.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling broadly, relaxed, obviously enjoying himself, he made
his way up the center aisle to the basso profundo of the cathedral
organ and the sustained applause of 2,700 people, including members
of his family, 800 friends from Bridgeport and hundreds more in
clerical garb and habits of religious orders.
</P>
<P>
   On the crowded altar, still in his bishop's red skullcap, he
presented his letter of appointment from the pope _ a document in
Latin on parchment _ to the archdiocesan officials. It was read
aloud by the Vatican's ambassador to the United States, Archbishop
Gabriel Montalvo, then stamped with the seal of the archdiocese and
handed to church officials for the archives.
</P>
<P>
   As thunderous applause swelled over the echoing cathedral,
Archbishop Egan donned a miter of office, was seated in the carved
wood throne of St. Patrick's and thus formally succeeded Cardinal
John J. O'Connor as head of the nation's most prominent Catholic
archdiocese, a 10-county realm of 2.4 million members, 413 parishes
and hundreds of schools, hospitals and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I humbly stand before each and every priest, deacon, religious
and member of the laity at this beautiful service to announce that
I come only to serve you, and all of the community in the three
boroughs and seven counties of the Archdiocese of New York,'' he
declared moments later in his first homily as archbishop. ``I come
with joy to serve to the best of my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled having served as vicar for education in the New York
archdiocese for three and a half years in the 1980s, and said he
had been ``continually captivated by the wonder and goodness'' of a
community of faith that educated its children, aided the sick and
needy, held tenaciously to church teachings and rejected ``all
forms of discrimination, mistreatment and cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop devoted most of his homily, however, to the story
of a young man he met one summer in New York _ a parable-like tale
of blood, compassion, riches and ultimately humility. At an
ordination ceremony with Mother Teresa in the poor neighborhood of
High Bridge in the Bronx, he said, a man suddenly staggered into
the church, bloody from a beating, shouting and sobbing for help.
Mother Teresa and other sisters, he said, took the man into a room
off the altar, calmed him, washed his wounds and found him a place
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, the archbishop said, a young man who had been
in church approached him and asked to talk about what he had seen.
The man, Jon Bokron, told him: ``I'm making a pile of money in the
market, but I need to be part of what I witnessed in that
sacristy.'' The man eventually became a priest and was ordained by
Bishop Egan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I am coming to join,'' the archbishop said, ``a
community of faith whose compassion and sacrificial self-giving can
melt the heart of a young man making a fortune on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years after becoming a priest, the man died of leukemia, and
Egan was at his bedside in his final days. ``I felt his loss
intensely,'' the archbishop said. He noted that the gold crucifix
on his chest, worn only on the most important occasions, had
belonged to Father Bokron, and was a reminder of him and of Christ.
``It is my inspiration, it is my strength,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Egan did not speak of policy matters or the direction his
administration of the archdiocese might take, he concluded his
homily with a message in Spanish, a gesture to Hispanic people who
make up one-third of the archdiocese. ``You can be sure that in the
coming years, I will do all that is possible to serve you as our
Father, God, has served,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's investiture _ known as a Ceremony of Canonical
Possession _ began two days of installation rites at the cathedral,
each followed by receptions around town to welcome the new
archbishop, who moved Sunday night into his official residence on
Madison Avenue behind the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ceremonies are to be more elaborate and celebratory: a
Mass of Installation with Egan presiding, a procession of 700
priests and an audience of 3,500, including eight cardinals and
hundreds of other church dignitaries, as well as scores of public
officials and other invited guests.
</P>
<P>
   Among those scheduled to attend are the four U.S. Senators from
New York and Connecticut, the New York Senate candidates Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Rep. Rick A. Lazio, Supreme Court Justices
Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, Gov. George E. Pataki and Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 90-minute ceremony was a more formal affair, a blend of
solemn ritual and canon law to invest authority in the new
archbishop, but it was full of pageantry and music, celebrated with
vespers, a service of evening prayers, choral psalms and scriptural
readings, unfolding as the day waned. There were prayers in
Ukrainian, Korean, Malayalam (a language of southwest India),
Tagalog, Arabic, Vietnamese, Spanish and Igbo (a Nigerian tongue).
</P>
<P>
   The skies were overcast and gray as the archbishop-elect arrived
on the cathedral's north terrace shortly before 4 p.m. Wearing a
white chasuble over a red alb, and a red skullcap, he was met by
Montalvo, the papal nuncio, and by Bishops Robert Brucato and
Patrick Sheridan, the apostolic administrator and the vicar general
of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   On a day that was largely scripted, the archbishop-elect,
surprising his security detail, turned aside on the steps to bless
4-month-old Amanda Brennan Hoffer, held by her father, John, while
her mother, Danielle, snapped pictures. The family, from
Hillsborough, N.J., beamed, and so did crowds on Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral's great central doors then swung open and the
archbishop-elect entered, taking his place at the rear of a
procession of banners, student honor guards, archbishops and
bishops from across the country and dozens of priests and other
officials of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   At the head of the procession were members of an intercultural
council, under a banner proclaiming ``Unus Dominus Una Fides, Unum
Baptisma'' (One Lord, One Faith, One Baptism). Then came students
carrying banners representing the counties of the archdiocese:
Manhattan, the Bronx, Staten Island, Westchester, Rockland, Putnam,
Orange, Sullivan, Ulster and Dutchess.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral interior glowed softly under the high chandeliers
as Sheridan presented the archbishop-elect with a crucifix, which
he kissed. Msgr. Anthony Dalla Villa, the rector of St. Patrick's,
then handed him an aspergil, a Holy Water sprinkler, which he used
to bless the procession and the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   As the procession moved toward the sanctuary, votive candles
flickered in violet shadows on the edges of the nave and transept.
Organ music vibrated against the stone and marble, and a 100-voice
choir sang timeless hymns and haunting psalms in the late spring
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   On the altar above the crypt where O'Connor was entombed after
his death on May 3 at age 80, the archbishop-elect sat on a
faldstool, used by a bishop in a church not (or in this case not
yet) his own. He handed his letter of appointment to Montalvo, who
read it aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as we mourn the sad passing of our venerable brother John
Joseph O'Connor, the late archbishop of New York, we naturally and
spontaneously choose you, venerable brother, whom we know to be an
experienced herald of the Gospel and administrator well-versed in
the affairs of the church, to fill the vacant See of New York and
to resume the interrupted governance of the Catholic community
there,'' the papal letter declared.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was then given to Msgr. Edward O'Donnell, the
chancellor of the archdiocese, who notarized it by affixing the
archdiocesan seal and turned it over to the Board of Consultors,
which empowers a bishop to exercise authority.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the pope's appointee became the ninth archbishop
(and 12th bishop) to lead the archdiocese. Egan then put on an
ivory miter and was escorted by Montalvo to the cathedra, the
throne of St. Patrick's, where he was seated and welcomed by the
assembled officials.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Egan's homily, especially the story of the young men inspired to
the priesthood, touched many in the crowd, including Msgr. Kevin
Sullivan, the chief operating officer of Catholic Charities in
Manhattan. ``I think that's just a tremendous vision to encourage
all of us New Yorkers to recognize, especially in a city that knows
a lot of power, a lot of wealth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Hernandez, a Mexican immigrant who lives in the Bronx
and attended the service with his wife, said he was impressed with
the archbishop's efforts to reach out to the Spanish-speaking
community. ``We're saddened by the death of Cardinal O'Connor, who
was very good to us,'' he said. ``But another chosen person is
here, and he'll represent us, he'll take care of us. He is making
us feel like we're part of the church and part of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   As Egan left the cathedral, shaking hands with old friends,
winking, beaming, stopping momentarily to thank well-wishers,
Evelyn Aquaro, a retired teacher, began to cry. ``The procession at
the end brought tears to my eyes,'' she said, ``because it brought
forth all my Catholic background and all the teachings. I was very
moved by the ceremony. I was impressed with the archbishop, his
manner, and I was really touched by the way he was able to speak in
other languages.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan is fluent in Latin, Italian and French and learned Spanish
in Bridgeport, home to many Hispanic Catholics. Much of his 43-year
career has been spent in upper echelons of the church, including 14
years in the Vatican, where he often worked with the pope, and 7
years as an aide to Cardinal John Cody in Chicago. In Bridgeport,
he was active in fund-raising, recruiting priests and reorganizing
schools and parishes. But critics said that he had been more of a
legal adversary than a pastor to parishioners who said they had
been sexually abused by priests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
