<SLUG> BC-PC-FUTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESKTOP COMPUTING HAS LONG FUTURE, DESPITE WEB VISIONS, EXPERT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As Microsoft prepares to announce its Next
Generation Windows Services initiative this week, an influential
computer scientist is circulating a thesis that challenges Bill
Gates' vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Microsoft Corp. plans to describe its most
radically new computing strategy since December 1995, when Gates,
the Microsoft chairman, announced the ``embrace and extend''
strategy to expand the company's dominance of desktop computing to
include the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will now push to shift the locus of computing off the
desktop altogether _ and out into a ``cloud'' of large server
computers located on the Internet. But the goal is the same as the
one laid out five years ago: maintaining a central role for
Microsoft's software.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, an influential critic is arguing that
Microsoft's new strategy may be a defensive plan that misjudges the
computer industry's future direction, that rather than moving to an
increasingly Web-centric model, computing is instead becoming
decentralized, with the key information distributed among millions
of desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds as if Microsoft is scared and defensive,'' the
critic, David Gelernter, said in a telephone interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has based its reputation on refusing to lead and
always following, and once again they're behind the wave here,''
said Gelernter, a respected Yale University computer scientist.
``More and more people are coming to understand that the power of
desktop machines is enormous and is largely wasted when you spend
your time browsing on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelernter's argument is spelled out in ``The Second Coming _ a
Manifesto,'' an essay published last week in the German newspaper
Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, and posted on the Edge, a
technology forum on the Web (www.edge.org).
</P>
<P>
   Gelernter's critique has some influential supporters, including
Danny Hillis, a computer scientist who recently left Walt Disney's
Imagineering research group to form a new company, Applied Minds;
David Ditzel, a computer designer who is the founder of Transmeta
Inc., a Silicon Valley microprocessor company; and Rodney Brooks,
director of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Artificial
Intelligence Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's criticisms of our current computing environments are
eloquently stated, and I think widely shared,'' Brooks wrote in a
recent comment posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's head of research, Rick Rashid, countered that
Gelernter was taking an academic, long-term view of computing that
might have little relevance for the current software market. ``It's
fairly predictable that David would be saying this,'' said Rashid,
a Microsoft senior vice president. ``This has been his mantra
throughout his career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Second Coming,'' a 10,000-word essay, contends that rather
than remaining a world that Microsoft or any company might
dominate, computing is actually shifting to a world in which data
and computer processing will be increasingly spread across
thousands, if not millions, of interconnected computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information travels through a sea of anonymous,
interchangeable computers like a breeze through tall grass,''
Gelernter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Rashid said Gelernter's criticism did not reflect the degree
to which data was already being distributed across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's already happening,'' Rashid said. ``There is already a
sea of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has pointed to Passport, a current e-commerce service
offered by the company, as the best example of what the Next
Generation Windows Services architecture will be like. Passport, a
program that verifies the identities of computer users when they
surf to a new site, is a clear example of the way data is now
flowing through the Internet between computers that are only
loosely coupled, Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passport actually encompasses a huge amount of distributed
computing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Gelernter's vision of a distributed computing
future is likely to be an accurate in the long term. He noted that
there had been a long tug-of-war between the ideas of centralized
and decentralized computing.
</P>
<P>
   Gelernter, who was seriously injured in 1993 by a mail bomb from
the so-called Unabomber, is a well-known computer scientist. His
credentials include his 1991 book ``Mirror Worlds,'' which forecast
the arrival of the World Wide Web and described a future in which
computing would make it possible to simulate virtually any aspect
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   As a software designer during the 1980s, Gelernter developed a
programming language known as Linda that was designed to spread
computations across hundreds of thousands of computers, harnessing
them into one distributed machine. Similar systems are now common
in the world of supercomputing.
</P>
<P>
   But distributed computing has been slow to arrive in the
mainstream computing world, and Gelernter places the blame for the
lack of innovation to a great extent on the absence of a new
computing vision from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that Microsoft's Windows 98 and Windows 2000
software is derived from the Apple Macintosh and the Unix operating
systems, which he derides as fragile, decades-old technologies that
lock away much of the power of computing from nonexpert users.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the bulliest pulpit in the world,'' Gelernter said
of Microsoft, ``but what have they done with it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ONLINE-ACCOUNTS-NYT     06-18 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-ACCOUNTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPLETE FINANCIAL PICTURE ON ONE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  By PATRICK MCGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Banks and brokerage firms are racing to offer the newest new
thing in online financial services: a single place where customers
can find up-to-date information about all of their accounts at a
range of institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, big financial firms saw this innovation,
known as account aggregation, as a threat to their customers'
privacy and financial security. But now, fearing an onslaught of
competition on the Internet, they are embracing it as a convenience
for customers and a powerful tool for building their own business.
Instead of warning against the service, banks are now telling their
customers to be wary of obtaining such services from anyone but
them.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Bank, hoping to get a head start on its
traditional competitors, is expected to announce Monday that it is
teaming up with a year-old Internet-based company called Yodlee.com
to introduce free account-aggregation services later this year for
Chase's 30 million online customers. Other major banks and
brokerage firms, including Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and the PaineWebber
Group, are considering offering similar services through Yodlee or
one of about a dozen other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new services are expected to be free to consumers,
at least initially.
</P>
<P>
   These firms are reacting to the Internet-based businesses that
are offering account aggregation with the hope of serving as a
financial home page for consumers. Ameritrade Holdings, which
operates a popular online brokerage, has been offering account
aggregation at its Onmoney.com site on the Web, and earlier this
month, America Online announced an alliance with Yodlee to provide
a similar service for AOL's 22 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, fewer than 300,000 people have registered for account
aggregation, which compiles a variety of information from different
sources, from savings and checking balances at a bank to the value
of stocks and bonds in brokerage accounts to the frequent-flier
miles customers have accumulated with airlines. But financial
industry executives predict that many more people will sign up for
the service as major firms demonstrate their acceptance of the
technology behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Using a process known as ``screen scraping,'' companies like
Yodlee gain electronic access, usually overnight, to their
customers' accounts at various financial institutions and download
them into a central file. In the morning, a user can log in and get
a current snapshot of her finances on one computer screen, or even
on the screen of a hand-held device like a Palm Pilot or a wireless
phone.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off for that convenience is that customers must
surrender the electronic passwords to all of their financial
accounts. That is an exchange that some privacy advocates warn
against. Even purveyors of the service acknowledge that most people
are uneasy about disclosing that information, especially to a
company they had never heard of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing for someone to go to a start-up with an unusual
name like Yodlee and ask them to keep all of their personal
financial data,'' said Anil Arora, chief executive of Yodlee, based
in Sunnyvale, Calif. ``It's another thing to go to a company like
Chase that you already use as your primary financial company.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Zimmerman, a senior vice president of Chase, said that in
a survey, about 45 percent of consumers said they would use an
account-aggregation service if it were provided by a financial
institution they trusted. ``We know that not everyone is going to
use this tomorrow, but we think customers want this service and the
time is right for us to take a leadership position in offering
it,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Account aggregation could prove very valuable to banks like
Chase. Financial institutions want a complete picture of their
customers' finances. They want to know what assets _ and debts _
their customers have elsewhere, both to protect themselves and to
create opportunities to sell more products, like credit cards,
loans and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   When its customers start using account aggregation, Chase will
get a peek at their outside holdings, like a brokerage account at
Merrill Lynch or use of an American Express card, and will be able
to use that information to create solicitations to them. Chase will
apply its own standards for privacy and security to the service,
even though it will be operated by Yodlee, Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   If customers do not want to receive pitches for credit cards or
other products, he said, they can choose to be removed from mailing
and calling lists. ``You have the right at any point to say, `Do
not call me, do not make me an offer,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial industry executives say that using account
aggregation as a tool for aggressive cross-selling could backfire.
``The firms that approach it that way are going to lose,'' said
Marten Hoekstra, director of marketing at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, financial firms should treat account aggregation as a
necessary convenience that all customers will soon demand and as a
critical offering to cement relationships with customers, he said.
Within a few years, brokerage firms will be using this innovation
to offer to advise customers on the management of all of their
assets, whether they are held in banks or at competing brokerages,
Hoekstra said.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber is negotiating with Yodlee and several of its
competitors, but it has not settled on a partner for the account
aggregation services it plans to offer because the technology has
not been perfected, Hoekstra said. ``It's a must-do as soon as it's
reliable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch already offers an early version of account
aggregation, for a monthly fee, to its wealthiest customers, those
with at least $5 million invested at the firm, through Greentrak, a
small, private company in New Rochelle, N.Y. The new management
team for Merrill's brokerage operation is considering whether to
offer a simpler form of account aggregation, through an
Internet-based service like Yodlee's, to all of its customers,
according to people at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's in the financial services area wants to try to
own the total financial relationship with clients,'' said Lon
Massingil, executive vice president of Greentrak. ``That's the race
that's going on now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
