<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS' MILLER: TIME FOR A SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK   
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - The Pacers lost their first two games at the
Staples Center, and Reggie Miller was quiet as an Al Gore booster.
</P>
<P>
   He had his infamous 1-for-16 game in the opener. He came back
with 21 points in Game 2 but failed to score in the fourth quarter
of a game the Pacers could have stolen.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller came alive in Indiana, averaging 31 points a game and
shooting .545 from beyond the 3-point line, and the Pacers know
they need the deadly Miller if they are to make history.
</P>
<P>
   No team in the Finals has ever come back from a 3-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I can put on a better show than I did in the first
two games,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having shot the ball pretty well back home, I feel I'm in a
pretty good groove and a nice little rhythm, so it's definitely
time to be more aggressive on the offensive end.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history indicates the Lakers should beware. He's made a
habit of being there when the Pacers needed him in these playoffs.
In each of Indiana's three previous closeout games, Miller was the
leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   He's averaged 33.3 points in their closeout games, including 41
in the one-point victory in Game 5 in the opening round against
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Bird, however, said the Pacers would be better
served not looking for Miller to carry the scoring load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the emphasis (tonight) is to continue to move the
basketball,'' Bird said. ``I don't care who gets the points.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get good ball movement, we're going to score a lot of
points. If we get stagnated, and try to post Reggie up and depend
on him getting too much, it's going to cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Road less traveled: The Staples Center might have a brief
history, but it hasn't been a pleasant one for Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have lost all four games they played here this
season, including both games of the Finals, and regular-season
games against the Lakers and ... Clippers?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clippers beat us there, the Lakers beat us there,'' Bird
said. ``Hell, anybody can beat is in there. Maybe we're due.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jalen Rose points out the Pacers have won at least one
road game in every other series to this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can find a way to do that with Game 6, then
everybody tells us, in Game 7 anything can happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Points 'R' us: Both teams are scoring at an unusual clip in the
2000 NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Spurs averaged 84.8 points per game in capturing
the title over the Knicks, who averaged 79.8 points.
</P>
<P>
   Through five games in the Finals this year, the Pacers are
averaging 105.8 points and the Lakers 102.6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Defense typically tightens in the playoffs, as teams become
increasingly familiar with their opponents, but both teams are over
their season averages (Pacers, 101.3; Lakers 100.8).
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we can't get any better,'' Bird said. ``We're
shooting the ball extremely well, we're moving the basketball,
we're finding open guys, we're hitting a lot of 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by the scores of the last two games. I like it,
but defense wins you championships. If we can hold them to 85-to-87
points, we have a good chance of beating them.''
</P>
<P>
   A dad remembered: Mark Jackson, who lost his dad this past
season, battled some mixed emotions Sunday on Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bittersweet day,'' he said. ``I'm a dad, so it's a
great day for me. I look at the way God has blessed me with three
beautiful children. Also when I look at my Heavenly Father. It's
great to know him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when I look at the father I was given on this Earth, a
great man who still lives in me and is missed daily. It's a great,
great day. I thank God for him, not just today on Father's Day, but
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   This and that: Enough of those road obstacles. The Pacers were
in a Santa Monica hotel during their first two games at the Staples
Center, but this time around are staying downtown. ... Guard Travis
Best (sprained right shoulder) claimed it is a game-time decision
whether he plays. He played only the first half of Game 5, before
the shoulder tightened. Said Best: ``It's very sore. I'd say it's
about the same.'' ... Rose went to the Staples Center on Saturday
to take in ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley's split-decision over Oscar De La
Hoya. Said Rose: ``I wondered what one of the judges was looking
at.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally: The Pacers claim to be loose and say the Lakers are
still in control but can't help wondering how things will turn if
there is a Game 7. Said Bird: ``If we get to the next one, I think
they'll be a little shaky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
