u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT     06-18 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX'S GOOD-GUY IMAGE NOW HAS AN EDGE TO IT 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Charismatic, intelligent and blessed with a movie
star's good looks, Los Angeles Lakers forward Rick Fox thinks he is
made for Hollywood, even saying on occasion that he would be a star
on the silver screen if he was not playing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But in watching Fox play against the Indiana Pacers, many
observers feel he is already acting out a character role in these
National Basketball Association finals. His looks, his marriage to
the singer and actress Vanessa Williams and his history of
nonconfrontation in the NBA are hard to reconcile with the way he
is suddenly pushing around and challenging the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to answer some of those kinds of questions: `Where is
this coming from? You were a model citizen and a complete angel for
10 years,''' Fox said Sunday at the Lakers' practice facility. ``In
a lot of cases, it's having enough respect to stand up for yourself
and your teammates. When challenged, if you don't put your foot
down, then guys are going to walk over your team. They are going to
have less respect for you, and in the past that has been the case
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sentiments are a sign of the tension that has built
between these clubs. Virtual strangers when this four-of-seven-game
series began, the Lakers and the Pacers are developing a sincere
dislike for one another. Fox got into an argument with Indiana's
Jalen Rose in Game 3, and exchanged heated words with Rose, Mark
Jackson and Reggie Miller in Game 5. And Jackson and Ron Harper had
a confrontation that resulted in a double-technical foul in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of bad blood,'' Lakers point guard Derek Fisher
said. ``It's not just about them; it's about this time of year.
This is now our sixth time playing this team in 12 days or so. That
is where the bad blood comes from. They get tired of getting pushed
around by Shaquille O'Neal just like we get tired of chasing their
3-point shooters around. It's not personal. It's just that we are
competing.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of it may be personal. After Indiana's 120-87 victory
in Game 5, Miller said the Lakers were not the laid-back team that
many people associate with Los Angeles and the resurrection of
Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing all the pushing, the holding,'' he said. ``Then
they look at the refs like they're not doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was almost certainly referring to what he perceived to be
dirty play by Fox. He elbowed Fox in the back while Fox was arguing
with Rose with 11 minutes remaining in Game 5. Fox, on the other
hand, believed the Pacers were getting too celebratory and cocky
near the end of their rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times in blowouts, teams take the liberty of
celebrating, enjoying themselves, having an air of bravado,'' Fox
said. ``That is something that I don't take too keenly to and I
don't think our team does either. If you let it continue, it
carries over to the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jalen and I had a great exchange. It wasn't a pleasant
exchange but it was a competitive exchange. But Reggie wants to
sneak in his exchange. He doesn't want to square up with you. I
don't think that's very manly.''
</P>
<P>
   The verbal back-and-forth probably favors the Pacers, who like
having hostile feelings toward their opponents. It is well
documented that Miller feeds off controversy, and Fox realizes that
he may be playing into the hands of the deadliest shooter in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to have a charge,'' Fox said. ``He needs to be the
villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the extra motivation, Miller and the Pacers
returned to Los Angeles with confidence. They felt tremendous after
manhandling the Lakers in Game 5 and, after averaging 119 points
the last two games, they believed they could be the ones ahead in
the series, three games to two. The Pacers attributed their Game 1
loss to nervousness about appearing in their first NBA finals,
though they missed a prime opportunity to win Game 2 after Kobe
Bryant sprained his ankle, and said that Game 4, which the Lakers
won by 120-118 in overtime, could have gone either way.
</P>
<P>
   The aura of invincibility that the Lakers had the last time they
played host to Indiana at the Staples Center is gone. ``The Lakers
are not an impossible team to beat three times in a row, especially
with the firepower we have as a team,'' said Travis Best, who is
questionable for Monday's game with a bruised left shoulder. ``This
is a closer series than people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, used to being viewed as superior all season, does
not like the arrogance and sense of entitlement that was spawned in
Indiana. The Lakers' plan is to return the Pacers to the cowering,
uncertain team they handled easily in Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have confidence because they have the chance to play
another game,'' Fisher said defensively, when asked about Indiana's
newfound brashness. ``But the fact is that we are still up, 3-2,
and now we play on our court. It's easy to feel confident at home
with your crowd. Let's see how much confidence they have tomorrow
night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
