<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S STAY HOT IN 10-2 WIN OVER TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Gil Meche can't pitch much better than this.
</P>
<P>
   Who could? Meche had allowed no runs in his past two starts,
including Sunday's six innings of three-hit ball in a 10-2 win over
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't break Meche's heart any, though, if he could go
deeper into the game. It's part of innate greed of competition _ if
you throw six shutout innings, you want to throw seven.
</P>
<P>
   Six innings is about Meche's limit these days, however. Despite
going 2-0 in his first two starts off the disabled list, Meche
continues to have problems with a ``dead arm.'' He came out of the
game Sunday in the Metrodome despite the fact that the Twins
couldn't hit him with a tennis racket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great about what I did,'' Meche said. ``Six innings, no
runs? No matter how my arm felt, I'd take that any time.''
</P>
<P>
   But ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's aggravating to go six innings, throw only 80 pitches and
know you should be good for one or two more innings,'' Meche said.
``But I just can't seem to go past there.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella said the Mariners are ready to take a new
approach with Meche. There is talk of changing his diet. Of
changing his running program. Of having him stretch his arm between
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've tried hasn't worked,'' Piniella said. ``We're
trying to figure out how to get this resolved. The disabled list
isn't the answer. If nothing else, maybe we'll try some good snake
oil.''
</P>
<P>
   With Meche winning twice, the Mariners went 7-3 on this June
road trip. In the first two months of the season, the Mariners
didn't have a winning road trip and went 10-16 overall away from
Safeco.
</P>
<P>
   And Meche's discomfort wasn't going to stand in the way of the
Mariners enjoying the results of this trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this team would play better on the road,'' DH Edgar
Martinez said. Martinez drew four walks. The one time the Twins
tried to pitch to him, Martinez launched a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, 3-4-5 hitters Alex Rodriguez, Martinez and John
Olerud were a combined 9-for-11 with a couple of homers and eight
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   For Rodriguez and Martinez, those top-notch performances have
come to be regarded as commonplace. But for Olerud, who had slumped
badly of late, this four days in the Twin Cities has resuscitated
his batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud had been stuck in a quagmire of murky offense, so much so
that he'd been dropped from fourth to fifth in the batting order
against right-handed pitching.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Metrodome, Olerud found himself at a pharmacy that
had the goods to cure many of his ills. Under the influence of
Minnesota pitching, Olerud had four hits Sunday and nine for the
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Most encouraging for the Mariners was the quality of those hits.
After not hitting a homer since April 26, Olerud went deep twice in
four games, both to center field. And of his other seven hits, four
were doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I had a good day, so the 3-4-5 guys were good today,''
said Olerud. ``I haven't been swinging as well as I'd like. I've
been missing pitches I should be able to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this was a real good series for me. I want to see it carry
over to the next series, though.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the road trip as a whole, the Mariners can once again lay
claim to being road warriors.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of this 10-game trip, the Mariners won seven times.
Before the trip started, the Mariners had just 10 road wins in 26
games.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trip started, Piniella held a meeting in the new
Pacific Bell Park in San Francisco. Part of the reason for the
meeting was to get familiar with the park. Part of it was for
Piniella to make a statement _ the 10-16 record on the road wasn't
acceptable. It was time to play good baseball on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Message received.
</P>
<P>
   As such things go, the trip was a complete success, with both
the pitching and hitting holding up. The hitters averaged .318
(110-for-346), while the pitchers compiled an earned run average of
3.87 (36 earned runs in 832/3 innings).
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we'd be better than what we've been playing,''
Rodriguez said. ``We got good pitching, we got good hitting and we
always play good defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It begins here.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
