<HEADLINE>
ON THE WEB, ONE STOP FOR DEATH SERVICES  
 WEB SITE CHALLENGES CHAT-ROOM STATUS QUO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the Web portal to the great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to heavenlydoor.com! Find a funeral home or cemetery
near you!'' reads the greeting on the home page of
HeavenlyDoor.com, which has been busily signing deals to offer
one-stop shopping for a complete line of death-related services.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week it announced deals with SympathyFlowers.com;
Classicmemorials.com; Mooney &AMP; Co., a provider of sympathy and
cremation cards; and the Funeral Fine Art Collection, which
according to the news release offers ``high-end urns.''
</P>
<P>
   The deals enable the partners to sell their wares on
HeavenlyDoor.com's site, in exchange for up to 40 percent of the
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The company was formed in November and went public in January,
and so far it has mainly offered a free online service linking
people who want to plan funerals _ in many cases, years before
anyone actually dies _ with one of the 100 funeral homes it has
signed up as members.
</P>
<P>
   But as last week's deals indicate, the company is expanding into
transactions. Helen Maynard, HeavenlyDoor's senior vice president,
said the company was discussing similar arrangements with insurance
companies, airlines and hotels. Starting in September, the company
plans to offer Heavenly Store, an online supermarket of
funeral-related services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious jewelry, ash-scattering services _ there are just so
many facets of the funeral industry that people don't automatically
think of on their own,'' Maynard said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a business-to-business play in the works, too. By
autumn, HeavenlyDoor hopes to have an electronic marketplace up and
running that will hook funeral homes up with makers of caskets and
embalming fluids and with other vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard said HeavenlyDoor.com planned to negotiate discount
contracts for its funeral-director members and hoped to make money
in transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH
</P>
<P>
   Web Site Challenges Chat-Room Status Quo
</P>
<P>
   Few marketing gimmicks challenge the status quo as much as
im-ur.com, the brainchild of Jonathan Shem-Ur, an Israeli former
journalist turned Web entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist on the traditional chat room, Shem-Ur is producing a
site with 4,000 discussion areas, sections where anybody can post
opinions, offer advice and engage in debate on assorted subjects.
Every day the comments posted in each area are displayed in the
format of a newspaper's editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   The more an opinion is read, the more prominently the opinion is
displayed in the daily forum.
</P>
<P>
   The site also takes an unusual approach to advertising:
Participants will see ads only if they want to, rather than being
barraged with banner ads on every page. To view an ad, the reader
clicks on a ``relevant ads'' logo.
</P>
<P>
   The site officially started last week, but without advertising
at first. The company said it wanted to build its audience before
trying to sell ads. Shem-Ur says he wants to turn the Web into a
great town square, much like an ancient Greek agora, where people
can air their opinions freely. He said the standard Internet chat
room, plastered with banner ads, was too chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   For a celebrity spokesman, Shem-Ur has hired Judge Joseph
Wapner, formerly of television's ``The People's Court,'' who is now
wielding the gavel on ``Judge Wapner's Animal Court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could always have your say in my court,'' Wapner said in a
statement released by the company. ``And that's what im-ur.com is
all about _ having your say.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Will advertisers agree to have their say the
im-ur way?
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
</TEXT>
