u s BC-BKN-PACERS-JACKSON-NY     06-18 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON LASTS IN A LEAGUE OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Mark Jackson attended the Oscar De La
Hoya-Shane Mosley fight on Saturday night, trying to blow off steam
with teammates before Game 6 of the NBA finals. Among those
accompanying the 35-year-old point guard to the Staples Center were
Jonathan Bender, a willowy 19-year-old, who last June was attending
his senior prom, and Al Harrington, 20, two years removed from high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got them popcorn and those cinnamon churros, or whatever you
call them,'' Jackson said. ``They were excited. But no Coke. Water
instead. I didn't want them to have too much sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   The responsible patriarch of the Indiana Pacers roster spoke on
Father's Day, slightly more than a year after his own father died.
Someone asked Jackson if the Pacers' attempt to come back from a
three-games-to-one deficit in the National Basketball Association
finals was the hardest thing he ever had to do on a basketball
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing after losing my father,'' he said. ``That was simply
the hardest. If I look back and think how I did it, it had nothing
to do with me. It was all God. There were times when I wanted to
roll over and put my head under the pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson gathered himself and forged on. As he has been doing
for much of the last four or five seasons, he lived on instincts,
skill and smarts to keep up with the NBA's kids and compensate for
his lack of athleticism. One of the few pass-first point guards
left in the league is now two victories from a championship,
blemishes in his game and all.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years after he was drafted out of St. John's, you
wonder which odds should have been longer: on Jackson playing this
long or the Pacers becoming the first team in finals history to
erase a 3-1 deficit and win in seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you leave it to the critics, probably about the same,'' he
said through a half-smile.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have referred to him as a slow-footed point guard.
``Some people even say a very slow-footed point guard,'' Jackson
said. ``When you look around and guys are on vacation now that
don't have half as many question marks as I have _ and to know that
God has put me in a position to have a Game 6 and to be the maestro
of a championship-caliber team, a guy that's as limited as me, I
can't help but thank him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is a free agent after this season, and there is no
guarantee he will return to the Pacers _ although putting the
floor-leader duties exclusively in Travis Best's hands does not
seem like the wisest move Indiana could make in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his physical limitations, Jackson still knows how to
find the open man, whether it is Reggie Miller materializing on the
perimeter from the morass of bodies in the paint or Jalen Rose
sneaking along the baseline. A prospective coaching career _ Rick
Pitino recently said he thought Jackson would become the next great
young coach in the game _ will most likely be put on hold for at
least two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The competition and the kids still enrapture Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the state of basketball in general, it's a tremendous
lesson,'' he said. ``Rather than working on some things that can
get you endorsements and praise, work on some things that can get
you here in June. Work on some things that's going to get you a
ring. Work on some things that can separate you from the pack as a
winner. Be students of the game. I learned that going to college
and watching Chris Mullin every single day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I watch guys run around like chickens without heads and I
realize that was me once.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before Game 6, Jackson recalled draft day in 1987, when
he was picked in the first round by the Knicks. ``You're thinking,
`I made it,''' he said. ``I didn't put a timetable on myself
because a lot of people didn't think I would make it. I didn't
think about playing 13 years. I was just tickled I actually
arrived. I wanted to prolong it as long as I actually could.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's been a great ride. To know there's still some
gas left in the tank makes it more enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says the Pacers ``rebuked the demons'' in Game 5, in
which the Pacers annihilated the Lakers, 120-87. He likes his
team's resilience, its ability to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a few years now, when our back is against the wall, we've
responded,'' he said. ``And we've been a lot of places. So this
isn't anything that stands out right now. This isn't nothing new to
me or this basketball team. And if I have to go down swinging with
a bunch of guys, this is the group I want to go down with.''
</P>
<P>
   His three children were back in Indiana and could speak to their
father Sunday only by telephone. He would have to make do with
Bender and Harrington, the Pacers kids he took to the fight on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of what it's going to take in this series,''
Jackson said of Mosley's thrilling victory by split decision. ``If
you want it, rather than sitting back, dancing and jabbing, you got
to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be some finish, watching the Pacers move the ball for
two more games and blend together seamlessly, five as one. Knocking
off the heavily favored Lakers of Shaq and Kobe would be an amazing
story, almost as amazing as a very slow-footed point guard playing
13 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
