<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-MOSELY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA TALKS OF RETIREMENT WHILE PROMOTER TALKS OF REMATCH WITH
MOSLEY
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hands on hips, Oscar De La Hoya stood alone in his
corner of the ring, stunned by the decision. His promoter, Bob
Arum, leaned against the ropes and looked stone-faced into the
future.
</P>
<P>
   According to De La Hoya, his welterweight title loss to Shane
Mosley on Saturday night could be his last fight. As a surprised
Arum listened after the split decision was awarded to Mosley, the
27-year-old De La Hoya announced that retirement was one option he
was considering after suffering the second defeat of his heretofore
golden career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to rethink my whole game plan in life,'' said De La
Hoya. who is 32-2 after losing two of his last three fights. ``I'm
considering a lot of things. We all know this is a business, and a
rematch would make a lot of money, but I'm not looking at it that
way. Right now, I'm thinking about my health, my career, my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He then added: ``A lot of things go on in your head after a
fight. It'll take me a few days to rethink things.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another in a series of classic De La Hoya contradictions,
the least of which was his performance in the later rounds before a
crowd of 20,744 at the Staples Center. Mosley (35-0) dominated from
the seventh round on, including a ferocious slugfest in the 12th
and final round, to capture the WBC welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Despite evidence to the contrary, De La Hoya believed he had won
the fight by a point, clinging to the notion that the defending
champion should receive the benefit of the doubt in a split
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Two judges saw the fight quite differently, though, with Pat
Russell giving Mosley the last six rounds and Lou Filippo scoring
five of the last six for Mosley. Russell (115-113) and Filippo
(116-112) had Mosley winning, while Marty Sammon thought De La Hoya
had won, 115-113. All three judges scored the final round for
Mosley. Still, if De La Hoya had won that round, Russell's score
would have been 114-114 and De La Hoya would have kept the title at
147 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not give it a draw?'' De La Hoya said. ``Why take it away
from me like that? It's not justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see things like this happen, it turns me off. It's
tough to live with what goes on around boxing. I just don't feel I
can continue on like this. He deserves it. He's a good champion. I
have no problem with him winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-win situation. What if I do box Shane Mosley? I
would not get the decision. In my mind, when I didn't get the
knockout, I said forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya had plenty of chances to floor Mosley for the first
time in the challenger's career. Instead, Mosley recovered from
early danger, wore down De La Hoya with his speedy attacks and
clinched the victory with a devastating finish.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting at will with his right hand, Mosley outscored De La
Hoya, 45-18, in punches landed in the 12th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was flat-footed and wasn't much of a boxer in that round,''
Mosley said. ``He didn't bounce and move like I've seen him do.''
</P>
<P>
   In only his third fight since moving up two classes to
welterweight, Mosley impressively weathered De La Hoya's power and
consistently beat him to the punch, especially with quick jabs.
Mosley landed 42 percent of his punches (284) to 36 percent (257)
for De La Hoya. ``I was never really hurt,'' Mosley said. ``I got
hit with good shots, but I never got hurt where I was wobbled. This
was my time. This takes my career to another level. I just had to
make sure I had enough energy to close the show out in the 12th
round.''
</P>
<P>
   A rematch loomed even as Mosley's celebration swirled around the
ring. Mosley had agreed to one before signing the contract to fight
De La Hoya. Arum said he expected the two fighters to meet again in
November if details can be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have to consider Los Angeles; however, Las Vegas would
have to be in the running to bid on this rematch,'' Arum said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
