<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX POUND HERNANDEZ FOR A SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES thruout with update on injury to Hernandez)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez trudged a few feet behind the
mound, allowed a new ball to tumble out of his glove and crouched
down like a catcher. El Duque stared at the grass below his cleats
for about 10 seconds that felt more like 10 minutes. Hernandez
looked uncomfortable. Everyone on the Yankees felt uneasy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Valentin had just smashed a grand slam and the White Sox
already had nine runs in the first inning when Hernandez dropped
the ball, lowered his head and waited for the inevitable. Manager
Joe Torre was fast approaching and the boos were escalating so El
Duque stood, scooped up the ball, handed it to Torre and ended his
brief debacle with a wounded ego and a sprained right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle was not brief for the rest of the Yankees. It
stretched across nine torturous innings, culminating in a 17-4 loss
to the White Sox. On Saturday, the Yankees had rallied from an 8-0
deficit before losing, 10-9, but they had no dramatic rallies on
this gray, gloomy day and were swept in a four-game series at
Yankee Stadium for the first time since the White Sox did it in
July 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say it's embarrassing,'' Torre said, ``but you
sure don't like getting your butt kicked like we have over this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were despondent after the White Sox outscored them
by 42-17 in the series, with Torre referring to this slide as ``a
blow to the organization'' and General Manager Brian Cashman
saying, ``We're playing as bad as we can play.'' The anxiety
increased because El Duque was found to have a sprained elbow after
he underwent X-rays and a magnetic resonance imaging test at Beth
Israel North Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are unsure whether Hernandez , their leading winner,
will make his next start against the White Sox on Friday in
Chicago, and they are hopeful that he does not have to join Roger
Clemens on the 15-day disabled list. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously not an immediate DL situation,'' Cashman said.
``We think he'll make a start. We're not ruling out Friday, but
we're not guaranteeing it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said that doctors prescribed rest for Hernandez and that
he would be re-evaluated this week, but it seems improbable that he
will be able to make his scheduled start. With Clemens sidelined,
the team will monitor Hernandez and decide if he can pitch within a
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would probably allow El Duque to miss a start, but
it would be logical to place him on the disabled list if he had to
miss more than one.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Hernandez, who missed a start in May
because of an upper back injury, has had elbow complications,
adding to an already bleak situation for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Torre said, ``you have to sit back and take it.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have held repeated discussions about acquiring the
Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa or Detroit's Juan Gonzalez, and this
drought could intensify the owner George Steinbrenner's desire to
improve the team. After losing for the sixth time in seven games,
the Yankees (34-29) remained a half game behind the first-place Red
Sox, whom they play in a four-game series starting Monday night in
Boston. But, suddenly, the Blue Jays trail the Yankees by a half
game.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman reiterated that there were more quality position players
available than pitchers and acknowledged that the Yankees' poor
play could make a trade tougher to execute. The Yankees are hanging
on and are fortunate that the other teams in the American League
East have also been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dropping 16 of 28 games, the Yankees have gained a half
game. Still, the standings cannot hide a struggling team that was
down by 9-0 after one inning, by 12-0 after two and by 16-0 after
five. The Yankees had not allowed nine in a first inning since
1979, and the White Sox had not scored nine in a first in 38 years.
Derek Jeter was 16 the last time the Yankees were battered for 17
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it concerns you,'' Paul O'Neill said. ``You don't
want someone to come in and embarrass you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (6-6) looked as if he might have hurt himself on the
first batter of the game. He sprinted to cover first on Ray
Durham's grounder to Tino Martinez and jumped for the base,
buckling as he landed and perhaps hurting his back.
</P>
<P>
   Then the devastation began. After Hernandez walked Valentin,
Frank Thomas laced a booming double to make the score 1-0. El Duque
walked a batter and Paul Konerko singled home a run, prompting an
injury visit from Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching coach. Hernandez
told Stottlemyre that he was fine.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Singleton smashed a two-run double and Carlos Lee
singled in a run to put the Yankees in a 5-0 hole. Hernandez was
not fine. His fastball was limping and his usually impeccable
control was awry. El Duque threw first pitch balls to 6 of 11
batters and went to four three-ball counts, which resulted in three
walks and the grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez tugged on his jersey, adjusted his cap and dug around
the dirt, searching for a comfort zone. He gave up two singles to
the next three batters and later told Torre he first felt pain in
his elbow on the No. 9 batter Mark Johnson's single.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even though Stottlemyre and Jorge Posada both quizzed
Hernandez on how he felt, he continued pitching. Hernandez threw 11
pitches after feeling the pain, walking Durham and surrendering
Valentin's grand slam on a weak 3-2 fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know he's hurt, you don't dare'' let him pitch, Torre
said. ``I'm sorry he went two more hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Hernandez toil for two thirds of an inning shocked some
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like they were getting cheap hits,'' Jeter said.
``It was like a couple of guys on and `Bam!' A couple of guys on
and `Bam!' Before you knew it, it was 9-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you knew it, the Yankees had flopped again. Torre
speculated that teams are bound to get even with the Yankees after
they dominated baseball for three of the last four years. That
trend might be changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've enjoyed ourselves for four years,'' Torre said. ``We're
on our heels and we need to bounce back. We sort of know now what
other clubs felt when they played us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
