<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIVENDI, SEAGRAM BOARDS MEET TO CONSIDER MERGER
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both Vivendi and Seagram met over the weekend to
weigh Vivendi's $33 billion acquisition of Seagram. A decision was
expected as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The final price is still being negotiated, a person close to the
talks said, in part because Vivendi's stock has fallen since the
deal was reported last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   AOL TO REPAIR NETWORK FLAWS
</P>
<P>
   America Online said it would take steps to fix flaws in its
network that allowed hackers to get access to personal information
about some members last week.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN ASSAULT VICTIMS ARE IDENTIFIED
</P>
<P>
   Amateur videos taken in New York during the attacks on dozens of
women after the National Puerto Rican Day Parade on June 11 were
widely disseminated, but usually with the women's faces blurred so
they could not be identified. But on five news programs and in The
New York Post, the women were clearly identifiable, several with
their shirts taken off and others with no clothes at all. The
coverage showed how competition can overtake news organizations in
a 24-hour news cycle and how questionable ethical decisions made by
one outlet can influence others.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS PUSH ONE-STOP SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   Banks and brokerage firms are racing to offer the newest thing
in online financial services: a single place where customers can
find up-to-date information about all of their financial accounts.
Less than a year ago, big financial firms saw this innovation,
known as account aggregation, as a threat to their customers'
privacy and financial security. But now, fearing an onslaught of
competition on the Internet, they are embracing it as a convenience
for customers and a powerful tool for building their own business.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONING A MICROSOFT INITIATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft plans to announce a new initiative this week that
would shift the locus of computing off the desktop and out into a
``cloud'' of large server computers located on the Internet. The
goal is to maintain a central role for Microsoft's software. But an
influential critic, David Gelernter, said the plan misjudged the
computer industry's direction _ that rather than moving to an
increasingly Web-centric model, computing is instead becoming
rapidly decentralized, with the key information distributed among
millions of individual desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   GUIDEPOSTS MAGAZINE TO ACCEPT ADS
</P>
<P>
   Guideposts magazine, founded by Dr. Norman Vincent Peale 55
years ago, has been spinning out stories filled with hope and
inspiration, and it has refused to run any form of advertising. But
that is about to change. Faced with the same problems that are
affecting the rest of the subscription-only magazine industry,
Guideposts has decided to start accepting advertising in January,
albeit from ``wholesome'' sources.
</P>
<P>
   GENOMICS AS THE NEW NEW THING
</P>
<P>
   Soon, perhaps within days, researchers expect to announce
completion of the decade-long project to map the human genome.
Stand by for the New Genomics to become the next big thing in the
New Economy. Aided by extensive computer processing power, the
genome researchers have been engaged in what is essentially a giant
software project. Sequencing the human genome involves sifting
through the 3 billion units of DNA at the heart of every human cell
to identify the 80,000 or so genes that define all inheritable
physical and behavioral traits.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA SAID TO REJECT ING OFFER
</P>
<P>
   ING Groep, based in the Netherlands, said Aetna had rejected its
offer to buy Aetna's financial-services and international units
because it was not high enough. ING also confirmed that Aetna was
talking with other companies about buying those divisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
