<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LITTLE MAN' SHAQ IS JUST ENJOYING LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For a guy averaging more than 37 points and 17
rebounds during the final round of the NBA tournament, causing
havoc usually reserved for yellow-iron construction equipment, it
is remarkable that the transcendent moment for Shaquille O'Neal
came when he simply stood.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who else can stand like a 7-foot-1, 315-pound
panther?
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Game 4, end of regulation, Pacers' ball, chance to
win a magnificent game with one shot. The smallest, quickest man on
the court, Indiana's 5-11 Travis Best, is, thanks to a defensive
switch, isolated on the big man, who is crippled by five fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was,'' said Best later, ``pretty happy about that matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   A good little man in basketball always thinks he can get a shot
off against a lumbering big man. Quick feet and a quick release are
always the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Except against the Lakers center.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reacting, Best found himself thinking _ the worst
thing to do with the clock running down and the defender, hands up,
looming large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could go to the hole on him,'' Best said. ``But at
the same time, I was below the free throw line, and I felt if I did
get by him, he still had enough space to catch up and make a play
on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable going to the hole unless I really
had him off-balance. I was able to get him off-balance, acting like
I was going to the hole, and I raised up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; rr &LR; ``The shot was short. I don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was fear, and it became the turning point in the
series. Failing to drive because O'Neal- is almost as agile as he
is big, Best's tepid, fallaway 15-foot jumper over outstretched,
outsized mitts had no chance. It forced the overtime where the
Lakers won, 120-118, giving them the lone victory in the three
matches in Indianapolis, and, for all intents, the 3-2 lead they
carry into the sixth game Monday night in Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the search for meaning for the much-abused sports lingo,
``the man,'' O'Neal helped the project along with that moment. When
one alters a game, and probably a series, merely by standing, he is
... well, you know.
</P>
<P>
   To call him the big man states the obvious. However, call him
the little man, and you're on your way to some serious
ingratiation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Best matchup was a big man's worst nightmare,
O'Neal scoffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I'm a little man trapped in a big man's body.
All big guys want to be little guards.''
</P>
<P>
   The little man in O'Neal is not an abstraction, but just one of
a number of virtuous aspects emerging in this series about the
league's Most Valuable Player. Along with the overwhelming play
that finally has him linked properly in the same sentence with Wilt
Chamberlain, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Bill Russell, it is O'Neal's
demeanor and personality that have become nearly as noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you whose televised exposure to O'Neal has been his
mumbling, cliched responses to group-interview questions, well,
that's a darn shame. Away from that stilted forum, yet sometimes
even within it, O'Neal is offering up a refreshingly adolescent
exuberance about his life and creations. As successful as was Tom
Hanks in ``Big,'' the movie blew it by not casting O'Neal as the
full-grown child.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for Seattle fans to appreciate what is to them merely
a massive, glowering obstacle to a return to NBA prominence. So
let's put it this way:
</P>
<P>
   If Ken Griffey Jr. had as much fun being Junior that O'Neal has
being Shaq, he not only wouldn't be hitting .230 in Cincinnati, he
wouldn't be in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, O'Neal's recent emotional growth has been almost as
impressive as his physical spurt a decade earlier. He and the
Lakers couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference the other day in Naptown, O'Neal
stopped questioners before they began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you all should try one of these muffins, because these
muffins is real good,'' he said. Then he smiled, flashing the
muffin smashed against his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Just the kind of thing one would expect from a dopey kid brother
at the breakfast table _ not the somber inheritor of the
Chamberlain-Kareem legacy.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, after he had written a flattering column about
O'Neal as MVP, ex-P-I sportswriter Bill Plaschke, now of the Los
Angeles Times, was greeted at Lakers practice by the big man and
asked if he really meant what he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, said Plaschke, whereupon he was hugged by O'Neal, who
proceeded to hop with the startled writer for several seconds. Even
though afterward he claimed to be too sore to write, Plaschke
counted the moment unique in his experiences with superstar
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of painful embraces, that is what opponents often do to
O'Neal in the absence of any plausible alternative defense. Even as
recently as last season, Hack-a-Shaq sometimes fueled a reckless
rage in him, as did the hard fouls that went uncalled by referees
simply because of his extraordinary physical advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Now, O'Neal barely flinches, and almost never complains. No
longer can teams count on him becoming flustered and distracted,
despite the fact that the annoying clobberings force him to expose
to the world his lone vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the tactic ``The Big Homage'' to his game, he practices
free throws relentlessly and betrays no shame at his persistent
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I shot 80 percent,'' O'Neal mused the other day, ``I
wouldn't even bother talking to you guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But he smiled (muffin-free, this time) and everyone laughed.
</P>
<P>
   That is what a lot of people do around him these days, as long
as they aren't responsible for keeping him off the low blocks or
snatching a rebound from him.
</P>
<P>
   He is the rare modern sports star who is appreciative of his
station in life. Instead of abusing it, he chooses to savor. As
Charles Barkley understood best and most splendidly before him, it
is a good thing. Mumbles notwithstanding, O'Neal is learning to
share it.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough he will be a champion, be it Monday or Wednesday.
Then he will be villainized even more than he already had been in
the minds of basketball fans everywhere but Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK, too. As Chamberlain was once told, nobody loves
Goliath. Basketball fans pay huge money for the privilege of
heckling him, and he is paid huge money to take it.
</P>
<P>
   But as the NBA Finals close out, it might be fun to do what
Travis Best did and stop to consider for a moment the large man
ahead (hey, you don't have to get a shot off).
</P>
<P>
   Consider that in the body of the giant warrior, there is a
little man dying to get out _ the quick guard, the kid brother, the
class clown, the good teammate, the solid citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, a man at peace.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
