<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7810 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-     06-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-730(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S PLAN WILL OFFER VOLUNTARY RETIREMENT ACCOUNTS TO SOME
TAXPAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ky.) 
(CLARIFIES that investments must be made through account managers
in 7th graf)  By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore plans in a speech on Tuesday
to propose a $200 billion program to help low- and middle-income
taxpayers build retirement accounts separate from what they will
receive from Social Security, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   As described by Gore aides, the program would work the way
401(k) savings plans work, but instead of employer contributions,
the federal government would make contributions in the form of tax
credits, providing in some cases up to a 3-to-1 match.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``retirement savings plus,'' the plan would offer tax
relief for couples with combined annual incomes of up to $100,000,
or individuals making up to $50,000. Gore's program would provide
the greatest benefit for couples with incomes of less than $30,000.
The program would cost the government $200 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary program, designed to compete with Gov. George W.
Bush's proposal for individuals to invest an unspecified portion of
their Social Security payroll tax in the stock market, would create
a fund for each participant that could expand by a maximum of
$2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   A married couple making up to $30,000 a year could contribute up
to $500 annually. They would then receive a refundable tax credit
of $1,500, bringing their account to $2,000. A couple making
$100,000 could contribute $1,500 to their account and earn a tax
credit of $500.
</P>
<P>
   Like IRAs and 401(k) plans, contributions to the accounts would
be tax deducible, accounts would grow tax-free and withdrawals
would be taxed. Private financial institutions would manage the
accounts. According to Gore aides, participation in the program
over 35 years of work would yield an individual about $200,000 for
retirement over and above Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan does two things that Gore had earlier criticized in
the plan offered by his Republican rival. One, it allows people to
invest taxpayer money in the stock market through the account
managers. Two, it substantially increases the amount of the federal
budget surplus that Gore would devote to tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has been fiercely critical of Bush for
devoting 1.3 trillion dollars of the surplus to an across-the-board
income tax cut over 10 years. But now, with this new savings plan,
Gore's total of targeted tax cuts clocks in at $500 billion over 10
years, twice what he had proposed before, and half of Bush's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers, in interviews Sunday, said that the Gore plan is
a hedge against what they see as the risky alternative that Bush is
proposing. They said financial institutions would be limited to
offering investment options based on broad-based mutual funds for
equities, bonds and government securities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore intends to lay out the plan in a speech on Tuesday in
Lexington, Ky. The speech comes at the beginning of the second week
of his three-week ``progress and prosperity tour'' (sometimes
called the ``prosperity and progress tour'' by Gore) in which he is
traveling to key battleground states to try to get credit for the
nation's booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement plan is a vivid example of how Gore is trying to
take advantage of the burgeoning federal budget surplus by spending
it on targeted groups of voters whom he needs to win over in
November _ in this case, low-income and middle-income working
families, the core Democratic base that polls have indicated are
slipping from Gore's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Gore's proposal revealed a weakening of his
stance against putting taxpayer money in the financial markets and
would thus contribute to an overall impression of Gore as someone
without reliable core values.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week the vice president will flip flop flip by coming out
for the use of tax money to be invested in the market to help
people retire,'' said Ari Fleischer, Bush's campaign spokesman.
``It's his third position in six months on the soundness of using
tax money to invest in markets to secure people's retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer pointed to the Clinton administration's now abandoned
position laid out in this year's budget proposal to allow
government-controlled investments in the markets, and then to a
Gore speech in May when he criticized Bush's plan to allow people
to invest a portion of their payroll taxes in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing this to blunt Governor Bush's approach to allow
people to invest in the markets to help them retire with more
money,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer was talking about Gore's retirement plan, but he was
not the only one suggesting Sunday that Gore was perhaps going
through multiple reinventions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's new campaign chairman, William Daley, the commerce
secretary, made the rounds of the television talk shows Sunday and
was asked repeatedly about the vice president's continually
evolving personas.
</P>
<P>
   As Tim Russert posed the question on the NBC program ``Meet The
Press'': ``Fairly or unfairly, there's a perception that Al Gore
has changed positions on abortion, on gun control, Elian Gonzalez,
wearing earth tones, wearing sports shirts, wearing coats and ties,
changing campaign chairmen, moving from Washington to Nashville,
suddenly in favor of a $500 billion tax cut _ that Gore has no
center, that he flips and panders as a politician. Is that a
problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Daley replied, ``There's a problem because those are all
misconceptions that have been developed by either the opposition or
by media who aren't really following this day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The fact of the matter is, Al Gore has been
consistent about working for the average man and woman out there
and trying to address their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But organized labor has been tepid lately toward Gore, both for
his support for a bill to make normal trade relations permanent
with China and for naming Daley as his chairman to replace the
ailing Tony Coelho. Daley led the administration's fight on Capitol
Hill to pass the trade bill, which labor vehemently opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said Sunday that he had talked with several labor leaders
over the last few days, including John Sweeney, president of the
AFL-CIO, who met with Gore on Friday to complain about the Daley
appointment. Daley suggested his talks with labor leaders had been
fruitful and said he expected to meet with Sweeney on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other Gore aides spent the day briefing reporters on the
retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   They said that while the chief goal of the plan would be to
provide a cushion for retirement nest eggs, participants could
withdraw their savings at any time without penalty for three
specific purposes: to cover catastrophic health expenses, to help
buy a first home, or to pay for a child's college education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the plan would encourage the rate of personal
savings, which has plunged to more than half the previous total
over the last decade. And they said that at a rate of return of 5.3
percent, an account for an individual could grow to $202,000 over
35 years.
</P>
<P>
   They also suggested that the program would be simplified by
having the Internal Revenue Service create a mechanism to deposit
people's tax credit and a share of their tax refunds directly into
the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus,'' according to briefing paper prepared by the Gore
campaign, ``with a simple check-off on your tax return, workers
could see up to $2,000 each deposited in the `retirement savings
plus' each year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore plan is based on the universal savings accounts
proposed in the 1999 State of the Union address by President
Clinton, a complex proposal that never made it through Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
