<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-COMMUTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURIST RAIL OWNERS PROPOSE COMMUTER RAIL IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Owners of the Branson Scenic Railway have
expressed interest in starting and operating commuter rail service
in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which is still very preliminary, the rail
service would reach from Grandview to Union Station and then to
Olathe, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel pretty confident about our proposal,'' said Saul Kass,
one of the owners of the Branson tourist railroad. ``The key thing
now is to know whether we will get enough riders to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal must overcome serious challenges.
</P>
<P>
   First, the railroad needs a ridership survey to judge local
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the railroad has yet to discuss its plans with the
railroads that own the tracks a commuter line would share with
freight traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of other railroads say they are open to the idea, but
they are concerned about the capacity of their tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to comment without having seen anything,'' said
Steve Forsberg, general director of public affairs for Burlington
Northern Santa Fe Railroad, which owns the tracks that parallel
Interstate 35 in Johnson County, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That particular line is the line that is already extremely
crowded with freight traffic,'' Forsberg said. ``Besides, Johnson
County is already talking to us about using it for their commuter
rail service.''
</P>
<P>
   An official with Kansas City Southern Railway said that although
the company was aware of the interest in commuter rail, there had
not been a formal presentation. The railroad owns the tracks that
run from about Grandview north to the Missouri River, along
Interstate 435.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saul mentioned this to me, in vague terms in passing,'' said
Warren Erdman, vice president of corporate affairs for Kansas City
Southern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that we certainly would be open-minded to his
ideas, but it takes time to work out the capacity problems,''
Erdman said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge might be getting commuter rail service
started and operating it using only private funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Carnaggio, director of engineering for the Federal Transit
Administration, said it was rare for someone to start commuter rail
service using only private funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually takes a sizable investment,'' Carnaggio said. ``To
be honest with you, it is very difficult to get your return on
investment. I would say what they are proposing is very unusual and
somewhat ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg put it bluntly: ``Commuter rail just doesn't make
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Kass disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 1993, Branson Scenic Railway has taken tourists on
40-mile excursions out of Branson. Last year the railroad carried
more than 90,000 passengers, and it expects to carry more than
100,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kass said the company hoped to translate its success into a
commuter line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what it takes to run a profitable system.''
</P>
<P>
   Under their commuter rail proposal, Branson Scenic Railway would
form a new company. The new company, said Tom Johnson, president of
the Branson Railway, would lease several engines and buy used
passenger cars and refurbish them.
</P>
<P>
   Kass said they faced a tight deadline. They have to get the
passenger cars now, before they are sold to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars we originally wanted to buy have been sold,'' Kass
said. ``We know of eight other cars, and we can purchase them for a
good price. But we need to make the decision soon, or Kansas City
can just forget about commuter rail.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Kass said, the new company would spend less than $1.5
million in start-up costs to get commuter rail service in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, about $30 million, most of it from federal money,
has been allocated for Johnson County's commuter rail project.
</P>
<P>
   Kass' company, however, would rely on the railroads that own the
tracks to make improvements to accommodate commuter service. These
costs would be recouped through long-term lease arrangements with
the new commuter rail service.
</P>
<P>
   Kass and Johnson said the lease payments would be paid through
passenger fares.
</P>
<P>
   They said they did not know how much fares would be but said
costs would be comparable to what people paid for parking, gas and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The railroads are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it stands now, the homework has not been done,'' Erdman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they developed a meaningful, serious proposal, we would
take a look at what it would take to improve the capacity to ensure
the safety on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Erdman said, Kansas City Southern probably would prefer a
more regional look into commuter rail for the Kansas City area, one
that would take into consideration how other public transit modes
would work together.
</P>
<P>
   Mell Henderson, director of transportation for the Mid-America
Regional Council, said the metropolitan planning agency was
embarking on a regional commuter rail study that would identify
which rail corridors held potential for passenger service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is more complicated than just saying, `There are
rails out there; let's go put commuter rail on them,' &UR; '' Henderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Henderson said, Kass and Johnson's proposed commute rail
project was consistent with ideas others had expressed the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not coming completely out of the blue,'' Henderson
said. ``But there are other questions that need to be looked at and
get answered before moving forward on what they are suggesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg said Burlington Northern Santa Fe might not be
interested in working with the owners of the Branson Scenic Railway
without first consulting with Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are in the position where we are trying to
invite a bidding war of any kind,'' Forsberg said. ``Johnson
County's willingness to look at this will have a lot of impact on
our view as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County is doing preliminary engineering on the I-35
commuter rail project. That work is expected to give the county a
true look at the potential of the project.
</P>
<P>
   If feasible, those commuter trains would likely start running in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Kass says his trains could be running as early as the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Ferguson, commuter rail project director for Johnson
County Transit, said he did not see this as a competition to be the
first provider of commuter rail service. He said that if Kass was
successful, the county probably would drop its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not parochial here,'' Ferguson said. ``If somebody has
a better idea, we will stop and look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Johnson County will continue with its commuter rail
project, Ferguson said. The county would probably hire a firm to
operate its system.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Kass and Johnson do not proceed with their own plans,
Ferguson said, Johnson County probably would see whether they had
interest in operating Johnson County's commuter rail service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they have been very successful with Branson Scenic
Railway, and obviously they know how to operate a passenger
train,'' Ferguson said. ``They are certainly positioning themselves
to be a player in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
