<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CHEF-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-18 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHEF-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: MYSTERY ALLURE OF `IRON CHEF' ONLY ADDS TO
EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to understand how the premiere of ``Survivor'' on CBS
last month drew 16 million viewers and became one of the network's
greatest successes. The show, about a group of strangers pitted
against one another on an island in the South China Sea while
television cameras looked on, was almost impossible to avoid, with
a TV Guide cover, articles in numerous newspapers and a barrage of
on-air promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Far more unusual, however, has been the success of an obscure
Japanese cooking show called ``Iron Chef,'' which is emerging as
the newest cult hit on television. Since its introduction on the
Food Network last summer, it has become that cable channel's
second-highest-rated show after ``Emeril Live!''
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic illustration of what network people call
``appointment viewing'': shows people actually make plans to watch,
instead of watching by chance or because they're too lazy to change
channels. But it's also an example of something new: the way cable
television, the Internet and old-fashioned word of mouth can
combine to propel quirky phenomena into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Even Julia Child has expressed her delight with the show (in the
current issue of Gourmet). But the appeal of ``Iron Chef'' extends
well beyond food enthusiasts. Julie Yaeger, a 31-year-old vice
president for publicity at Miramax (who says she is ``into the
ordering in and eating out phase'' of life), for example, was
channel-surfing when she was stopped by the ``Iron Chef.'' That was
last September. Since then, she and her boyfriend, the actor Paul
Rudd, and a group of friends frequently get together Friday nights
to watch the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iron Chef'' is a rococo blend of highbrow and low, of culinary
artistry and wrestling-match vulgarity, of fantasy and practicality
(though there are no recipes). What captures and holds viewers like
Yaeger is the show's combination of kitsch and craft and the way it
cloaks earnest competition and serious cooking in the goofiest
trappings, including English dubbing that seems modeled on the
exclamatory rhythms of kung-fu movie translations.
</P>
<P>
   The show combines Japanese formalism with American-style
showmanship to create a hybrid that is the equivalent of a Pokemon
for grown-ups. There is, clearly, a universal appeal in these timed
contests between supremely skilled artisans who chop flesh and
fruit with speed and ferocity, and with very big knives.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, a chef challenger comes to the show to try to defeat
one of the regulars, a Cooking Iron Man. (On Sunday, in a special
edition taped in New York, Bobby Flay, chef of Mesa Grill and Bolo
_ and a Food Network star himself _ will be the challenger.)
Moments before the cooking contest begins, each chef is given a
single ``theme ingredient,'' which must be the centerpiece of every
course in a multicourse meal. The ingredients can be as pedestrian
as a potato, as exotic as bird's nest and oat yam.
</P>
<P>
   The cooks, with a supporting cast of assistants, have one hour
to finish. Dishes are prepared in a real-time frenzy. Beautiful and
sometimes bizarre creations (sturgeon-head ice cream and frog-fish
creme brulee) emerge from this on-the-spot creation of a menu. A
panel of four judges tastes, comments and declares the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The show always opens with a quotation from Brillat-Savarin, the
18th-century French gourmet and philosopher, which appears on the
screen: ``Tell me what you eat, and I'll tell you what you are.''
Then a narrator briefly recounts the tale of Takeshi Kaga, a
wealthy man with a fantasy ``to encounter new and original
cuisines, which could be called true artistic creations.''
</P>
<P>
   We see the slender Kaga, who dresses like Liberace, sampling
food and surveying the scene. The opening ritual continues as Kaga
chooses a yellow pepper from a pile of peppers, bites into it and
smiles mysteriously. ``Iron Chef'' aficionados debate whether his
smile is ironic or not. Is it a smile or, in fact, a smirk?
</P>
<P>
   The camera pans across the Kitchen Stadium, a studio with
red-draped backdrops and torch-lit runways. Portentous music
throbs, as the four Iron Chefs come rising out of the stage like
fountains in front of a Las Vegas hotel. The narrator introduces
the challenger chefs and video clips of their restaurants, shot in
the homespun style of a local commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Kaga unveils the ingredient of the week, sounds the Gong of
Fate, and the culinary samurai prepare to do battle. The
commentators, former Japanese sports announcers, have transported
the play-by-play patter of the sports arena to the kitchen. ``Look
at this, check it out,'' one of them pants during one session
featuring pork bellies.
</P>
<P>
   Though challengers do receive free advertisements for their
restaurants, their real reward is honor. There is no cash prize.
The show's resident Iron Chefs aren't unseated, even if they're
defeated. So it doesn't diminish the fun to discover that host Kaga
is an actor (who has played Jean Valjean in ``Les Miserables'' and
Jesus in ``Jesus Christ Superstar''), and that chefs are informed
in advance of possible ingredients that may be selected for the
battle. The show's purity transcends its fakery.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
