<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CHEF-REVIEW-2NDTAK     06-18 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHEF-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: transcends its fakery. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From 1993 through 1999 ``Iron Chef'' was one of Japan's most
popular shows. It became an underground favorite in Los Angeles and
San Francisco three years ago, when local cable stations broadcast
it during Japanese-language programming blocks. Web sites
proliferated, in English and Japanese. Food Network bought ``Iron
Chef,'' which its producer, Fuji Television Network, had translated
into English, but wasn't prepared for the response.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first took a look at the show, I was immediately
captured by the humor, and my culinary staff was transfixed as well
by the food information,'' says Eileen Opatut, the network's head
of programming, who is nevertheless astonished by the show's
popularity. Nielsen Media Research reports that about 222,000
people watched each ``Iron Chef'' episode in May, more than the
131,000 viewers seven months earlier. These numbers are tiny by
network standards but impressive in the world of cable, which
reaches many fewer homes and operates with much smaller programming
and marketing budgets.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to explain why some shows cross the line.
``Antiques Road Show'' _ which tours the country and features
experts who appraise viewers' antiques _ has become the top-rated
program on PBS, with a regular audience of almost 14 million fans.
``The Crocodile Hunter'' on Animal Planet is about to spawn its own
toy line. ``Iron Chef'' isn't yet in that league: no dolls wearing
chef's hats are due any time soon. Even so, its success is
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji Television Network, which produced the original 290
episodes of ``Iron Chef,'' spared no expense on food ingredients.
The company spent $7.7 million on exotica like matsutake _ a
Japanese mushroom that cost around $300 an ounce _ and electric eel
and lobster (used by one chef to flavor an asparagus dish, which
required the lobster to be discarded after its essence was
extracted).
</P>
<P>
   ``The show seems associated with the years of the economic
bubble, and the absurd extravagances of the late '80s,'' said
Jordan Sand, who teaches Japanese history and culture at Georgetown
University and who discovered ``Iron Chef'' when he was living in
Japan in 1994. ``Since it ran in the post-bubble years, it must be
parodic. It was more funny because the dream was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not ``Iron Chef'' signaled a cultural response to
economic stimuli, the elaborate machinations of the chefs
undoubtedly harken to a particularly Japanese kind of food
fetishism. ``Iron Chef'' follows the tradition of Ajikko, the main
character of a Japanese cartoon series shown in the 1980s about a
boy who traveled around the country challenging chefs to culinary
battles. And remember ``Tampopo,'' the 1987 Japanese comedy, in
which all of life boiled down to the perfect bowl of noodles?
</P>
<P>
   In the United States the word has spread in many ways. Paul
Witcover's girlfriend forced him to watch the show the first time
and then he was hooked. They've broken up, but each remains
faithful to ``Iron Chef.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the cooks, the effort and the passion they put into
their work; that cannot be faked,'' said Witcover, 41, who writes
science fiction. ``Did you see the first woman chef?'' he asked.
``She slices her hand open and the blood is flowing. There are no
doctors on hand so, they take masking tape and tape her hand, and
she continues to cook. The samurai aspect rose to the core with
this woman who wounds herself and battles on.''
</P>
<P>
   Witcover introduced the show to Dan Von Behren, who works for a
computer software company. ``Now I have hundreds of people who can
pontificate about the beauty of the `Iron Chef,''' he said. On
Thanksgiving he and three friends, from different cities, convened
to have their own ``Iron Chef'' cook-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch NYPD Blue,'' Behren said. ``I watch West Wing. I love
the Simpsons.'' Still, what attracts him to ``Iron Chef'' is a bit
of a mystery to him. ``I don't know how to describe it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how to cook, or wanting to cook, or being a grown-up, is
not a prerequisite. Sam Tobis, a 10-year-old fifth-grader in
Manhattan, took a look at the show after overhearing friends of his
parents talking about it. He was mesmerized by the sight of a chef
frying the scales of sea bass and then serving them with chocolate
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the skill mixed with the rarity of everything that's
going on,'' he said, offering a persuasive argument for the show's
attraction. ``It's so 21st century. Everything is weird and
different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
