<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-BACKERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OZ INVESTOR PLANS TO TRIPLE HIS STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Michigan-based marketing company and its
chairman own 26 percent of the Oz Entertainment Co., and the
executive plans to almost triple his investment in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   As Oz Entertainment proposes to clean up environmental
contamination at the Sunflower Army Ammunition Plant in Johnson
County, Kan., and build an $860.6 million theme park resort there,
public interest in the company's investors has swelled.
</P>
<P>
   Oz Chairman Robert Kory is often asked about whose money is
behind Oz.
</P>
<P>
   In large part the answer is 75-year-old Steve Toth Jr. and his
company.
</P>
<P>
   Toth owns 83 percent of VSI Holdings, a marketing company near
Detroit that hopes to tap Oz's potential for Internet education and
entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   VSI is publicly traded and has 390 shareholders of record. The
stock closed Friday at 2 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, VSI Holdings and Toth's family trust have invested
$12.4 million in Oz and its investment arm, K.C. Investors LP. Of
that, $7.9 million came from the Toth family.
</P>
<P>
   The total investment gives Toth and VSI a 26 percent stake in Oz
and makes them Oz's largest investor.
</P>
<P>
   VSI representatives hold two of five seats on the Oz
Entertainment Co.'s board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the game,'' Toth said. ``That's not a huge amount (of
money), but it's still a lot to put in a good-faith venture, which
is what we've done with the state. It's very important it moves
along in the direction it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Toth, through his family trust, plans to invest $15 million to
$20 million more to help Oz close on the Sunflower land near De
Soto. Such expenses include paying closing costs and about $11.5
million to buy insurance to guarantee the Sunflower cleanup, said
Tom Marquis, VSI's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Toth's share of the company will grow with the investment, but
not enough to control Oz, Kory and Marquis said.
</P>
<P>
   Kory and VSI expect to raise an additional $70 million when Oz
closes the land deal, Marquis said.
</P>
<P>
   That round of fund raising will dilute Toth's share of the
company, Marquis and Kory said.
</P>
<P>
   VSI enjoys a strategic partnership with Oz: VSI invests in Oz
and gets the contracts for marketing the theme park's opening and
creating the 3-D animatronic characters for the theme park, said Jo
Bourjaily, who handles new business development for VSI.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the investment, VSI executives meet regularly with
Kory and often send representatives to Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching carefully what happens in Kansas,'' Bourjaily
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oz does not have key approvals for its project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board doesn't feel this is any more at risk than any
investment we've made,'' Marquis said. ``To the contrary, we feel
it probably will have a higher payoff than other investments.''
</P>
<P>
   LaVern Krueger, an associate professor at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City's Bloch School of Business and Public
Administration, said: ``This is a vehicle put together for the Toth
interests. It's not the normal corporate business you'd think of.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger reviewed VSI's public financial filings at the request
of The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gamble,'' Krueger said. ``But he's not really
answerable to (many) stockholders for that gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   An Oz critic said VSI's involvement did not improve his opinion
of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious where Oz stands on the totem pole of investors
when it has to find unrelated, unknown, small-company financing and
then turn around and brag about it like it's a big deal,'' said
Bill Sheldon, president of Taxpayers Opposed To Oz. ``This further
brings in unknown people and unknown circumstances, which the
public and the government is supposed to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Oz and public officials call the project a public-private
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Oz would clean up the Sunflower site in exchange for acquiring
the land, and the state would issue bonds to finance part of the
construction cost for the theme park.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds would be repaid with sales tax revenue generated by
the park. The state would not be responsible for repaying the bonds
if the venture failed.
</P>
<P>
   Oz also seeks property tax breaks for the site.
</P>
<P>
   Toth's marketing company began in the early 1960s as Visual
Services Inc. Visual Services went public in 1997 by merging with a
publicly traded company called the Banker's Note, operated by
Toth's nephew. The Banker's Note was later spun off.
</P>
<P>
   The result was VSI Holdings, a 1,200-employee company that had
about $145 million in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   VSI does an array of marketing work, such as conducting
high-tech training for sales people, helping to launch new products
and developing e-commerce Web sites. About 90 percent of VSI's
marketing revenue comes from the automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
   An entertainment arm of VSI creates 3-D animatronic, or
robotlike, characters for theme parks, including Universal Studios.
It also uses the technology for education, such as a
drunken-driving simulator sent to high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kory and Toth said VSI's missions dovetailed with the Oz plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a company that understands marketing and event
marketing that's necessary for a theme park launch and understands
the theme park industry is a unique combination of talent,'' said
Kory. ``And they have a passion for the Web and a serious
understanding of the future of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Oz executives said the theme park would be digitally networked
to draw upon Internet possibilities _ such as a virtual park,
interactive games and other entertainment spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a key reason for us to be involved in Oz,'' Toth said.
</P>
<P>
   Toth's company also is creating a Web site development business
with Oz.
</P>
<P>
   VSI is about to invest $200,000 to $250,000 in e-City Studios, a
division of Oz that creates Web sites for businesses other than Oz,
Marquis said.
</P>
<P>
   E-City Studios would become a separate entity, and VSI would own
70 percent, Marquis said. VSI expects e-City Studios to bill $5
million to $6 million in work the first year.
</P>
<P>
   While VSI has dabbled in Web development, it has not been a key
company business, Marquis said. The partnership with Oz's e-City
Studios allows VSI to expand and gives clients a new respect for
the company's Web abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Other business opportunities down the road include a possible
training center on the Sunflower land, Toth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to dream a little bit, this is just the beginning
of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
