<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODYKOONTZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A UNIVERSE OF OFFBEAT TELEVISION, `IRON CHEF` STANDS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's going to be anything more than just a curiosity for
late-night, tipsy channel surfers, a niche cable network needs an
offbeat hit.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a concept that works itself all the way to the
big screen - remember the Sci-Fi Channel's ``Mystery Science
Theater 3000`?
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes it's a bunch of Japanese guys running around
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Which is one way of describing ``Iron Chef,'' the Food Network's
bizarre Japanese import that combines the hilarity of badly dubbed
dialogue with the silliness of competitive cooking.
</P>
<P>
   `Good, solid, goofy fun` is another, one that Eileen Opatut,
senior vice president for programming for the Food Network, likes
to use.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither description quite gets it done. To its fans, the
show is so much ... more. What makes it so oddly addictive is hard
to describe to anyone who hasn't seen it.
</P>
<P>
   `You can imagine what it was like presenting it to my senior
managers,` Opatut says.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a universe of hundreds of TV channels, ``Iron Chef'' is
unique. And it'd better be.
</P>
<P>
   `I think every cable channel, just because of the inherent level
of competition ... needs something that stands out, that sets it
out from the rest of the pack,` Opatut says.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Iron Chef,'' the Food Network certainly has that.
</P>
<P>
   The production comes to the United States next Sunday for a
one-time competition, called, in typical ``Iron Chef'' hyperbole,
`New York Battle.` It's fun, but don't be fooled; the regular show
is better.
</P>
<P>
   Each episode begins with a professional chef challenging one of
the `Iron Chefs,` four guys decked out in loud costumes that make
them look as if they got lost on the way to Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   Once the competitors are set, the secret ingredient is revealed,
rising from the floor in a swirl of dry ice, and the two chefs have
one hour to put together a multicourse meal based on it. (The
ingredients range from the sublime - crabs, say - to the
ridiculous. Unless you're a big ostrich egg fan.)
</P>
<P>
   For much of the next hour, we watch the chefs perform all sorts
of culinary wizardry, accompanied by oddly dubbed play-by-play and
color commentary so passionately over the top it makes John Madden
sound like Stephen Wright in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   When time runs out, a panel of judges puts the food's taste to
the test, gobbling it down and describing each dish in the glowing
terms you usually hear only when the white-haired lady in front of
you in the grocery store line talks about her new grandson. Mind
you, these are invariably dishes so authentic - which is to say,
repulsive to American palates - that most of us couldn't imagine
putting them anywhere near our mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the winner is announced; if you bet on the ``Iron Chef''
every time, you'd never go broke.
</P>
<P>
   All this takes place in Kitchen Stadium, in front of a
hooting-and-hollering throng that would do any self-respecting
soccer hooligan proud.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner gets? Nothing, really.
</P>
<P>
   `They're fighting for honor and stature,` Opatut says. `You're
fighting for the valor and the glory of it.... You're not just
winning a brand new car.`
</P>
<P>
   Which is why ``Iron Chef'' is likely to remain what it is: a fun
Japanese import. It simply wouldn't work remade as an American
show, `New York Battle` notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   `I think we might just ruin it,` Opatut says.
</P>
<P>
   Why mess with success? ``Iron Chef'' bounces between being the
second- and third-highest-rated show on the Food Network (nothing
beats Emeril Lagasse - just ask him).
</P>
<P>
   `Who would know that a cooking show, a cooking competition that
looks more like Gladiators than it does a PBS cooking show, would
end up being a hit,` Opatut says.
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense, however. In a weird way, watching ``Iron Chef'' is
no different from watching a football game: It allows you a finite
amount of time to get caught up in something that is, in the big
scheme of things, completely unimportant. In other words, it's a
nice break from everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   `At the end of it, it's not going to decide the future of the
planet,` Opatut says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's not. But for an hour, it sure is fun to pretend
it will. &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz(at)ArizonaRepublic.com
</P>
<P>
   or (602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
