<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7940 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-USOPEN-LADN     06-18 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER IS UNBEATABLE AT PEBBLE BEACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH - Hagen, Hogan, Nicklaus ... and Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods strode the famed fairways of Pebble Beach Golf Links
into history Sunday, tying the U.S. Open record of 272 with a
final-round 67 that earned him a record 15-stroke victory in the
100th national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Woods missed just four of 14 fairways, hit 15 greens in
regulation and rolled in five birdies in a bogeyless round that
left him 4-under par for the day and 12 under for a tournament in
which no other player came within three strokes of par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played beautifully all day and it was just one of those
great weeks,'' Woods said. ``To play as solidly as I did all week,
it's just hard to put into words and describe the emotions that are
going through me - especially coming up 18. It was just
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Ernie Els and Miguel Angel Jimenez shared second
place, Jimenez closing with a 71 and Els a 72 to finish tied at
3-over-par 287. But Woods' biggest rival on Sunday was history.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped to the first tee with a 10-stroke lead over Els,
Jimenez, Jose Maria Olazabel and Padraig Harrington and never gave
them or anyone else a hint of a chance, winning by the greatest
margin in the history of major championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome to watch,'' said Els, who played in the final
pairing with Woods and was at a loss to describe the quality of
Woods' round. ``Just a dominating performance. That's also an
understatement - whatever I say is going to be an understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominating was just one of the adjectives Woods' beleaguered
opposition used to describe the play of a man who joined an
Open-record list that includes such golf legends as Walter Hagen,
Ben Hogan and Jack Nicklaus,
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty phenomenal,'' said John Huston, the PGA Tour 72-
hole record-holder who finished fourth at 288 after a final-round
70. ``He's certainly out there in a league of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing a different game from the rest of us,'' said
Northern Ireland's Darren Clarke, who defeated Woods in the WGC
match play championship but finished 39 strokes behind him at the
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, twice a PGA Player of the Year in the 1990s, opted
for the historical reflection:
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt for the longest time that someone was going to
come along who could drive the ball 300 yards and putt like (Ben)
Crenshaw,'' said the 43-year-old Price. ``Well, this guy drives the
ball better than anyone I've ever seen and putts better than
Crenshaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting, leading to 20 birdies - second-best ever by an Open
champion - carried Woods this week. But he also excelled at the
shots that set up his putts - ranking first in greens in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   What little trouble he faced Sunday he escaped with a poise and
deftness that might have seemed beyond his years but for the fact
Woods is now - at age 24 - three-quarters of the way toward a
career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   He won the Masters by a record 12 strokes in 1997, added a PGA
Championship last summer and can complete the slam next month by
winning the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won three - three different ones!'' said Els, 30, who has
won two U.S. Opens. ``Man, that's unbelievable. That's what you
want. You want those four. That's my goal ... but with Tiger Woods
to contend with, I've got a pretty tough job ahead of me for the
next 10 years at least.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the young guys,'' said Price. ``Basically
I've had my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods had the latest of his four stellar Open days Sunday and
was flawless early. He hit his first three fairways and greens,
narrowly missing birdie putts on each hole. He parred from fairway
rough on No. 4, then showed his perseverance on the 513-yard, par-5
sixth, saving par with a six-foot putt after hitting out of rough
on both sides of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger really hasn't missed any putts this week, or very, very
few,'' said Tom Watson, who won the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach in
1982. ``That's the key, but to get into position where he's making
those 5-footers, 8-footers, 10-footers like he did at No. 6, he's
had to get there from some pretty awkward lies. And he's been doing
a great job of that all week.''
</P>
<P>
   He was doing it again just a few holes later, hacking out of
thick fairway rough to within a foot of the flagstick on No. 13 to
set up his third birdie in four holes - following 15- and 18-foot
birdie putts on 10 and 12, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But marvelous as he was dodging disaster, Woods was more
tactician than troubleshooter Sunday, as he demonstrated on the
573-yard, par-5 14th -laying up and than lobbing a wedge shot to
within eight feet for a birdie that got him to 4 under for the back
nine and the round.
</P>
<P>
   One hole later, he was combination mowing and putting machine -
hacking out of the hay again to barely reaching the green from
right-side fairway rough and then nearly draining a 30-foot birdie
putt that stopped on the lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He meant business,'' I'll tell you that,'' said Els. ``He was
never in any trouble - any kind of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   What looked like trouble for Woods on 16 and 17 merely produced
pars, first on a chip from out of the rough and following 15-foot
putt, then a bunker shot that he almost holed.
</P>
<P>
   With a 15-stroke lead on the 18th tee, Woods further
demonstrated his focus, eschewing trying to reach the par-5 green
in two for a shot at the outright tournament record. Instead, he
hit 4-iron off the tee, laid up on his second shot and wedged onto
the green for a two-putt par.
</P>
<P>
   All he wanted was the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible feeling to be our nation's Open champion,''
Woods said. ``It's just something that we all, as kids who play
golf and who want to aspire to become professionals, this is what
we look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what does Woods look forward to next?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
