<HEADER>
A7943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-GENTLEMEN-REVIEW-N     06-18 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GENTLEMEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LEAGUE OF GENTLEMEN': PYTHONESQUE, BUT THE VULGARITY IS OUT OF
CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By NEIL GENZLINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can someone please explain how the British can get so worked up
about genetically altered food yet be perfectly at home with
genetically altered comedy? Because ``The League of Gentlemen,''
the series from the BBC that makes its U.S. debut Monday night on
Comedy Central, is nothing if not genetically altered. It is comedy
far more outlandish, far more deranged than nature ever intended
comedy to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The League of Gentlemen,'' which first appeared on the BBC in
1999, is an amalgam of sketches, sight gags, running jokes and plot
lines that almost defies description. Attempting it is like trying
to convey to someone living in two dimensions what
three-dimensional existence feels like. Two dimensions in this case
is ``Frasier,'' ``Friends'' and every other mainstream U.S. comedy.
Remove the taste barriers and the strictures of the sitcom format _
the tidy half-hour plots, the setup-zinger-laugh writing _ and
you're in the realm of ``The League of Gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, puts you in very strange, often offensive
territory. More specifically, it puts you in Royston Vasey, a
fictional town in northern England where pets die strange deaths
and humans who make the mistake of entering a certain local shop
are rarely seen again. Mark Gatiss, Steve Pemberton, Reece
Shearsmith and Jeremy Dyson created the show, and the first three
men play dozens of characters in it, often in dresses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sort of mock-horror soap opera, and, like a soap opera,
it may be difficult for viewers who miss the first episode to
figure out what's going on. Not that there is anything so normal as
a continuous plot; sometimes the sketches and scenes are related to
one another, sometimes they're not. The problem for the
late-arriving viewer will be more in the nature of getting a bead
on the assorted wackos. Someone tuning in ``Seinfeld'' for the
first time might pigeonhole George, Jerry, Elaine and Kramer with
rough accuracy after about 15 minutes. But in Royston Vasey there
are scores of characters, and all of them make Kramer look
downright normal.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of U.S. viewers won't get any of this. And plenty will
find it in very bad taste. There is bathroom humor, animal abuse
humor, humor at the expense of the homeless and the mentally
impaired. And those bothered by the sight of a woman (played by a
man) nursing a pig _ yes, that's right; nursing a pig _ need not
apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strangers you would bring would not understand us, our
customs, our local ways,'' the woman's husband tells two
unfortunate highway construction workers during this scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I'll say,'' a segment of the United States will respond.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The League of Gentleen'' is not frat house humor, or even
``South Park.'' The show is regularly compared to Monty Python, and
it has a Pythonesque intelligence running through it, even if the
vulgarity does sometimes get out of control.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, once the shock of the material has worn off, in the
end, what impresses about ``The League of Gentlemen'' is that the
characters _ more than 60 of them, the publicity packet claims _
are distinct, vivid, each crazy or appalling in his or her own way.
The contrast with the U.S. prime-time sitcom, with its
interchangeable collection of self-absorbed teen-agers and young
professionals, is dismaying.
</P>
<P>
   Even if much of what goes on in Royston Vasey would never make
network television, there's a lesson here for America's moribund
sitcom universe. Not all humor emanates from Cosby-type families;
not all casts must be six characters or fewer; not all comedic
scripts have to be written in two concurrent plot lines that
intersect and resolve at the end of the half-hour. There is, as Rod
Serling taught us, another dimension.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE LEAGUE OF GENTLEMEN'
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central, Monday at 10:30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by Jeremy Dyson, Mark Gattis, Steve Pemberton and Reece
Shearsmith; performed by Gattis, Pemberton and Shearsmith; produced
by Sarah Smith and Jemma Rodgers; directed by Steve Bendelack; Jon
Plowman, executive producer. Produced by BBC Worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
