<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SMOKE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     06-18 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN ARENA, SHATTERING STEREOTYPES OF RAP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ A giant skull with red lasers shooting out of
its eyes slowly descended from the top of the stage until it
hovered over the audience of 20,000 people at Arrowhead Pond here
on Friday night. Its bone-white teeth clattered open and shut, as
an evil laugh reverberated through the arena. Then flash pots
exploded, the sounds of a thunderstorm pealed through the air and _
who emerged onstage? Was it Metallica? Iron Maiden? No, it was Dr.
Dre and Snoop Doggy Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   The era of arena rap is upon us. Last week what may be the
slickest, largest-scale, most professional and most punctual rap
tour to date kicked off in California. Full of spectacular light
displays, elaborate sets and expensive short films, it had all the
pomp and eye candy of a Pink Floyd concert. Billed as the Up in
Smoke tour, it featured, besides Dr. Dre and Snoop, Ice Cube,
Eminem and an extremely brief reunion by NWA, the pioneering
gangsta rap band that included Dre and Cube.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle was a far cry from typical hip-hop shows, at which
performers often appear onstage hours late and then proceed to
spend more time giving instructions to their DJs than actually
rapping. Also weaved into the show were Xzibit, Warren G., Nate
Dogg, Kurupt, Tha Eastsidaz and the Westside Connection. (The tour
comes to the Continental Arena in East Rutherford, N.J., on July
15.)
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour show was a slap in the face to hip-hop detractors.
For one, it let the air out of the notion that because hip-hop is a
studio medium, it doesn't translate onto the stage unless the act
includes a live band. None of the headliners on this tour had live
instruments or even dancers. They just used DJs, combined with
strong performances and lavish production, which was enough to keep
the audience riveted and on its feet for the entire show. In the
case of Dre and Snoop, this meant a 90-minute set crammed with hits
stretching back to the late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The tour also blew away the notion that the hip-hop audience is
fickle, and that careers are impossible to sustain. Most current
rock stars would love to have the longevity of Dr. Dre and Ice
Cube, who began putting West Coast hip-hop on the map with NWA in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   In fact Dr. Dre's resurrection has been one of the most
impressive in contemporary music. In 1996 his career ground to a
halt when he left the violence-torn Death Row label he helped
start, repudiated the gangsta lifestyle in favor of positive
messages and started his own record company, Aftermath. But last
year he came back with his negativity guns blazing, putting out one
strong single after another, chewing out his fans for abandoning
him while he was in the lab inventing hot new gangsta beats for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Radio at the time had seemingly surpassed Dre's laid-back,
driving West Coast sound in favor of more minimal, sophisticated
and rhythmically adventurous beats. But Dre turned back the clock,
and now, on the West Coast at least, his music dominates urban
radio, through his own singles and his collaborations with Eminem,
Snoop and the other members of NWA.
</P>
<P>
   A short film shown before his performance glorified all the
gangsta cliches of luxury living and merciless killing that just
won't go out of style. Onstage these headliners were a perfect
team: Ice Cube was a masterful performer, Snoop had a winning
persona, Eminem held his own as a dizzying rhymer, and Dr. Dre just
stood there, proudly representing his beats.
</P>
<P>
   Between acts an MC kept the crowd entertained, at one point
leading a cheer rarely heard at a hip-hop show: ``All the
Caucasians in the house, make some noise!'' The audience was a mix
of ages and races, which seemed to clash only slightly, as when
groups of black teen-agers scoffed, ``Eminem fans'' at passing
white concertgoers.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday night at least the tour avoided another hip-hop
stereotype: that the shows are dangerous to attend. A spokesman for
the Anaheim police said there were only a few arrests, mostly for
disorderly conduct and drug possession, par for any arena show. The
performers, on the other hand, have not been so well behaved. On
the road for less than a week, two of them, Snoop Dogg and Nate
Dogg, have already run afoul of the law (for marijuana and domestic
violence charges, respectively).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000618.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7950 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-18 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THESE FINALS, VETERANS KNOW THE DRILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thirty-four-year-old Reggie Miller, keyed up for
his long-awaited NBA Finals debut, misses 15 of 16 shots for the
Indiana Pacers in the Lakers' series-opening victory.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six-year-old Ron Harper and 33-year-old Glen Rice, coolly
picking up slack for the injured Kobe Bryant, set their 2000
playoff highs with 21 points apiece in the Lakers' second win.
</P>
<P>
   Miller shows he's settling in, evoking memories of postseason
masterpieces past, scoring 33 as the Pacers break through.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Bryant puts on a fearless, brilliant shooting
performance in the pivotal overtime game.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant slips, Miller soars and outsmarts the Lakers again as the
Pacers stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   The ups and downs of the very (by pro basketball standards) old
and very (by anybody's standards) young have been a theme running
quietly through these NBA Finals. The series might be colored gray
and green as easily as gold and blue.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the talk has been about the first championship chase of
Bryant and 28-year-old Shaquille O'Neal of the Lakers. But just as
important is the work of the eight Pacers and six Lakers who are 30
and older, including three on each team who are 35 and up.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of each set of starters is 33. It's hard to
imagine another NBA Finals with as many old-timers. On the other
hand, it's hard to imagine an NBA Finals without them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many players coming out (of college early), the league
is getting a lot younger, of course. So you're going to get young
players in (key) positions at times,'' said Sam Perkins, the
soon-to-retire Pacers sub who sank a 3-pointer to force overtime on
his 39th birthday Wednesday. ``You may have one or two this year in
the finals because of their talent or the team they're on, but you
won't see a collection of 20-year-olds in any finals because they
don't have the experience and don't know what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, talk of an NBA generation gap was in vogue, as
the veteran core got down on the 20-year-old corps for failing to
respect the game or whatever it was they were supposed to be
respecting.
</P>
<P>
   That talk has died down. One theory is that the 1998-99
players-owners dispute taught the talent the value of sticking
together across generational lines.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that the young guys took the criticism to
heart, and another is that everybody learned there's more to gain
on the court by blending the brashness of youth and the measured
guile of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Where would Harper be without Bryant? Where would Bryant be
without Harper?
</P>
<P>
   Harper is the !ital!thirtysomething!off! who is acquitting
himself most surprisingly in the playoffs, carving paths to the
basket past younger, quicker defenders with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron came in (to the NBA in 1986 with Cleveland) as a very
offensive-minded player. It's maturity,'' assistant coach Jim
Cleamons said Sunday before the Lakers' practice on the eve of Game
6 in a series they lead 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young and a high flyer, you're driving and
attacking the basket. Now, look at how he gets to the basket
through knowledge and transition. He's probably doing more for his
team to help them win than when he was putting up high numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron's not going to beat you on speed anymore. So he's taking
his little cracks through the lane, or in transition, to get to the
basket. When we have the floor spaced, if they don't stop (him),
he's able to get to the basket. You think, 'Is he ever going to get
there?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys at the end of their careers !ital!should!off! understand
the game better. They may not be as talented physically, but
through maturity and wisdom and the amount of games they've played,
they know how to play. So it's wonderful to see them rewarded at
this point of their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the fourth quarter Friday in Indianapolis, with the
Lakers down by 19 but still thinking about a comeback, Miller went
up for a 3-point shot and flicked a foot at 25-year-old Derek
Fisher, cleverly drawing a foul that Fisher compounded with a
technical foul for arguing. Miller's four free throws were the
final nails in the Pacers' 120-87 victory. It was an example of old
taking advantage of young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience pays off,'' said A.C. Green, at 36 the senior
Laker. ``That's really the moral of the story. You want to have
people who have been there before.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a difference between the veterans, team to team. Being in
the league for 10 years doesn't necessarily mean they've been
!ital!here!off!, in the Finals pressure cooker.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' veterans are notable for their NBA Finals
experience. Green (with the Lakers in the '80s), Harper (Chicago),
John Salley (Detroit and Chicago) and Robert Horry (Houston) have
won championships. The Pacers' veterans are stigmatized by their
postseason failures. The only Pacer with a championship ring is Zan
Tabak, the just-turned-30-year-old from Croatia who averaged 0.8
points a playoff game for Houston in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Six Pacers players are going into free-agent summers, and coach
Larry Bird has expressed his intention to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this team, it creates a little bit more of a sense of
urgency, because you don't know what the personnel will be next
year,'' said Austin Croshere, one of the potential free agents even
though, at 25, he's one of the younger Pacers. ``It's kind of 'Make
the most of the moment, because you don't know if this
opportunity's going to be here again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, for all intents and purposes, the last run.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Pacers veterans have five NBA Finals tip-offs under
their experience belt, so the age-vs.-experience battle is
anybody's game. Anyway, assuming you have a little gray in your
temples, you'll still have something to cheer about if it comes
down to a Miller-Bryant shootout and the Lakers lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
